1
00:00:55,922 --> 00:00:57,764
- Susan! Sorry.
- Oh.

2
00:00:57,848 --> 00:01:00,443
So sorry, have you got the turkey now?

3
00:01:00,527 --> 00:01:02,094
Taxi!

4
00:01:42,569 --> 00:01:44,513
Oh.

5
00:01:44,597 --> 00:01:46,182
You all right?

6
00:01:46,266 --> 00:01:48,015
Never mind.

7
00:02:00,383 --> 00:02:05,976
♪ I'll see you again ♪

8
00:02:06,060 --> 00:02:13,916
♪ Whenever spring breaks through again ♪

9
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:20,151
♪ Time may lie heavy between ♪

10
00:02:20,235 --> 00:02:23,726
♪ But what has been ♪

11
00:02:23,810 --> 00:02:28,390
♪ Is past forgetting ♪

12
00:02:28,474 --> 00:02:34,234
♪ This sweet memory ♪

13
00:02:34,318 --> 00:02:41,845
♪ Across the years will come to me ♪

14
00:02:41,929 --> 00:02:46,113
♪ Though my world may go awry ♪

15
00:02:46,197 --> 00:02:50,512
♪ In my heart will ever lie ♪

16
00:02:50,596 --> 00:02:54,887
♪ Just the echo of a sigh ♪

17
00:02:54,971 --> 00:02:57,955
♪ Goodbye ♪

18
00:03:01,177 --> 00:03:07,103
♪ I will see you again ♪

19
00:03:07,187 --> 00:03:14,911
♪ Whenever spring breaks through again ♪

20
00:03:14,995 --> 00:03:18,708
♪ Though my world has gone awry ♪

21
00:03:18,792 --> 00:03:23,150
♪ Though the years my tears may dry ♪

22
00:03:23,234 --> 00:03:27,590
♪ I shall love you till I die ♪

23
00:03:27,674 --> 00:03:35,422
♪ Goodbye. ♪

24
00:03:35,506 --> 00:03:37,458
What a melody.

25
00:03:37,542 --> 00:03:40,494
My God, what a melody.

26
00:04:09,546 --> 00:04:10,997
It's the door at the end
of the corridor, sir.

27
00:04:11,081 --> 00:04:12,431
- Ah.
- Betty?

28
00:04:12,515 --> 00:04:14,695
- What?
- Can I borrow some lippy?

29
00:04:14,779 --> 00:04:16,834
Again? You're terrible.

30
00:04:16,918 --> 00:04:19,205
- Bring it back.
- You never gave me mine back last time.

31
00:04:19,289 --> 00:04:21,037
Excuse me, can I...

32
00:04:21,121 --> 00:04:22,807
Nice show tonight, ladies and gentlemen.

33
00:04:22,891 --> 00:04:24,375
- Mmm.
- Don't forget, it's the matinee tomorrow.

34
00:04:24,459 --> 00:04:26,059
The half will be at five to 2:00.

35
00:04:28,425 --> 00:04:29,545
Ah.

36
00:04:29,629 --> 00:04:30,844
Hello, Barrow.
You got our note?

37
00:04:30,928 --> 00:04:32,348
I-I hope we're not being a nuisance.

38
00:04:32,432 --> 00:04:33,723
Not at all, my lord.

39
00:04:33,807 --> 00:04:35,051
Mr. Dexter.

40
00:04:35,135 --> 00:04:36,156
Hello.

41
00:04:36,240 --> 00:04:37,960
How about a glass of champagne?

42
00:04:38,044 --> 00:04:39,159
You mustn't let us hold you up.

43
00:04:39,243 --> 00:04:40,788
It's so thrilling to be backstage.

44
00:04:40,872 --> 00:04:43,165
<i>Bitter Sweet</i> seems to be a big hit.

45
00:04:43,249 --> 00:04:45,497
We're living in the age of Noël Coward.

46
00:04:45,581 --> 00:04:47,562
Exactly.
Although I don't suppose Noël

47
00:04:47,646 --> 00:04:48,905
would put it quite like that.

48
00:04:48,989 --> 00:04:50,303
How would I put it?

49
00:04:50,387 --> 00:04:52,001
- Oh.
- We were just saying

50
00:04:52,085 --> 00:04:54,672
how your star shines more
brightly with every new show.

51
00:04:54,756 --> 00:04:56,141
- Ah.
- Do you know Lord and Lady Grantham,

52
00:04:56,225 --> 00:04:58,013
Lord and Lady Hexham?

53
00:04:58,097 --> 00:04:59,975
- The show was marvelous.
- Yes.

54
00:05:00,059 --> 00:05:01,747
Although we're not
qualified to judge, of course.

55
00:05:01,831 --> 00:05:03,878
Everyone is qualified to say
something nice, Lady Grantham.

56
00:05:03,962 --> 00:05:06,581
Mr. Dexter's dresser used to work for us,

57
00:05:06,665 --> 00:05:08,191
so we thought we'd look in.

58
00:05:08,275 --> 00:05:09,585
Guy made that picture
at your house, didn't he?

59
00:05:09,669 --> 00:05:11,427
I so enjoyed it.

60
00:05:11,511 --> 00:05:13,492
I hope you'll return one day
to the scene of your triumph.

61
00:05:13,576 --> 00:05:15,522
Oh, we'd like that very much, milady.

62
00:05:19,852 --> 00:05:21,336
And we better run.

63
00:05:21,420 --> 00:05:23,239
We're dining at the new Ivy on West Street.

64
00:05:23,323 --> 00:05:25,666
My favorite haunt
if it weren't for the prices.

65
00:05:25,750 --> 00:05:27,010
The last time I dined there,

66
00:05:27,094 --> 00:05:28,175
I asked for the bill and a pistol.

67
00:05:28,259 --> 00:05:29,406
How much was it?

68
00:05:29,490 --> 00:05:31,243
Ten pounds for three of us.

69
00:05:31,327 --> 00:05:32,742
Ten pounds for three people?

70
00:05:32,826 --> 00:05:35,179
Well, I suppose we don't have to go there.

71
00:05:35,263 --> 00:05:36,548
Oh, yes, we do.

72
00:05:36,632 --> 00:05:38,382
We must get a wiggle on if we don't want

73
00:05:38,466 --> 00:05:40,286
- to lose our table.
- Yes.

74
00:05:40,370 --> 00:05:41,685
- Thank you.
- Bye-bye.
- Bye.

75
00:05:41,769 --> 00:05:42,849
- We loved it.
- Thank you.
- Ah. Thank you.

76
00:05:42,933 --> 00:05:44,558
- Milord.
- Goodbye.
- Thank you.

77
00:05:44,642 --> 00:05:46,296
The stage door will be closing in 30 minutes.

78
00:05:46,380 --> 00:05:48,258
They're very hearty
with each other, aren't they?

79
00:05:48,342 --> 00:05:49,624
Dexter and Barrow?

80
00:05:49,708 --> 00:05:51,526
They must travel a lot together.

81
00:05:51,610 --> 00:05:53,275
That's right, of course.

82
00:05:56,650 --> 00:05:58,031
How long did you work for them?

83
00:05:58,115 --> 00:06:00,205
- Quite a few years.
- And were you happy?

84
00:06:00,289 --> 00:06:02,142
Not as happy as I am now.

85
00:06:08,968 --> 00:06:10,864
What a lovely night.

86
00:06:12,030 --> 00:06:14,319
The London season's always good fun.

87
00:06:14,403 --> 00:06:16,451
Then back we go to Downton.

88
00:06:22,645 --> 00:06:24,000
Oh, they're still up?

89
00:06:24,084 --> 00:06:25,492
MRS. HUGHES:
Oh. There you are.

90
00:06:25,576 --> 00:06:26,968
How was it?

91
00:06:27,052 --> 00:06:28,236
It was a lovely night.

92
00:06:28,320 --> 00:06:29,501
So, we walked back along Piccadilly,

93
00:06:29,585 --> 00:06:31,298
then down through the Green Park.

94
00:06:31,382 --> 00:06:33,639
Oh, we saw what they've built
to replace Devonshire House.

95
00:06:33,723 --> 00:06:36,241
You mustn't do too much,
not in your condition.

96
00:06:36,325 --> 00:06:38,444
I feel fine. Honestly.

97
00:06:38,528 --> 00:06:40,128
It was good to be out in the air.

98
00:06:40,158 --> 00:06:42,015
It looks as if the new Grosvenor House Hotel

99
00:06:42,099 --> 00:06:43,445
is open at last.

100
00:06:43,529 --> 00:06:44,781
I'm impressed.

101
00:06:44,865 --> 00:06:46,812
It's sad to think of London being stripped

102
00:06:46,896 --> 00:06:48,257
of its private palaces.

103
00:06:48,341 --> 00:06:50,152
MRS. HUGHES:
It had to happen, Charlie.

104
00:06:50,236 --> 00:06:52,795
What with these new taxes,
no one can afford them anymore.

105
00:06:54,747 --> 00:06:56,998
MRS. PATMORE: Well, who could
that be at this time of night?

106
00:06:57,082 --> 00:06:58,498
No, no, no. I'll get it.

107
00:06:58,582 --> 00:07:00,764
Oh, tell us more about
Mr. Dexter's show.

108
00:07:00,848 --> 00:07:02,372
There was one song which keeps

109
00:07:02,456 --> 00:07:04,199
- going round in my head.
- Sir, do you have

110
00:07:04,283 --> 00:07:05,271
- something to say about Lady Mary?
- Certainly not.

111
00:07:05,355 --> 00:07:07,767
♪ I'll see you again... ♪

112
00:07:07,851 --> 00:07:09,936
Thank you, Miss Baxter.

113
00:07:10,020 --> 00:07:11,440
Hey, don't let her put you off.

114
00:07:11,524 --> 00:07:13,175
Oh, who was that?

115
00:07:13,259 --> 00:07:16,017
Some fool asking impertinent
questions about the family.

116
00:07:16,101 --> 00:07:17,518
I shut the door on him.

117
00:07:17,602 --> 00:07:20,050
It is odd to think tomorrow is your last day.

118
00:07:20,134 --> 00:07:22,684
What will we do when you're
no longer here to protect us?

119
00:07:22,768 --> 00:07:24,788
Andrew will-- I should say

120
00:07:24,872 --> 00:07:27,287
Mr. Parker will look after you instead.

121
00:07:27,371 --> 00:07:29,921
How do you feel about
your imminent promotion, Andy?

122
00:07:29,939 --> 00:07:31,134
I feel ready.

123
00:07:31,218 --> 00:07:33,727
I've served my years before the mast.

124
00:07:33,811 --> 00:07:35,146
I only hope you're right.

125
00:07:37,483 --> 00:07:39,307
Charlie...

126
00:07:39,391 --> 00:07:42,036
Was that about Lady Mary?

127
00:07:42,120 --> 00:07:44,711
Oh, there's bound to be some interest.

128
00:07:44,795 --> 00:07:47,474
After our little exchange,
he won't trouble us again.

129
00:07:47,558 --> 00:07:49,010
Hmm.

130
00:07:51,396 --> 00:07:55,254
Lord knows what I'd have worn
tonight if it wasn't ready.

131
00:07:55,338 --> 00:07:57,086
You will be a sensation.

132
00:07:57,170 --> 00:07:58,919
Did I hear that one
of the Petersfields' daughters

133
00:07:59,003 --> 00:08:00,603
- is engaged?
- Gwendolen.

134
00:08:00,641 --> 00:08:02,095
They've just announced it.

135
00:08:02,179 --> 00:08:03,524
Someone nice?

136
00:08:03,608 --> 00:08:04,867
Lord Belsay.

137
00:08:04,951 --> 00:08:06,469
Very suitable.

138
00:08:06,553 --> 00:08:08,734
♪ London Pride has been handed down to us ♪

139
00:08:08,818 --> 00:08:12,869
♪ London Pride is a flower that's free ♪

140
00:08:12,953 --> 00:08:15,501
♪ Whoa, Liza, see the coster barrows ♪

141
00:08:15,585 --> 00:08:18,875
♪ The vegetable marrows
and the fruit piled high ♪

142
00:08:18,959 --> 00:08:21,681
♪ Oh, Liza, little London sparrows ♪

143
00:08:21,765 --> 00:08:23,250
- Oh, Catherine.
- ♪ Covent Garden Market ♪

144
00:08:23,334 --> 00:08:26,521
♪ Where the costers cry ♪

145
00:08:26,605 --> 00:08:29,284
♪ Cockney feet mark the beat of history ♪

146
00:08:29,368 --> 00:08:32,691
♪ Every street pins a memory down ♪ - ♪

147
00:08:32,775 --> 00:08:36,298
♪ Nothing ever can quite replace ♪

148
00:08:36,382 --> 00:08:41,100
♪ The grace of London Town. ♪

149
00:08:42,720 --> 00:08:45,971
You are good to stay in London
for Uncle Harold.

150
00:08:46,055 --> 00:08:49,774
Do you think he's finally made
sense of Grandmama's estate?

151
00:08:49,858 --> 00:08:52,746
It seems unfair that both Papa and Mama

152
00:08:52,830 --> 00:08:55,582
should lose their mothers
in such quick succession.

153
00:08:55,666 --> 00:08:57,766
- At least Papa was there for Granny.
- Hmm.

154
00:08:57,798 --> 00:08:59,718
It's been much harder for Mama.

155
00:08:59,802 --> 00:09:02,024
To be the grieving and dutiful daughter

156
00:09:02,108 --> 00:09:03,791
from across the ocean.

157
00:09:03,875 --> 00:09:06,427
All the more reason to hope
Harold has settled things.

158
00:09:06,511 --> 00:09:08,211
We've already spent half the money.

159
00:09:08,247 --> 00:09:09,496
That dress won't have helped.

160
00:09:11,583 --> 00:09:14,334
- Hello, Mary. Edith.
- Mrs. Vanneck.

161
00:09:14,418 --> 00:09:16,231
- How are you?
- Very well.

162
00:09:16,315 --> 00:09:19,240
I saw your parents at
the new Lady Rosebery's party.

163
00:09:19,324 --> 00:09:21,670
As full of energy as ever.

164
00:09:21,754 --> 00:09:23,012
Yes, they're holding up.

165
00:09:23,096 --> 00:09:24,741
How are Henry and Bertie?

166
00:09:24,825 --> 00:09:26,941
We're all pretty good, I think.

167
00:09:27,025 --> 00:09:29,081
So, Henry's home from his travels?

168
00:09:29,165 --> 00:09:30,782
Uh, yes.

169
00:09:30,866 --> 00:09:32,783
- Yes, he is.
- I'm afraid we have to run,

170
00:09:32,867 --> 00:09:34,517
but we'll give them all your love.

171
00:09:34,566 --> 00:09:36,354
Oh.

172
00:09:36,438 --> 00:09:37,685
Thanks for that.

173
00:09:37,769 --> 00:09:39,105
Happy to help.

174
00:09:40,176 --> 00:09:41,458
Jump on.

175
00:09:48,848 --> 00:09:50,705
I don't mind admitting it.

176
00:09:50,789 --> 00:09:53,289
After tonight, I'll be ready
to go back to Downton.

177
00:09:53,292 --> 00:09:55,208
The London season's endless.

178
00:09:55,292 --> 00:09:56,510
I'm worn out.

179
00:09:56,594 --> 00:09:57,940
You enjoy the season.
You know it.

180
00:09:58,024 --> 00:10:00,041
I used to, but now the girls are out,

181
00:10:00,125 --> 00:10:01,925
I'm not sure
I see the point anymore.

182
00:10:01,960 --> 00:10:03,885
This has just been delivered.

183
00:10:03,969 --> 00:10:06,687
So nice of you all to stay on
for my cousin's bash tonight.

184
00:10:06,771 --> 00:10:08,684
An invitation to Petersfield House feels like

185
00:10:08,768 --> 00:10:09,985
quite a hot ticket.

186
00:10:10,069 --> 00:10:11,459
I'm glad they've held on to their HQ.

187
00:10:11,543 --> 00:10:13,894
- Not for much longer.
- Oh, no.

188
00:10:13,978 --> 00:10:17,191
The Petersfield ball has been
an institution all my life.

189
00:10:17,275 --> 00:10:19,194
You can't blame them for not wanting to run

190
00:10:19,278 --> 00:10:21,061
a fully staffed house the size of Selfridge's

191
00:10:21,145 --> 00:10:23,029
in order to give one party a year.

192
00:10:23,113 --> 00:10:25,316
I suppose not.

193
00:10:26,450 --> 00:10:28,337
It's been a while
since we've seen Mr. Levinson.

194
00:10:28,421 --> 00:10:32,314
He's been busy settling
my late grandmother's affairs.

195
00:10:32,398 --> 00:10:34,009
He and Mama are both executors,

196
00:10:34,093 --> 00:10:35,893
but with the estate being in America,

197
00:10:35,928 --> 00:10:37,710
it's really fallen to him.

198
00:10:37,794 --> 00:10:40,083
I'm sure he and Her Ladyship
can manage things between them.

199
00:10:40,167 --> 00:10:42,424
You must tell me when it's too much for you.

200
00:10:42,508 --> 00:10:44,258
I can always share Baxter with Mama

201
00:10:44,342 --> 00:10:45,925
until the baby's born.

202
00:10:46,009 --> 00:10:48,889
There's time yet, and anyway,
I've done it before.

203
00:10:48,973 --> 00:10:50,814
Right.

204
00:10:51,847 --> 00:10:53,751
I think that's everything, milady.

205
00:10:57,115 --> 00:10:59,035
Last day with Carson in charge.

206
00:10:59,119 --> 00:11:01,070
And Mrs. Patmore leaves in a few weeks.

207
00:11:01,154 --> 00:11:03,238
But I think Parker will do well enough,

208
00:11:03,322 --> 00:11:05,675
even if it will feel strange without Carson.

209
00:11:05,759 --> 00:11:07,207
Things change, milord,

210
00:11:07,291 --> 00:11:08,885
and somehow, we must change with them.

211
00:11:08,969 --> 00:11:10,543
Very true.

212
00:11:10,627 --> 00:11:12,214
Did you see they're pulling
down Dorchester House?

213
00:11:12,298 --> 00:11:15,284
We used to go there a lot
when the Reids had it.

214
00:11:15,368 --> 00:11:18,559
But plenty of families
are throwing in the towel.

215
00:11:18,643 --> 00:11:21,188
I hope Grantham House is in no danger.

216
00:11:21,272 --> 00:11:23,057
How long has it been in the family?

217
00:11:23,141 --> 00:11:26,358
Oh. We bought it in about 1760,

218
00:11:26,442 --> 00:11:29,305
and my grandfather rebuilt it in 1854.

219
00:11:29,389 --> 00:11:30,732
- Quite a time.
- You're right.

220
00:11:30,816 --> 00:11:32,704
Quite a time.

221
00:11:32,788 --> 00:11:35,111
And that means something to me.

222
00:11:35,195 --> 00:11:36,893
Would you tie this?

223
00:11:39,422 --> 00:11:41,145
Darling, how nice you look.

224
00:11:41,229 --> 00:11:43,080
But I wish you were coming home
with us tomorrow.

225
00:11:43,164 --> 00:11:45,514
Someone needs to be here
to welcome Uncle Harold

226
00:11:45,535 --> 00:11:47,449
when his ship gets in.

227
00:11:47,533 --> 00:11:50,115
I'll give him dinner and bring
him north for the weekend.

228
00:11:50,199 --> 00:11:51,958
The weekend?

229
00:11:52,042 --> 00:11:53,890
I'm glad Mama isn't alive
to hear you say that word.

230
00:11:55,238 --> 00:11:56,999
The car's outside, milord.

231
00:12:12,697 --> 00:12:15,117
Divorce in high places!

232
00:12:15,201 --> 00:12:16,416
Get your paper!

233
00:12:16,500 --> 00:12:17,650
Divorce in high places!

234
00:12:17,733 --> 00:12:19,083
Come on, read all about it!

235
00:12:19,133 --> 00:12:20,286
There you go, love.
Thank you so much.

236
00:12:34,587 --> 00:12:35,832
This way. This way, please.

237
00:12:35,916 --> 00:12:37,298
My lady, my lord, this way.

238
00:12:37,382 --> 00:12:39,382
You got a quote for the <i>Herald,</i> have you?

239
00:12:39,392 --> 00:12:41,373
Lady Mary, you look exquisite.

240
00:12:42,893 --> 00:12:45,305
Why do they all want a picture of Mary?

241
00:12:45,389 --> 00:12:47,348
Because she's so pretty, of course.

242
00:12:51,870 --> 00:12:54,182
Ah, it's Mr. Carson's last night in service.

243
00:12:54,266 --> 00:12:56,149
I couldn't let that pass unnoticed.

244
00:12:56,233 --> 00:12:58,728
Oh, you won't be far behind him,

245
00:12:58,812 --> 00:13:02,397
which I'm sure your husband
is very glad about.

246
00:13:02,481 --> 00:13:04,195
Mr. Mason has been very patient.

247
00:13:04,279 --> 00:13:06,735
You've seen the Crawleys
through some testing times,

248
00:13:06,819 --> 00:13:09,169
- Mr. Carson.
- Oh, they've been good to me, too.

249
00:13:09,220 --> 00:13:11,668
Not everyone would have taken
in a former song and dance man,

250
00:13:11,752 --> 00:13:12,902
not back then.

251
00:13:12,986 --> 00:13:14,269
You don't often talk about that.

252
00:13:14,353 --> 00:13:16,879
And he's not going to now.

253
00:13:16,963 --> 00:13:21,047
At the end of a career,
you look back more than you did

254
00:13:21,131 --> 00:13:23,343
and think about all the changes
you've witnessed.

255
00:13:23,427 --> 00:13:25,420
Shall we raise a glass to Mr. Carson?

256
00:13:25,504 --> 00:13:27,281
- Yes.
- I'm not going far.

257
00:13:27,365 --> 00:13:29,724
But we will miss seeing you each day.

258
00:13:29,808 --> 00:13:32,074
I would like to thank you,
Mr. Carson.

259
00:13:33,071 --> 00:13:34,521
You've taught me so much,

260
00:13:34,605 --> 00:13:36,559
and I hope one day
I'll be a worthy successor.

261
00:13:36,643 --> 00:13:37,849
Mm.

262
00:13:38,811 --> 00:13:40,401
Mr. Carson.

263
00:13:40,485 --> 00:13:41,930
Mr. Carson.

264
00:14:03,639 --> 00:14:05,559
Uh, uh, Lady Mary.

265
00:14:05,643 --> 00:14:07,121
Could I have a quick word?

266
00:14:07,205 --> 00:14:09,394
- Excuse me.
- Of course.

267
00:14:09,478 --> 00:14:10,594
Mama?

268
00:14:12,311 --> 00:14:13,897
What's going on?
Are you all right?

269
00:14:13,981 --> 00:14:15,868
Uh, I'm so sorry, but a...

270
00:14:15,952 --> 00:14:17,966
A rather tricky situation has arisen.

271
00:14:18,050 --> 00:14:19,540
Why? What's happened?

272
00:14:19,624 --> 00:14:22,136
Uh, my maid just told me...

273
00:14:22,220 --> 00:14:24,303
Your maid just told you what?

274
00:14:24,387 --> 00:14:27,446
That Lady Mary is divorced.

275
00:14:29,966 --> 00:14:32,650
She said it was in the evening paper.

276
00:14:32,734 --> 00:14:33,915
This is nonsense.

277
00:14:33,999 --> 00:14:35,653
It's not nonsense.

278
00:14:38,874 --> 00:14:41,092
I got the decree nisi today.

279
00:14:41,176 --> 00:14:42,695
Well, that explains the photographers.

280
00:14:42,779 --> 00:14:45,126
You mean it's true?

281
00:14:45,210 --> 00:14:46,969
I'm sorry to say that it is.

282
00:14:47,053 --> 00:14:48,795
Well, then
I'm afraid you can't stay.

283
00:14:48,879 --> 00:14:51,137
Prince and Princess Arthur
of Connaught are on their way,

284
00:14:51,221 --> 00:14:54,343
and the princess simply
cannot be in the same room

285
00:14:54,427 --> 00:14:56,503
as a divorced woman.

286
00:14:56,587 --> 00:14:59,948
I do apologize, but Lady Mary must go now.

287
00:15:00,032 --> 00:15:02,682
- Sarah, is this really...
- No, I really must insist.

288
00:15:02,759 --> 00:15:05,681
You're chucking my daughter
out of your house?

289
00:15:05,765 --> 00:15:08,824
Oh, most reluctantly, I assure
you, but their Royal Highnesses

290
00:15:08,908 --> 00:15:11,455
would be badly compromised
if anyone found out.

291
00:15:11,539 --> 00:15:13,220
I've never heard anything
so ridiculous in all my life.

292
00:15:13,304 --> 00:15:15,796
Papa, it's all right. I'll go.

293
00:15:15,880 --> 00:15:17,729
I'm very sorry,
Lady Petersfield.

294
00:15:17,813 --> 00:15:19,676
I shouldn't have come.

295
00:15:20,879 --> 00:15:22,304
Wait.

296
00:15:29,727 --> 00:15:31,380
It's going to be hard for her.

297
00:15:31,464 --> 00:15:33,473
Very hard, I'm afraid.

298
00:15:33,557 --> 00:15:35,157
The young crowd may be all right,

299
00:15:35,193 --> 00:15:37,217
but you have to remember,

300
00:15:37,301 --> 00:15:40,367
my mother wouldn't have
a divorced woman in the house.

301
00:15:42,569 --> 00:15:43,790
It's just shocking.

302
00:15:43,874 --> 00:15:45,054
I do thank you

303
00:15:45,138 --> 00:15:46,553
for your kind understanding.

304
00:15:46,637 --> 00:15:48,154
I've asked the footman to bring your coat.

305
00:15:48,238 --> 00:15:49,464
Ah, there he is.

306
00:15:49,548 --> 00:15:50,632
Ah, thank you.

307
00:15:50,716 --> 00:15:51,862
I am sorry.

308
00:15:51,946 --> 00:15:53,327
Well, so you keep saying.

309
00:15:53,411 --> 00:15:54,731
Your Royal Highnesses.

310
00:15:54,815 --> 00:15:56,535
Oh. Quickly.

311
00:15:56,619 --> 00:15:58,154
Hide, hide!

312
00:16:02,385 --> 00:16:04,644
Your Royal Highnesses.

313
00:16:04,728 --> 00:16:06,507
What a splendid evening

314
00:16:06,591 --> 00:16:08,544
you've laid on for us,
Lady Petersfield.

315
00:16:08,628 --> 00:16:12,479
Your presence is what lends
its splendor, ma'am.

316
00:16:12,563 --> 00:16:14,323
Let me take you up to the ballroom.

317
00:16:18,272 --> 00:16:19,428
What an enchanting

318
00:16:19,512 --> 00:16:20,660
little house this is.

319
00:16:20,744 --> 00:16:22,192
What an absurd woman.

320
00:16:22,276 --> 00:16:24,126
There's no need to sound so indignant.

321
00:16:24,147 --> 00:16:25,734
You knew Henry and I were getting a divorce.

322
00:16:25,818 --> 00:16:27,418
But not that it had come through.

323
00:16:27,486 --> 00:16:28,704
Well, it has.

324
00:16:28,788 --> 00:16:29,998
And you never thought to tell us?

325
00:16:30,082 --> 00:16:31,264
Why on earth not?

326
00:16:31,348 --> 00:16:33,008
Because I'm a fool.

327
00:16:33,092 --> 00:16:35,268
And I suppose I thought
I could have one last night

328
00:16:35,352 --> 00:16:36,776
before the sky fell in.

329
00:16:36,860 --> 00:16:38,407
Of course, it's all ludicrous.

330
00:16:38,491 --> 00:16:40,243
Ludicrous or not, it's time for me to leave,

331
00:16:40,327 --> 00:16:41,927
and with little fuss as possible.

332
00:16:41,964 --> 00:16:43,213
Then we're coming with you.

333
00:16:43,297 --> 00:16:44,777
Uh, don't try and talk me out of it.

334
00:16:44,861 --> 00:16:46,215
Papa, you know perfectly well you can't leave

335
00:16:46,299 --> 00:16:48,087
before the prince and princess.

336
00:16:48,171 --> 00:16:50,556
Go back up and come home when they've left.

337
00:16:50,640 --> 00:16:51,888
I mean it.

338
00:16:51,972 --> 00:16:53,120
What will you do?

339
00:16:53,204 --> 00:16:54,755
I'll take a taxi.

340
00:16:54,839 --> 00:16:57,840
If I can find one that
will carry a divorced woman.

341
00:17:10,058 --> 00:17:11,139
Lady Mary, one photo, please.

342
00:17:11,223 --> 00:17:12,977
Lady Mary, one photo!

343
00:17:13,061 --> 00:17:15,011
Lady Mary, a photograph, please!

344
00:17:20,038 --> 00:17:21,755
Is it true what they're saying?

345
00:17:21,839 --> 00:17:23,558
What's the reason for the split?

346
00:18:20,896 --> 00:18:22,849
It was stupid.

347
00:18:22,933 --> 00:18:24,544
I don't blame anyone but me.

348
00:18:24,628 --> 00:18:27,050
I bet His Lordship was furious.

349
00:18:27,134 --> 00:18:29,319
Yes, but it wasn't fair.

350
00:18:29,403 --> 00:18:32,050
Lady Petersfield did what she had to.

351
00:18:32,134 --> 00:18:35,025
I'm divorced and not wanted
in respectable company.

352
00:18:35,109 --> 00:18:36,631
Don't say such a thing.

353
00:18:36,715 --> 00:18:37,815
Why not, if it's true?

354
00:18:39,576 --> 00:18:42,318
What do the servants know?

355
00:18:44,219 --> 00:18:47,302
They knew it was coming, and...

356
00:18:47,386 --> 00:18:49,457
Tonight they know it's happened.

357
00:18:50,488 --> 00:18:51,838
It was in <i>The Evening News.</i>

358
00:18:52,795 --> 00:18:54,746
So I gather.

359
00:18:54,830 --> 00:18:56,010
Was it bad?

360
00:18:56,094 --> 00:18:57,234
No.

361
00:18:58,296 --> 00:18:59,481
No, not too bad.

362
00:18:59,565 --> 00:19:02,140
Just how Mr. Talbot's gone and...

363
00:19:03,239 --> 00:19:05,039
...You run Downton with His Lordship.

364
00:19:05,910 --> 00:19:08,212
Which is all true, I suppose.

365
00:19:10,477 --> 00:19:12,827
But now the other papers will pick it up.

366
00:19:12,911 --> 00:19:15,648
I'm sorry if the newspapers
made you unhappy, milady.

367
00:19:16,814 --> 00:19:19,113
The divorce has made me unhappy. -

368
00:19:20,850 --> 00:19:22,106
Mama, if you've left the party...

369
00:19:22,190 --> 00:19:23,338
The royals left before us.

370
00:19:23,422 --> 00:19:25,170
They went early, thank God.

371
00:19:25,254 --> 00:19:27,710
But I've decided I won't visit
anywhere you're not welcome.

372
00:19:27,794 --> 00:19:30,046
- Will that be all, milady?
- No. You can hear this.

373
00:19:30,130 --> 00:19:31,301
And sit down.

374
00:19:33,463 --> 00:19:35,517
Mama, I forbid it.

375
00:19:35,601 --> 00:19:37,753
Papa would be in a hopeless situation.

376
00:19:37,837 --> 00:19:39,953
You'd make the whole thing
much worse than it is.

377
00:19:40,037 --> 00:19:42,062
- But what can I do then?
- If you want to please me,

378
00:19:42,146 --> 00:19:43,423
you'll behave completely normally.

379
00:19:43,507 --> 00:19:44,957
- How?
- I don't know.

380
00:19:45,041 --> 00:19:47,694
Some friends will be happy
to break the rules.

381
00:19:47,778 --> 00:19:49,735
But the rest, you'll go without me.

382
00:19:49,819 --> 00:19:51,104
I couldn't.

383
00:19:51,188 --> 00:19:52,982
We'll just have to get used to it.

384
00:19:55,387 --> 00:19:56,537
Good night, my darling.

385
00:19:56,563 --> 00:19:58,152
Try and sleep.

386
00:20:06,962 --> 00:20:09,130
Well, now we know what I'm up against.

387
00:20:10,402 --> 00:20:13,089
I admire you, Lady Mary.

388
00:20:13,173 --> 00:20:14,641
You're very brave.

389
00:20:21,350 --> 00:20:23,232
- MRS. PATMORE: Good morning.
- Is it?

390
00:20:23,316 --> 00:20:24,684
I haven't slept a wink.

391
00:20:25,683 --> 00:20:27,535
We knew it was coming, Charlie.

392
00:20:27,619 --> 00:20:29,542
We've known as much for months.

393
00:20:29,626 --> 00:20:31,571
It'll change our lives, though,
now it's out in the open.

394
00:20:31,655 --> 00:20:33,825
How's Lady Mary taking it?

395
00:20:34,823 --> 00:20:36,813
She's not happy. I can say that.

396
00:20:36,897 --> 00:20:40,283
Well, I'm just glad the
old lady didn't live to see it.

397
00:20:40,367 --> 00:20:41,820
Oh, he forced her into it.

398
00:20:41,904 --> 00:20:43,655
Mr. Talbot,

399
00:20:43,739 --> 00:20:46,861
with his airs and graces and
his fast cars, I don't think.

400
00:20:46,945 --> 00:20:48,460
He pushed her and tricked her

401
00:20:48,544 --> 00:20:51,832
and brought scandal
on this once great family.

402
00:20:51,916 --> 00:20:53,364
We don't know everything.

403
00:20:53,448 --> 00:20:55,004
I know enough to recognize a bully

404
00:20:55,088 --> 00:20:57,637
and a feckless playboy when I see one.

405
00:21:01,191 --> 00:21:02,805
<i>I don't know, Mama.</i>

406
00:21:02,889 --> 00:21:05,374
The more he drove,
the more he toured the world,

407
00:21:05,458 --> 00:21:07,342
the less he cared about me.

408
00:21:07,426 --> 00:21:08,809
What else can I say?

409
00:21:08,893 --> 00:21:10,946
It still annoys me that Henry's girlfriend

410
00:21:11,030 --> 00:21:13,887
wasn't named in court
and he hired that tart instead.

411
00:21:13,971 --> 00:21:15,221
You know the rules.

412
00:21:15,305 --> 00:21:17,022
The husband names a paid trollop,

413
00:21:17,106 --> 00:21:18,523
not his real mistress.

414
00:21:18,607 --> 00:21:22,291
It's all very proper in its prim dishonesty.

415
00:21:22,375 --> 00:21:23,625
I still blame Mrs. Baron.

416
00:21:23,708 --> 00:21:25,466
She wasn't the problem.

417
00:21:25,550 --> 00:21:27,397
Henry had made up his mind,
and that's all there is to it.

418
00:21:27,481 --> 00:21:29,031
That is what's happened,

419
00:21:29,044 --> 00:21:30,696
and now we must just get on with it.

420
00:21:30,780 --> 00:21:33,141
Thus spake the Englishman.

421
00:21:33,225 --> 00:21:35,642
I am English, and I thank God for it.

422
00:21:35,726 --> 00:21:37,218
We know.

423
00:21:38,997 --> 00:21:41,057
Thank heaven we'll soon be home.

424
00:22:46,557 --> 00:22:49,410
Home sweet home.

425
00:22:56,205 --> 00:22:57,521
Have you missed me?

426
00:22:57,605 --> 00:22:59,971
Of course.

427
00:23:01,174 --> 00:23:02,492
Hello.

428
00:23:02,576 --> 00:23:03,991
Don't tell Nanny.

429
00:23:04,075 --> 00:23:05,795
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

430
00:23:05,879 --> 00:23:07,300
Where's Mrs. Patmore?
Have you left her behind?

431
00:23:07,384 --> 00:23:09,296
She stayed in London with Lady Mary.

432
00:23:09,380 --> 00:23:11,966
They'll be back on Friday, but
you'll have to cook until then.

433
00:23:12,050 --> 00:23:14,406
I don't mind.
It's not long till I take over.

434
00:23:14,490 --> 00:23:16,218
So this is the start of our time.

435
00:23:17,224 --> 00:23:19,180
Hello, Andy.

436
00:23:19,264 --> 00:23:21,190
Can we go and see
Mr. Mason's pigs?

437
00:23:22,165 --> 00:23:23,784
Good idea, Master George.

438
00:23:23,868 --> 00:23:25,514
After you.

439
00:23:25,598 --> 00:23:27,585
Is Mama back, too?

440
00:23:27,669 --> 00:23:29,956
Lady Mary will be here on Friday.

441
00:23:30,040 --> 00:23:31,457
"Man overboard!

442
00:23:31,541 --> 00:23:32,961
It startled everybody."

443
00:23:33,045 --> 00:23:34,461
I'm so sorry.

444
00:23:34,545 --> 00:23:36,628
It must have been terribly upsetting for her.

445
00:23:36,712 --> 00:23:38,761
How much does George know?

446
00:23:38,845 --> 00:23:40,268
- Oh.
- I'm not sure,

447
00:23:40,352 --> 00:23:42,467
but I think we should leave it to Mary

448
00:23:42,551 --> 00:23:44,038
to tell him.

449
00:23:44,122 --> 00:23:46,273
I keep thinking about Mary.

450
00:23:46,357 --> 00:23:48,503
Will she be treated that way up here?

451
00:23:48,587 --> 00:23:50,344
Not if I can help it.

452
00:23:50,428 --> 00:23:52,103
She won't find it easy being an outcast.

453
00:23:52,187 --> 00:23:53,776
She was always the belle of the ball.

454
00:23:53,860 --> 00:23:56,484
What's happened, uh, since we've been away?

455
00:23:56,568 --> 00:24:00,485
Mainly Isobel organizing the County Show.

456
00:24:00,569 --> 00:24:02,551
You don't mind they made her president?

457
00:24:02,635 --> 00:24:04,553
Are you joking? She's my savior.

458
00:24:04,637 --> 00:24:06,051
Mama enjoyed it.

459
00:24:06,135 --> 00:24:07,556
She always complained, of course.

460
00:24:07,640 --> 00:24:09,155
The hardest task

461
00:24:09,239 --> 00:24:11,196
is hauling Sir Hector Moreland
over to her side.

462
00:24:11,280 --> 00:24:12,395
Good luck with that.

463
00:24:12,479 --> 00:24:14,309
Mama couldn't stand him.

464
00:24:21,155 --> 00:24:22,902
Daisy!

465
00:24:22,986 --> 00:24:24,077
- Daisy.
- Hello, Mr. Molesley.

466
00:24:24,161 --> 00:24:25,360
What have you got there?

467
00:24:25,361 --> 00:24:27,180
Latest copy of <i>Picturegoer.</i>

468
00:24:27,264 --> 00:24:28,645
Has an article on my new film.

469
00:24:28,729 --> 00:24:30,016
I bought some copies for the house.

470
00:24:30,100 --> 00:24:31,484
How exciting.

471
00:24:31,568 --> 00:24:33,919
But it's-it's quite a responsibility, too.

472
00:24:34,003 --> 00:24:35,321
What is?

473
00:24:35,405 --> 00:24:37,673
Being famous in the film world.

474
00:24:38,669 --> 00:24:40,185
Always remember--

475
00:24:40,269 --> 00:24:43,162
An actor is nothing without a good script.

476
00:24:43,246 --> 00:24:44,597
If audiences like them,

477
00:24:44,681 --> 00:24:46,425
it's only because
of what we tell them to say.

478
00:24:46,509 --> 00:24:47,933
You don't think of that when
you're sitting in the stalls.

479
00:24:48,017 --> 00:24:49,101
Yeah.

480
00:24:49,185 --> 00:24:50,653
Well, cheerio.

481
00:24:52,592 --> 00:24:56,318
In many ways, the writers
are the real stars of cinema.

482
00:24:57,294 --> 00:24:59,206
What do you mean, a tribute?

483
00:24:59,290 --> 00:25:01,416
Will the late Lady Grantham
approve of our disrupting

484
00:25:01,500 --> 00:25:03,881
the established traditions
of the County Show?

485
00:25:03,965 --> 00:25:06,919
Perhaps we can establish
a new tradition in her honor.

486
00:25:07,003 --> 00:25:08,287
Hmm.

487
00:25:08,371 --> 00:25:10,426
I'll need to be convinced.

488
00:25:10,510 --> 00:25:12,454
Here are the entrants
in the farming categories.

489
00:25:12,538 --> 00:25:13,855
They're confirmed.

490
00:25:13,939 --> 00:25:15,120
Thank you.
That will be very helpful.

491
00:25:15,204 --> 00:25:17,614
And this is my list of prize-givers.

492
00:25:18,647 --> 00:25:20,568
Including the present Lady Grantham?

493
00:25:20,652 --> 00:25:22,534
She can say something nice
about her mother-in-law

494
00:25:22,618 --> 00:25:24,231
that will give you what you want.

495
00:25:24,315 --> 00:25:27,273
Even if I didn't find
old Lady Grantham very easy.

496
00:25:27,357 --> 00:25:29,824
She could be so sentimental.

497
00:25:30,722 --> 00:25:32,271
Violet sentimental?

498
00:25:32,355 --> 00:25:35,275
She wanted children's prizes for everything.

499
00:25:35,359 --> 00:25:37,151
And since she was president
and I was only chairman,

500
00:25:37,235 --> 00:25:38,950
there wasn't much I could do.

501
00:25:39,034 --> 00:25:41,485
Thankfully, I put a stop to
all that the year before last.

502
00:25:41,569 --> 00:25:42,884
Well, I hope it won't annoy you,

503
00:25:42,968 --> 00:25:45,760
but I do have some ideas of my own.

504
00:25:45,844 --> 00:25:47,260
Really?

505
00:25:47,344 --> 00:25:48,926
If you'll take my advice, I...

506
00:25:49,010 --> 00:25:51,510
I shall be so grateful
for your advice, Sir Hector.

507
00:25:52,710 --> 00:25:54,231
When I ask for it.

508
00:26:03,227 --> 00:26:04,518
Uncle Harold.

509
00:26:06,230 --> 00:26:07,576
Oh.

510
00:26:07,660 --> 00:26:09,077
Do my eyes deceive me,

511
00:26:09,161 --> 00:26:12,846
or is this vision the great Lady Mary Talbot?

512
00:26:12,930 --> 00:26:14,256
I'm so pleased to see you.

513
00:26:14,340 --> 00:26:16,357
- Yeah.
- We are eager for your news.

514
00:26:16,441 --> 00:26:17,783
- Well...
- Please introduce us,

515
00:26:17,867 --> 00:26:18,819
- Harold.
- Oh.

516
00:26:18,903 --> 00:26:20,660
May I present Gus Sambrook.

517
00:26:20,744 --> 00:26:23,164
Oh. Have you come to see
my uncle, Mr. Sambrook?

518
00:26:23,248 --> 00:26:24,962
I-I've come with your uncle.

519
00:26:25,046 --> 00:26:27,035
- Didn't you warn them, Harold?
- Well, I meant to.

520
00:26:27,119 --> 00:26:28,092
I must have forgotten.

521
00:26:28,176 --> 00:26:29,166
But is the house not big enough?

522
00:26:29,250 --> 00:26:30,304
Oh.

523
00:26:30,388 --> 00:26:31,836
You mean you want to stay here?

524
00:26:31,920 --> 00:26:32,931
Is that a terrible nuisance?

525
00:26:33,015 --> 00:26:35,167
- No.
- Thank you.

526
00:26:35,251 --> 00:26:37,540
I went to make some old-fashioneds.

527
00:26:37,624 --> 00:26:38,674
There's one for you.

528
00:26:38,758 --> 00:26:40,157
You should've rung the bell.

529
00:26:40,158 --> 00:26:42,350
I did, but no one knew how to make them.

530
00:26:42,434 --> 00:26:44,009
Mr. Sambrook will be staying with us.

531
00:26:44,093 --> 00:26:46,044
Mr. Levinson said, milady.

532
00:26:46,128 --> 00:26:47,317
I've put him in the Bird Room.

533
00:26:47,401 --> 00:26:48,387
Very good.

534
00:26:48,471 --> 00:26:49,719
Gus wasn't sure he could come

535
00:26:49,803 --> 00:26:51,059
until just before the boat sailed.

536
00:26:51,143 --> 00:26:52,787
And why did you come?

537
00:26:52,871 --> 00:26:54,187
Oh, he knows all about business.

538
00:26:54,271 --> 00:26:55,694
He can help me explain things to Cora.

539
00:26:55,778 --> 00:26:57,666
Well, it's a long way to travel for that.

540
00:26:57,750 --> 00:27:00,860
I've also got a horse running
in the Gold Cup at Ascot.

541
00:27:00,944 --> 00:27:02,202
Ooh. This is very strong.

542
00:27:02,286 --> 00:27:03,670
You know, I should run.

543
00:27:03,754 --> 00:27:05,199
I'm having dinner at the Savoy, and I'm late.

544
00:27:05,283 --> 00:27:06,870
Uh, I suppose the night
watchman will let me in?

545
00:27:06,954 --> 00:27:08,869
The night watchman is a thing of the past.

546
00:27:08,953 --> 00:27:10,176
But I've got a key for you.

547
00:27:10,260 --> 00:27:11,310
I'll see you out.

548
00:27:13,329 --> 00:27:14,477
Here you are.

549
00:27:14,561 --> 00:27:16,083
So let me guess--

550
00:27:16,167 --> 00:27:17,646
Robert is furious

551
00:27:17,730 --> 00:27:19,419
and Cora's sympathetic.

552
00:27:19,503 --> 00:27:22,057
Papa's miserable as much as angry.

553
00:27:22,141 --> 00:27:23,691
Now, Cora's a Yank.

554
00:27:23,775 --> 00:27:25,690
She knows society can learn
to live with divorce.

555
00:27:25,774 --> 00:27:27,920
It'll be true here before too long.

556
00:27:28,004 --> 00:27:29,527
But it's not true yet.

557
00:27:29,611 --> 00:27:32,393
Still, Downton keeps me busy.

558
00:27:32,477 --> 00:27:35,337
- What are you up to there?
- Mainly renovating the cottages

559
00:27:35,421 --> 00:27:37,771
and doing up the old smoking room.

560
00:27:37,855 --> 00:27:39,868
I thought a music room
would be a wonderful memorial

561
00:27:39,952 --> 00:27:41,670
- for both my grandmothers.
- Mm.

562
00:27:41,754 --> 00:27:43,404
That's a nice idea.

563
00:27:43,488 --> 00:27:45,710
Even if my mother was more
Gershwin than Rachmaninoff.

564
00:27:45,794 --> 00:27:47,105
It's a lot to get done,

565
00:27:47,189 --> 00:27:48,281
but that's where you come in.

566
00:27:48,365 --> 00:27:50,242
I really got to go.

567
00:27:50,326 --> 00:27:52,286
- Enjoy your dinner.
- Good night.

568
00:27:52,370 --> 00:27:54,246
Good night.

569
00:27:57,672 --> 00:27:59,260
Can I do anything to help?

570
00:27:59,344 --> 00:28:00,920
Everything's under control.

571
00:28:01,004 --> 00:28:02,421
And I've enjoyed myself.

572
00:28:02,505 --> 00:28:04,697
It's been a while
since I cooked for the family,

573
00:28:04,781 --> 00:28:06,795
and that was with Mrs. Patmore in charge.

574
00:28:06,879 --> 00:28:08,093
You'd better get used to it.

575
00:28:08,177 --> 00:28:09,932
I think they'll be pleased.

576
00:28:10,016 --> 00:28:12,272
- I'm sure we will.
- Oh. Lady Merton.

577
00:28:12,356 --> 00:28:13,868
What can we do for you?

578
00:28:13,952 --> 00:28:16,307
It's Daisy I've come to see.

579
00:28:16,391 --> 00:28:17,538
Me, milady?

580
00:28:17,622 --> 00:28:18,808
Yes.

581
00:28:18,892 --> 00:28:20,207
It's a straightforward request,

582
00:28:20,291 --> 00:28:21,643
but it will require some of your time.

583
00:28:21,727 --> 00:28:23,550
As you may know,

584
00:28:23,634 --> 00:28:25,380
every president of the County Show

585
00:28:25,464 --> 00:28:28,464
is supported by a committee,
and I want you to be a member.

586
00:28:29,701 --> 00:28:30,984
But why me?

587
00:28:31,068 --> 00:28:32,251
The show has always been run

588
00:28:32,335 --> 00:28:34,253
by a rather narrow group of people.

589
00:28:34,337 --> 00:28:36,598
I want to bring it more up-to-date,

590
00:28:36,682 --> 00:28:38,627
and I would value some fresh eyes to help me.

591
00:28:38,711 --> 00:28:40,092
Mm, a wise choice.

592
00:28:40,176 --> 00:28:41,730
I-If I may say so, milady.

593
00:28:41,814 --> 00:28:42,895
Please,

594
00:28:42,979 --> 00:28:45,401
do think about it.

595
00:28:45,485 --> 00:28:46,856
She will.

596
00:28:48,760 --> 00:28:50,475
You've paid her a great compliment,

597
00:28:50,559 --> 00:28:52,257
and you won't regret it.

598
00:28:54,432 --> 00:28:55,912
Not in a month of Sundays.

599
00:28:55,996 --> 00:28:58,516
Why would any of them listen to me?

600
00:28:58,600 --> 00:29:00,353
For your experience.

601
00:29:00,437 --> 00:29:02,656
Here and on the farm.

602
00:29:02,740 --> 00:29:05,518
But suppose Lady Merton disagrees with me.

603
00:29:05,602 --> 00:29:08,603
It's a good sign you
already know you'll be arguing.

604
00:29:11,779 --> 00:29:13,598
Why didn't you join Harold?

605
00:29:13,682 --> 00:29:15,282
So I could have dinner with you.

606
00:29:16,288 --> 00:29:17,938
Do you have many horses?

607
00:29:18,022 --> 00:29:21,341
A few, but I've never had one
in the Gold Cup before.

608
00:29:21,425 --> 00:29:23,171
We should get up a party.

609
00:29:23,255 --> 00:29:26,708
Although I suppose
Ascot's finished for me.

610
00:29:26,792 --> 00:29:28,442
If you can come,

611
00:29:28,526 --> 00:29:31,715
it would reward me for
my efforts on Harold's behalf.

612
00:29:31,799 --> 00:29:33,554
Can I ask about those efforts?

613
00:29:33,638 --> 00:29:35,855
Are you a sort of business advisor?

614
00:29:35,939 --> 00:29:38,359
I kept him out of some trouble a while back.

615
00:29:38,443 --> 00:29:40,051
But, really, we're friends.

616
00:29:40,135 --> 00:29:41,327
Can I top you up?

617
00:29:41,411 --> 00:29:42,363
Oh, I shouldn't.

618
00:29:42,447 --> 00:29:44,045
I've had more than enough.

619
00:29:46,416 --> 00:29:47,398
Oh, go on then.

620
00:30:11,670 --> 00:30:13,228
Hello.

621
00:30:13,312 --> 00:30:15,255
Oh.

622
00:30:15,339 --> 00:30:16,860
I didn't expect you back for hours.

623
00:30:16,944 --> 00:30:18,494
Her Ladyship sent me home early

624
00:30:18,507 --> 00:30:19,825
so we could have dinner together.

625
00:30:19,909 --> 00:30:21,532
Oh.

626
00:30:21,616 --> 00:30:23,499
How was London?

627
00:30:23,583 --> 00:30:24,667
Busy.

628
00:30:24,751 --> 00:30:26,065
For them, anyway.

629
00:30:26,149 --> 00:30:27,565
I've been busy, too.

630
00:30:27,649 --> 00:30:29,442
Working on the script of <i>Held to Ransom.</i>

631
00:30:29,526 --> 00:30:31,504
Are you pleased with it?

632
00:30:31,588 --> 00:30:33,544
It's taking a bit longer
than the last one, uh...

633
00:30:33,628 --> 00:30:35,082
You work too hard.

634
00:30:35,166 --> 00:30:36,117
Ease up.

635
00:30:36,201 --> 00:30:37,748
No, I can't.

636
00:30:37,832 --> 00:30:40,282
This is my moment.

637
00:30:40,366 --> 00:30:43,588
After years of being in the background, I...

638
00:30:43,672 --> 00:30:45,089
I'm changing lives.

639
00:30:45,173 --> 00:30:46,919
You were changing lives
when you were a teacher,

640
00:30:47,003 --> 00:30:48,422
weren't you?

641
00:30:48,506 --> 00:30:50,188
Yeah, you're right, but this, it's different.

642
00:30:50,272 --> 00:30:52,160
It's-it's...

643
00:30:52,244 --> 00:30:55,215
You know,
I-I've got to crack on then.

644
00:30:57,988 --> 00:31:00,220
Some of us went to see
Mr. Dexter's new play.

645
00:31:01,452 --> 00:31:03,876
Mr. Coward's new play,
I think you mean.

646
00:31:03,960 --> 00:31:06,738
How I would have loved to have seen that.

647
00:31:06,822 --> 00:31:10,979
To think Mr. Dexter relaunched
his career at Downton.

648
00:31:11,063 --> 00:31:12,362
I wonder if he'll be back.

649
00:31:12,363 --> 00:31:14,587
This place will be a desert for him,

650
00:31:14,671 --> 00:31:16,154
without anyone to talk to.

651
00:31:16,238 --> 00:31:18,909
- Well, he's got Mr. Barrow.
- Mr. Barrow's a servant.

652
00:31:19,905 --> 00:31:21,223
I'm a servant.

653
00:31:21,307 --> 00:31:22,926
And I've told you, you can give it up.

654
00:31:23,010 --> 00:31:25,245
And I've told you
I don't want to.

655
00:31:28,413 --> 00:31:32,000
Anyway, Mr. Barrow's not a servant anymore.

656
00:31:32,084 --> 00:31:33,598
Yeah, well, the fact remains,

657
00:31:33,682 --> 00:31:36,040
Mr. Dexter and I, we understand each other

658
00:31:36,124 --> 00:31:38,002
in a way that none of the rest of them can.

659
00:31:41,924 --> 00:31:43,979
Sounds like Isobel may regret
taking on the County Show.

660
00:31:44,063 --> 00:31:45,785
She's got her work cut out

661
00:31:45,869 --> 00:31:47,582
with that stuck-up fool
Moreland.

662
00:31:47,666 --> 00:31:50,366
She was shocked when I told her
about Lady Petersfield.

663
00:31:50,434 --> 00:31:51,855
I don't think she'd quite taken in

664
00:31:51,939 --> 00:31:53,820
what a divorce was gonna mean.

665
00:31:53,904 --> 00:31:56,456
If that's her reaction, imagine
what everyone else will think.

666
00:31:56,540 --> 00:31:58,690
Henry's decision has made Mary an outcast.

667
00:31:58,774 --> 00:32:02,468
- Somehow we will have to live with that.
- Mm.

668
00:32:02,552 --> 00:32:03,798
Isobel included.

669
00:32:03,882 --> 00:32:05,500
Thank you.

670
00:32:05,584 --> 00:32:07,342
I won't be surprised if people
start avoiding Downton

671
00:32:07,426 --> 00:32:09,009
in case Mary's here.

672
00:32:09,093 --> 00:32:10,838
Then we must challenge them
and change their minds,

673
00:32:10,922 --> 00:32:12,579
mustn't we?

674
00:32:12,663 --> 00:32:14,141
As a guest,

675
00:32:14,225 --> 00:32:16,044
can I offer you another drink?

676
00:32:16,128 --> 00:32:17,644
I really think we should stop.

677
00:32:17,728 --> 00:32:20,354
Nonsense. You said yourself
you'd lost your position.

678
00:32:20,438 --> 00:32:21,697
Let's celebrate.

679
00:32:24,436 --> 00:32:27,590
Is there any of that wine we had at dinner?

680
00:32:27,674 --> 00:32:29,024
Milady?

681
00:32:29,108 --> 00:32:30,557
Just bring some champagne.

682
00:32:30,641 --> 00:32:32,997
Carson would have left
a bottle in the icebox.

683
00:32:33,081 --> 00:32:35,216
- I thought you might like...
- Please.

684
00:32:38,251 --> 00:32:40,500
You're right.
I have lost my position.

685
00:32:40,584 --> 00:32:43,841
Have you ever been thrown out of a house?

686
00:32:43,925 --> 00:32:46,041
It's quite the experience.

687
00:32:46,125 --> 00:32:47,540
I hear the Prince of Wales

688
00:32:47,624 --> 00:32:49,384
is taken with my compatriot
Lady Furness,

689
00:32:49,468 --> 00:32:50,850
and she's divorced.

690
00:32:50,934 --> 00:32:52,486
The prince's interest will not enhance

691
00:32:52,570 --> 00:32:54,253
her standing in society.

692
00:32:54,337 --> 00:32:56,658
There's nothing wrong with
finding someone attractive.

693
00:32:56,742 --> 00:32:58,359
- You can't blame him for that.
- Mm.

694
00:32:58,443 --> 00:33:00,010
Or me, either.

695
00:33:00,974 --> 00:33:03,343
Meaning what, exactly?

696
00:33:04,350 --> 00:33:05,761
Meaning this.

697
00:33:12,787 --> 00:33:14,608
Just put it there.

698
00:33:14,692 --> 00:33:16,678
We'll look after ourselves.

699
00:33:16,762 --> 00:33:18,677
You can go to bed.

700
00:33:18,761 --> 00:33:20,546
If you're sure, milady.

701
00:33:20,630 --> 00:33:21,999
I'm quite sure.

702
00:33:27,264 --> 00:33:29,648
- Who?
- Daisy Parker.

703
00:33:29,732 --> 00:33:31,858
She works in the kitchens at the abbey.

704
00:33:31,942 --> 00:33:33,428
Sir Hector isn't going to like that.

705
00:33:33,512 --> 00:33:35,587
Next I'll ask Carson.

706
00:33:35,671 --> 00:33:37,271
He's well thought of in the area,

707
00:33:37,274 --> 00:33:39,031
so he'll be very helpful.

708
00:33:39,115 --> 00:33:40,592
So you really mean to bait Sir Hector?

709
00:33:40,676 --> 00:33:43,470
I mean to bait him very much indeed.

710
00:33:59,197 --> 00:34:00,895
My God.

711
00:34:04,509 --> 00:34:05,927
Good morning.

712
00:34:06,011 --> 00:34:08,924
Don't say "good morning"
as if everything's fine.

713
00:34:09,008 --> 00:34:10,858
Isn't it?

714
00:34:10,942 --> 00:34:12,060
No.

715
00:34:12,144 --> 00:34:13,559
This is not who I am.

716
00:34:13,643 --> 00:34:15,660
This is absolutely not how I behave.

717
00:34:15,744 --> 00:34:17,865
I suppose we were both quite drunk.

718
00:34:17,949 --> 00:34:19,353
Oh.

719
00:34:20,317 --> 00:34:22,333
I had a marvelous time.

720
00:34:22,417 --> 00:34:23,675
Well, I didn't.

721
00:34:23,759 --> 00:34:25,107
Oh, I'm sorry.

722
00:34:25,191 --> 00:34:26,914
Well, I don't mean that exactly.

723
00:34:26,998 --> 00:34:29,011
But I do not jump into bed with strangers

724
00:34:29,095 --> 00:34:30,411
at the drop of a hat,

725
00:34:30,495 --> 00:34:32,020
and I don't approve of people who do.

726
00:34:32,104 --> 00:34:34,984
Have you never done anything
you don't approve of?

727
00:34:35,068 --> 00:34:36,514
That's not the point.

728
00:34:36,598 --> 00:34:38,198
Well, you just got your divorce,

729
00:34:38,270 --> 00:34:39,828
and some old hag insulted you.

730
00:34:39,912 --> 00:34:42,091
Surely you're entitled to drink too much

731
00:34:42,175 --> 00:34:43,322
and have some fun with me.

732
00:34:43,406 --> 00:34:45,092
No one would blame you.

733
00:34:45,176 --> 00:34:46,491
I would blame me.

734
00:34:46,575 --> 00:34:48,135
And so would everyone else.

735
00:34:48,219 --> 00:34:51,034
Now get back to your room
before my maid arrives.

736
00:34:51,118 --> 00:34:52,764
I was hoping for a second round.

737
00:34:52,848 --> 00:34:54,539
I won't tell if you don't.

738
00:34:54,623 --> 00:34:55,939
Just go.

739
00:34:56,023 --> 00:34:57,435
Please.

740
00:34:57,519 --> 00:34:59,294
- Go.
- All right.

741
00:35:04,133 --> 00:35:06,697
But I'll go with a song in my heart.

742
00:35:25,823 --> 00:35:28,158
I hope you slept well, milady.

743
00:35:29,861 --> 00:35:31,469
Could you find me some aspirin?

744
00:35:31,553 --> 00:35:32,913
I've rather a headache.

745
00:35:32,997 --> 00:35:34,748
I thought you might have, milady.

746
00:35:34,832 --> 00:35:36,595
You'll find two on your tray.

747
00:35:40,662 --> 00:35:42,255
What's your plan for the day?

748
00:35:42,339 --> 00:35:44,525
I've got my first meeting
with Lady Merton's committee

749
00:35:44,609 --> 00:35:45,722
this afternoon.

750
00:35:45,806 --> 00:35:47,587
Oh, yes.

751
00:35:47,671 --> 00:35:49,864
It's flattering of her to ask you.

752
00:35:49,948 --> 00:35:51,694
Quite the compliment.

753
00:35:51,778 --> 00:35:54,933
If I can be helpful in
some way, then I'll be pleased.

754
00:35:55,017 --> 00:35:57,399
I'm sure you'll be very helpful.

755
00:35:57,483 --> 00:35:59,102
I'll come up to the house for lunch.

756
00:35:59,186 --> 00:36:01,203
Oh, Charlie, there's no need.

757
00:36:01,287 --> 00:36:03,207
You'll only tire yourself.

758
00:36:03,291 --> 00:36:06,272
If you mean that I look worn out,

759
00:36:06,356 --> 00:36:07,747
you're right.

760
00:36:07,831 --> 00:36:09,417
London finished me off.

761
00:36:09,501 --> 00:36:11,619
Then rest.

762
00:36:11,703 --> 00:36:13,830
Enjoy your freedom.

763
00:36:14,796 --> 00:36:16,881
Thank heavens for this cottage.

764
00:36:16,965 --> 00:36:19,594
Did you worry
Lady Mary might turn us out?

765
00:36:19,678 --> 00:36:21,261
She'd never do that.

766
00:36:21,345 --> 00:36:24,796
I just hope Mr. Talbot
doesn't want to make trouble.

767
00:36:24,880 --> 00:36:26,131
He might.

768
00:36:26,215 --> 00:36:29,101
No one knows how to behave anymore.

769
00:36:29,185 --> 00:36:31,085
- That's harsh.
- If it wasn't for him,

770
00:36:31,156 --> 00:36:33,438
Lady Mary would never have gone
for a divorce.

771
00:36:33,522 --> 00:36:36,133
Plenty of the gentry lived
with husbands and wives

772
00:36:36,217 --> 00:36:39,407
who were difficult or boring
or-or just plain nasty.

773
00:36:39,491 --> 00:36:41,876
And what do you think they did?

774
00:36:41,960 --> 00:36:45,532
They put it in their kit bag
and they kept on marching.

775
00:36:47,236 --> 00:36:48,548
<i>How are you getting on?</i>

776
00:36:48,632 --> 00:36:50,222
Pretty well, I think.

777
00:36:50,306 --> 00:36:52,125
- We're nearly there.
- You are good.

778
00:36:52,209 --> 00:36:55,227
At least the things
Mama loved are safe now.

779
00:36:55,311 --> 00:36:56,990
It made me nervous knowing the Dower House

780
00:36:57,074 --> 00:36:59,099
was full of her possessions
when no one was living here.

781
00:36:59,183 --> 00:37:01,133
What will you do, find a tenant?

782
00:37:01,215 --> 00:37:03,430
I suppose. Any suggestions?

783
00:37:03,514 --> 00:37:05,337
Maybe. Let me think about it.

784
00:37:05,421 --> 00:37:08,171
Let's go home if we're to meet
Mary and Harold

785
00:37:08,255 --> 00:37:10,472
and the mysterious Mr. Sambrook.

786
00:37:10,556 --> 00:37:12,647
How could Harold have landed us with him?

787
00:37:12,731 --> 00:37:13,881
And why is he here?

788
00:37:13,965 --> 00:37:15,610
It's not very English behavior.

789
00:37:15,694 --> 00:37:17,414
Well, we're not English, my brother and I,

790
00:37:17,498 --> 00:37:19,916
which I know takes some getting used to.

791
00:37:26,271 --> 00:37:28,168
Goodbye, Mama.

792
00:37:43,253 --> 00:37:44,610
Ah.

793
00:37:44,694 --> 00:37:45,856
Cora.

794
00:37:48,757 --> 00:37:51,709
Still so glamorous, I see.

795
00:37:51,793 --> 00:37:53,215
If you say so, my brother.

796
00:37:53,299 --> 00:37:54,954
- Hello, Mary.
- Mama.

797
00:37:55,038 --> 00:37:56,515
And you must be Mr. Sambrook.

798
00:37:56,599 --> 00:37:57,781
Welcome to Downton.

799
00:37:57,865 --> 00:37:59,192
But I hope you won't be bored.

800
00:37:59,276 --> 00:38:00,718
Harold and I have a lot to talk about.

801
00:38:00,802 --> 00:38:02,027
You can talk in front of Gus.

802
00:38:02,111 --> 00:38:04,446
Come in and have some tea.

803
00:38:06,942 --> 00:38:09,036
We thought the funeral was splendid.

804
00:38:09,120 --> 00:38:11,163
Mother would have been very touched.

805
00:38:11,247 --> 00:38:13,208
Pity you couldn't stay on
in New York for a bit longer.

806
00:38:13,292 --> 00:38:15,040
We would have if I'd known
the time it would take

807
00:38:15,124 --> 00:38:17,572
- to settle things.
- Mm.

808
00:38:17,656 --> 00:38:19,145
Uh, Robert, how are you getting on

809
00:38:19,229 --> 00:38:21,211
with Mary's plan to plumb the cottages?

810
00:38:21,295 --> 00:38:23,513
Not Mary's plan. Our plan.

811
00:38:23,597 --> 00:38:25,962
If it was sensible remains to be seen.

812
00:38:27,139 --> 00:38:29,457
- Seems sensible to me.
- Does it?

813
00:38:29,541 --> 00:38:32,327
I must get you to go through
our accounts while you're here.

814
00:38:32,411 --> 00:38:34,391
Perhaps you can tell me
how we're going to pay for it.

815
00:38:34,475 --> 00:38:36,229
Papa, what's the matter with you?

816
00:38:36,313 --> 00:38:38,528
Mama's inheritance will cover the new work.

817
00:38:38,612 --> 00:38:40,492
I just don't see why everything...

818
00:38:40,576 --> 00:38:42,099
Oh, never mind.

819
00:38:42,183 --> 00:38:44,231
I'm going for a walk.

820
00:38:44,315 --> 00:38:45,829
Where's Teo?

821
00:38:45,913 --> 00:38:47,267
Afternoon post, Your Ladyship.

822
00:38:47,351 --> 00:38:48,703
Thank you.

823
00:38:48,787 --> 00:38:51,104
- Why don't you all go?
- Oh. Good idea.

824
00:38:51,188 --> 00:38:54,614
Not you, Harold. We have a lot
to talk about, you and I.

825
00:38:54,698 --> 00:38:55,926
I'll go.

826
00:38:56,868 --> 00:38:58,418
He's so touchy lately.

827
00:38:58,502 --> 00:39:00,020
I suppose we've got
the divorce to thank for that.

828
00:39:00,104 --> 00:39:02,016
The divorce and the realization

829
00:39:02,100 --> 00:39:04,382
that his days as king of the
castle are coming to an end.

830
00:39:04,466 --> 00:39:05,816
Oh.

831
00:39:05,900 --> 00:39:07,290
Mama, is something the matter?

832
00:39:07,374 --> 00:39:08,722
I thought a dinner might help

833
00:39:08,806 --> 00:39:10,431
restore Mary's faith in humanity,

834
00:39:10,515 --> 00:39:12,800
so, I wrote to some neighbors,
and everyone has refused.

835
00:39:12,884 --> 00:39:14,902
All of them? Golly.

836
00:39:14,986 --> 00:39:16,534
Even Anne Manville has said no

837
00:39:16,618 --> 00:39:19,301
when she's always been so fond of you girls.

838
00:39:19,385 --> 00:39:20,775
We can't just give in.

839
00:39:20,859 --> 00:39:22,274
Are you coming, or what?

840
00:39:22,358 --> 00:39:24,218
- Oh.
- We're coming, Papa.

841
00:39:26,124 --> 00:39:28,924
I'm sorry you've arrived when
tensions are a little high.

842
00:39:29,395 --> 00:39:31,467
I got something for you.

843
00:39:32,694 --> 00:39:34,030
Mm.

844
00:39:35,063 --> 00:39:36,813
- My goodness.
- Yeah.

845
00:39:36,868 --> 00:39:38,390
I had this made for her when she lost

846
00:39:38,474 --> 00:39:39,619
the brooch she'd worn at her wedding.

847
00:39:39,703 --> 00:39:41,052
She wanted you to have it.

848
00:39:41,136 --> 00:39:42,986
Maybe we should go for a walk as well,

849
00:39:43,004 --> 00:39:45,294
because the news is bad, isn't it?

850
00:39:45,378 --> 00:39:46,562
How could you tell?

851
00:39:46,646 --> 00:39:48,726
I've known you since you were born.

852
00:39:48,810 --> 00:39:50,127
Gus should come with us

853
00:39:50,211 --> 00:39:51,971
since he can help me explain everything.

854
00:39:52,055 --> 00:39:53,214
Oh, I'd be happy to.

855
00:39:56,421 --> 00:39:57,978
Is she coming?

856
00:39:58,062 --> 00:39:59,507
She'll be here any moment.

857
00:39:59,591 --> 00:40:01,143
You'll have met Mr. Carson.

858
00:40:01,227 --> 00:40:02,812
Not really.

859
00:40:02,896 --> 00:40:06,029
Of course, I've seen him
when we've dined at the abbey.

860
00:40:08,940 --> 00:40:11,199
Now, I want to get going.

861
00:40:15,442 --> 00:40:17,526
- Sorry I'm late.
- Ah.

862
00:40:17,610 --> 00:40:19,358
I had to finish luncheon.

863
00:40:19,442 --> 00:40:20,494
Come in.

864
00:40:20,578 --> 00:40:22,194
This is Mrs. Parker.

865
00:40:22,278 --> 00:40:25,667
Lady Manville, Mr. Saunders,
Miss Bell, Mrs. Dewlish

866
00:40:25,751 --> 00:40:28,037
and our chairman,
Sir Hector Moreland.

867
00:40:28,121 --> 00:40:29,250
Welcome.

868
00:40:31,229 --> 00:40:33,045
- Hello, Mr. Carson.
- Daisy.

869
00:40:33,129 --> 00:40:36,142
That is, Mrs. Parker.

870
00:40:36,226 --> 00:40:37,951
Lady Merton believes
our new members will give us

871
00:40:38,035 --> 00:40:39,516
a different perspective.

872
00:40:39,600 --> 00:40:41,320
We don't want to disrupt anything.

873
00:40:41,404 --> 00:40:42,882
But we might have something to say.

874
00:40:42,966 --> 00:40:45,024
- Oh, I hope you do.
- We shall see.

875
00:40:45,108 --> 00:40:47,223
So, now, finally...

876
00:40:47,307 --> 00:40:49,823
We can start.

877
00:40:49,907 --> 00:40:51,729
What I don't understand is,

878
00:40:51,813 --> 00:40:55,536
since we survived the crash,
where's the money gone?

879
00:40:55,620 --> 00:40:57,564
Gus took everything out
of the market before the crash.

880
00:40:57,648 --> 00:40:59,031
If it wasn't for him,

881
00:40:59,115 --> 00:41:00,372
our mother's money would have been lost.

882
00:41:00,456 --> 00:41:01,836
You mean it would've been lost sooner?

883
00:41:01,920 --> 00:41:04,201
Gus, please explain.

884
00:41:04,285 --> 00:41:07,214
Well, Harold has been unlucky, it's true,

885
00:41:07,298 --> 00:41:08,711
but he wasn't alone in his suffering.

886
00:41:08,795 --> 00:41:11,310
I lost quite a bit myself as it happens.

887
00:41:11,394 --> 00:41:13,649
And now you'd like to
sell the property that's left,

888
00:41:13,733 --> 00:41:15,346
and for that you need my permission?

889
00:41:15,430 --> 00:41:19,189
Well, it will help him to recoup and rebuild.

890
00:41:19,273 --> 00:41:20,510
Harold...

891
00:41:21,908 --> 00:41:24,058
...You lost the capital
I left in your care.

892
00:41:24,109 --> 00:41:26,333
How do I know you won't lose
the rest of the money?

893
00:41:26,417 --> 00:41:28,731
I want the chance to make the money back.

894
00:41:28,815 --> 00:41:32,363
I have to live, and I have to repay Gus.

895
00:41:32,447 --> 00:41:35,907
He's been bankrolling me
until now, but it can't go on.

896
00:41:35,991 --> 00:41:37,758
No.

897
00:41:39,156 --> 00:41:41,372
We'll work out a plan to repay Mr. Sambrook

898
00:41:41,456 --> 00:41:44,160
but that doesn't involve
putting what's left at risk.

899
00:41:45,664 --> 00:41:48,011
So, item six,

900
00:41:48,095 --> 00:41:49,921
on the day itself, we've settled

901
00:41:50,005 --> 00:41:52,288
that last year's arrangements
will, for the most part, stand.

902
00:41:52,372 --> 00:41:54,423
Yes, absolutely.

903
00:41:54,507 --> 00:41:55,809
Is that a good idea?

904
00:41:57,475 --> 00:41:58,930
Mr. Carson?

905
00:41:59,014 --> 00:42:00,859
Hmm?

906
00:42:00,943 --> 00:42:03,237
- What?
- Well...

907
00:42:03,321 --> 00:42:05,899
To be honest, last year was chaotic.

908
00:42:05,983 --> 00:42:08,432
The livestock were hardly supervised.

909
00:42:08,516 --> 00:42:10,140
I don't think anyone else
would agree with you there.

910
00:42:10,224 --> 00:42:12,037
Mr. Carson.

911
00:42:12,121 --> 00:42:13,879
Remember what you said.

912
00:42:13,963 --> 00:42:15,379
Daisy.

913
00:42:15,463 --> 00:42:17,376
- What does she mean?
- Please,

914
00:42:17,460 --> 00:42:20,618
I have no wish to be rude
to Sir Hector or Lady Merton.

915
00:42:20,702 --> 00:42:23,034
Oh, please enlighten us.
What did you say?

916
00:42:24,040 --> 00:42:26,554
Only that...

917
00:42:26,638 --> 00:42:28,629
She's right.

918
00:42:28,713 --> 00:42:30,658
Things were pretty hopeless,
and they were running around

919
00:42:30,742 --> 00:42:32,996
all over the place, but I'm sure

920
00:42:33,080 --> 00:42:36,231
that Sir Hector would soon
have got things under control.

921
00:42:36,315 --> 00:42:37,367
Are you?

922
00:42:37,451 --> 00:42:38,819
You see what you've done?

923
00:42:40,081 --> 00:42:41,271
You bring in people like this...

924
00:42:41,355 --> 00:42:42,505
People like what?

925
00:42:42,589 --> 00:42:44,476
Surely, we can let them speak.

926
00:42:44,560 --> 00:42:47,109
So, the livestock were badly managed?

927
00:42:47,193 --> 00:42:49,012
And there was no provisions
for lost children, either.

928
00:42:49,096 --> 00:42:51,796
No one to help find them,
no safe place for them to go.

929
00:42:51,835 --> 00:42:53,947
We can't be held responsible
for every child in the county.

930
00:42:54,031 --> 00:42:55,631
But aren't we responsible?

931
00:42:55,672 --> 00:42:58,620
For every child that is a guest at our show?

932
00:42:58,704 --> 00:43:00,427
Restrain yourself, I beg you.

933
00:43:00,511 --> 00:43:02,327
I'm sure Sir Hector will be glad to know

934
00:43:02,411 --> 00:43:03,964
where he got things wrong.

935
00:43:04,048 --> 00:43:05,846
I beg your pardon?

936
00:43:07,108 --> 00:43:09,160
Shall we stick to the agenda?

937
00:43:09,244 --> 00:43:10,895
Well, I can't see that it would hurt

938
00:43:10,979 --> 00:43:12,699
to consider these points.

939
00:43:12,783 --> 00:43:14,591
Please.

940
00:43:15,588 --> 00:43:17,670
I really must insist.

941
00:43:17,754 --> 00:43:19,893
So, item seven.

942
00:43:21,356 --> 00:43:23,484
Lectures and demonstrations on beekeeping

943
00:43:23,568 --> 00:43:27,802
and bottling fruit
at intervals during the day.

944
00:43:29,300 --> 00:43:32,351
Are we to gather that
your talk did not go well?

945
00:43:32,435 --> 00:43:35,125
A great deal of my mother's
fortune has been lost.

946
00:43:35,209 --> 00:43:36,696
What?

947
00:43:36,780 --> 00:43:39,560
And now we need a new plan
to protect what remains.

948
00:43:39,644 --> 00:43:41,211
What happened?

949
00:43:42,486 --> 00:43:44,237
What part did you play in all this?

950
00:43:44,321 --> 00:43:46,165
None of it is Gus's fault.

951
00:43:46,249 --> 00:43:48,075
Without him, things could be a lot worse.

952
00:43:48,159 --> 00:43:49,409
I made the decisions.

953
00:43:49,493 --> 00:43:51,173
Why didn't you share them with me?

954
00:43:51,257 --> 00:43:53,212
And why didn't you tell me
when it was all going wrong?

955
00:43:53,296 --> 00:43:54,578
You put me in charge.

956
00:43:54,662 --> 00:43:56,043
God's sake, Harold.

957
00:43:56,127 --> 00:43:58,076
Don't you see what this means for Downton?

958
00:43:58,160 --> 00:43:59,713
Is it really as bad as you say?

959
00:43:59,797 --> 00:44:01,547
Has everything gone?

960
00:44:01,631 --> 00:44:04,219
Well, there's some property,
including the house in Newport.

961
00:44:04,303 --> 00:44:06,551
- Which Harold hopes to sell.
- But what does that mean

962
00:44:06,635 --> 00:44:08,254
- for the work going on here?
- I'm afraid we've spent money

963
00:44:08,338 --> 00:44:09,988
we don't have on a project
we haven't finished.

964
00:44:10,072 --> 00:44:12,490
But I won't allow a fire sale

965
00:44:12,574 --> 00:44:14,733
when what's left would not
be enough to settle things

966
00:44:14,817 --> 00:44:17,280
at Downton and cover
what we owe Mr. Sambrook.

967
00:44:18,681 --> 00:44:20,118
My God.

968
00:44:21,418 --> 00:44:23,470
Is this the time to think
of selling Grantham House?

969
00:44:23,554 --> 00:44:25,277
What?

970
00:44:25,361 --> 00:44:26,842
Where did that come from?

971
00:44:26,926 --> 00:44:28,606
We must be realistic, Papa.

972
00:44:28,690 --> 00:44:32,177
Keeping a London house is
a huge drain on our resources.

973
00:44:32,261 --> 00:44:34,121
It would give us the capital we need.

974
00:44:34,205 --> 00:44:36,784
Sell Grantham House?

975
00:44:36,868 --> 00:44:39,632
What absolute bloody nonsense!

976
00:44:46,107 --> 00:44:47,684
I'm going to change.

977
00:44:51,347 --> 00:44:53,447
Oh, the other side of cuddly Lord Grantham.

978
00:44:53,481 --> 00:44:55,740
I don't think I've ever seen it before.

979
00:44:55,824 --> 00:44:57,303
Well, you're the one who made him angry.

980
00:44:57,387 --> 00:44:59,244
We seem to be living
under rather a dark shadow

981
00:44:59,328 --> 00:45:00,912
at the moment.

982
00:45:00,996 --> 00:45:03,275
If not Grantham House,
what other options do we have?

983
00:45:03,359 --> 00:45:05,744
It's a good thing the dinner didn't work out.

984
00:45:05,828 --> 00:45:07,231
What dinner?

985
00:45:11,301 --> 00:45:13,116
Only that I invited some locals for dinner

986
00:45:13,200 --> 00:45:14,424
and they couldn't come.

987
00:45:14,508 --> 00:45:15,910
Because of me?

988
00:45:16,981 --> 00:45:18,656
Golly.

989
00:45:18,740 --> 00:45:20,595
A house full of Yanks, and I'm
the one keeping people away.

990
00:45:22,412 --> 00:45:24,467
Just when I thought
I couldn't sink any lower,

991
00:45:24,551 --> 00:45:25,935
down I go again.

992
00:45:26,019 --> 00:45:28,119
Maybe you should be grateful for the Yanks.

993
00:45:31,086 --> 00:45:32,442
We're going to change.

994
00:45:32,526 --> 00:45:33,895
Come on, Bertie.

995
00:45:35,327 --> 00:45:36,783
- I'm so sorry.
- Maybe now would be

996
00:45:36,867 --> 00:45:39,619
a good time for me to show Gus
the della Francesca.

997
00:45:39,703 --> 00:45:41,936
Don't present it as a way to raise capital.

998
00:45:49,412 --> 00:45:51,056
Papa's not being fair.

999
00:45:51,140 --> 00:45:52,799
You must know that, at least.

1000
00:45:52,883 --> 00:45:54,765
Don't you think he's entitled
to be a little unfair

1001
00:45:54,849 --> 00:45:56,698
with Granny's death, your divorce

1002
00:45:56,782 --> 00:45:58,331
and Harold's foolishness?

1003
00:45:58,415 --> 00:46:00,900
Harold's made a real mess
of things, hasn't he?

1004
00:46:00,984 --> 00:46:02,974
It's my fault, really.

1005
00:46:03,058 --> 00:46:05,839
It was like putting a drunk
in charge of a bar.

1006
00:46:05,923 --> 00:46:08,443
♪ I like America ♪

1007
00:46:08,527 --> 00:46:10,718
♪ I have played around every
slappy-happy hunting ground ♪

1008
00:46:10,802 --> 00:46:12,815
You go ahead. I'm going
to make a telephone call.

1009
00:46:12,899 --> 00:46:15,116
♪ But I find America okay ♪

1010
00:46:15,200 --> 00:46:17,655
- ♪ Come what may ♪
- Put them here.

1011
00:46:17,739 --> 00:46:19,524
♪ I shall return someday ♪

1012
00:46:19,608 --> 00:46:24,231
♪ To the good old USA ♪

1013
00:46:24,315 --> 00:46:29,327
♪ Hey, hey... ♪

1014
00:46:29,411 --> 00:46:31,171
That didn't go too well.

1015
00:46:31,255 --> 00:46:32,866
It's not over yet.

1016
00:46:32,950 --> 00:46:34,333
Not by a long shot.

1017
00:46:34,417 --> 00:46:37,008
I couldn't help wondering how it's happened.

1018
00:46:37,092 --> 00:46:39,038
And we were supposed
to double my mother's fortune,

1019
00:46:39,122 --> 00:46:40,747
and now most of it's gone.

1020
00:46:40,831 --> 00:46:42,941
But it's coming back
with interest, I promise.

1021
00:46:43,025 --> 00:46:44,583
It's a new market.

1022
00:46:44,667 --> 00:46:46,750
- I understand it better.
- Hmm.

1023
00:46:46,834 --> 00:46:49,323
But I have to have a free hand.

1024
00:46:49,407 --> 00:46:51,482
They're changing for dinner.

1025
00:46:51,566 --> 00:46:53,623
They'll assemble in the library at 8:00.

1026
00:46:53,707 --> 00:46:55,089
Thank you very much.

1027
00:46:55,173 --> 00:46:57,487
So, you did see him leaving my room?

1028
00:46:57,571 --> 00:46:59,027
I'd never have mentioned it, milady.

1029
00:46:59,111 --> 00:47:00,961
You'd never have forgotten it, either.

1030
00:47:02,319 --> 00:47:03,952
Thank you, Anna.

1031
00:47:07,084 --> 00:47:09,404
I hope Papa didn't upset you.

1032
00:47:09,488 --> 00:47:12,040
Not as much as you did
with the dinner that never was.

1033
00:47:12,124 --> 00:47:14,043
Bertie shouldn't have said anything.

1034
00:47:14,127 --> 00:47:16,511
By the way, Tom rang--
He's coming to stay.

1035
00:47:16,595 --> 00:47:17,912
I know.

1036
00:47:17,996 --> 00:47:19,520
He's meeting Henry in York.

1037
00:47:19,604 --> 00:47:21,183
They finally sold the car business.

1038
00:47:21,267 --> 00:47:23,956
Let's hope he can soothe
your father's spirits.

1039
00:47:24,040 --> 00:47:27,294
I'm not trying to push Papa
into anything, you know?

1040
00:47:27,378 --> 00:47:29,061
Well, I think you are.

1041
00:47:29,145 --> 00:47:30,894
I suspect you're trying
to push him into quite a lot.

1042
00:47:30,978 --> 00:47:32,892
But I believe you have good reasons.

1043
00:47:32,976 --> 00:47:34,434
We should go.

1044
00:47:34,518 --> 00:47:35,818
I'll wait for your father.

1045
00:47:37,882 --> 00:47:39,470
Are we the first?

1046
00:47:39,554 --> 00:47:41,154
Looks like it.

1047
00:47:43,120 --> 00:47:44,640
I know you like champagne.

1048
00:47:44,724 --> 00:47:46,547
Don't remind me.

1049
00:47:46,631 --> 00:47:48,011
You should try America, you know.

1050
00:47:48,095 --> 00:47:49,877
We don't care about divorce over there.

1051
00:47:49,961 --> 00:47:51,618
I think Downton needs me.

1052
00:47:51,702 --> 00:47:53,585
What will Harold do now, do you think?

1053
00:47:53,669 --> 00:47:55,121
Mama won't change her mind.

1054
00:47:55,205 --> 00:47:56,290
I wonder.

1055
00:47:56,374 --> 00:47:58,258
Don't wonder. She won't.

1056
00:47:58,342 --> 00:47:59,959
I love my uncle,

1057
00:48:00,043 --> 00:48:02,292
but he's hardly proved
to be a titan of business.

1058
00:48:02,376 --> 00:48:06,156
But unlike your uncle, I know
how to get the money back.

1059
00:48:06,240 --> 00:48:07,662
Won't you help me?

1060
00:48:11,045 --> 00:48:13,635
- Catch it! Catch it!
- That was a great shot!

1061
00:48:17,356 --> 00:48:19,556
Come on, girls, who's going to get it?

1062
00:48:25,027 --> 00:48:26,950
Thank you.

1063
00:48:27,034 --> 00:48:28,815
Sybbie, darling, have you come, too?

1064
00:48:28,899 --> 00:48:29,981
How lovely.

1065
00:48:30,065 --> 00:48:31,184
Aunt Edith.

1066
00:48:31,268 --> 00:48:33,350
Go and say hello to the others.

1067
00:48:33,434 --> 00:48:35,420
Welcome back to Downton, sir.

1068
00:48:35,504 --> 00:48:37,408
- Thank you, Parker.
- George!

1069
00:48:38,448 --> 00:48:40,543
- Edith.
- Tom.

1070
00:48:41,914 --> 00:48:43,735
Don't go in yet.

1071
00:48:43,819 --> 00:48:45,834
I want to bring you up to date.

1072
00:48:45,918 --> 00:48:47,969
How is Mary getting on?

1073
00:48:48,053 --> 00:48:49,873
Divorce has damaged her badly,

1074
00:48:49,957 --> 00:48:51,637
- as we knew it would.
- Mm-hmm.

1075
00:48:51,721 --> 00:48:54,340
I wanted to help her rebuild
while she ran Downton

1076
00:48:54,424 --> 00:48:57,148
- to take her mind off things.
- But?

1077
00:48:57,232 --> 00:49:00,013
- Socially, it's more difficult
than we expected.
- Oh.

1078
00:49:00,097 --> 00:49:01,647
And with the estate,

1079
00:49:01,731 --> 00:49:04,821
Papa's reluctant to give her
the power she needs.

1080
00:49:04,905 --> 00:49:06,451
We'd love you to talk him into

1081
00:49:06,535 --> 00:49:08,723
letting Mary take the reins properly.

1082
00:49:08,807 --> 00:49:10,694
Of course.

1083
00:49:10,778 --> 00:49:12,527
Does Harold being here

1084
00:49:12,611 --> 00:49:14,829
mean at least Mrs. Levinson's
estate is finally settled?

1085
00:49:14,913 --> 00:49:16,197
I'm afraid not.

1086
00:49:16,281 --> 00:49:19,065
He's made a complete bish of things.

1087
00:49:19,149 --> 00:49:21,371
How's Lucy? Well, I hope.

1088
00:49:21,455 --> 00:49:23,973
We're all well, and it was
a relief to sell the business.

1089
00:49:24,057 --> 00:49:25,304
Money's coming in for a change.

1090
00:49:25,388 --> 00:49:26,938
So you've made the full journey

1091
00:49:26,962 --> 00:49:28,739
from revolutionary to capitalist?

1092
00:49:28,823 --> 00:49:31,627
I prefer to call it being sensible.

1093
00:49:32,836 --> 00:49:34,215
Oh. Go get it. Go get it.

1094
00:49:34,299 --> 00:49:36,351
Very good.

1095
00:49:39,406 --> 00:49:44,489
♪ I'm old-fashioned, but I don't mind it ♪

1096
00:49:44,573 --> 00:49:48,095
♪ That's how I'll always be ♪

1097
00:49:48,179 --> 00:49:52,465
♪ If only you'll agree ♪

1098
00:49:52,549 --> 00:49:58,107
♪ To stay old-fashioned with me. ♪

1099
00:49:58,191 --> 00:50:01,177
Tom's here.
He's gone to his room.

1100
00:50:01,261 --> 00:50:03,508
You should know
I telephoned Guy Dexter.

1101
00:50:03,592 --> 00:50:06,114
His play's over, and he's coming to stay,

1102
00:50:06,198 --> 00:50:08,546
and he's bringing Noël Coward.

1103
00:50:08,630 --> 00:50:10,784
- How exciting.
- It'll cheer Mary up.

1104
00:50:10,868 --> 00:50:13,556
And, of course, they couldn't
care less that she's divorced.

1105
00:50:13,640 --> 00:50:17,561
I also thought it might tempt
the county back into the house.

1106
00:50:17,645 --> 00:50:19,227
Clever girl.

1107
00:50:19,311 --> 00:50:21,232
If we can find a way to let them know.

1108
00:50:21,316 --> 00:50:23,766
- Have you told the kitchen?
- I'm going down now.

1109
00:50:24,345 --> 00:50:26,240
- Edith.
- Hmm?

1110
00:50:26,324 --> 00:50:28,373
Thank you.

1111
00:50:38,195 --> 00:50:39,944
Mr. Carson, can I help?

1112
00:50:40,028 --> 00:50:43,054
Yeah, I've been thinking about
these Lamerie candlesticks.

1113
00:50:43,138 --> 00:50:45,119
His Lordship likes to see them on the table.

1114
00:50:45,203 --> 00:50:46,794
We often use them.

1115
00:50:46,878 --> 00:50:49,095
And you clean them with soap and water?

1116
00:50:49,179 --> 00:50:51,999
Not those awful creams
they keep coming up with now?

1117
00:50:52,083 --> 00:50:54,633
Everything is done as you
would have it, Mr. Carson.

1118
00:50:54,642 --> 00:50:57,229
Then I shall sleep more easily.

1119
00:50:59,222 --> 00:51:01,672
- Well, that sounds like Lady Hex...
- Lady Hexham.

1120
00:51:04,886 --> 00:51:06,941
And don't forget,
it's a secret from Lady Mary.

1121
00:51:07,025 --> 00:51:08,394
Of course, milady.

1122
00:51:11,735 --> 00:51:13,515
What did Lady Hexham want?

1123
00:51:13,599 --> 00:51:15,722
She just came down to tell us
there's to be a dinner

1124
00:51:15,806 --> 00:51:17,254
the night before the County Show.

1125
00:51:17,338 --> 00:51:20,154
Mr. Dexter, Mr. Barrow and Mr. Noël Coward

1126
00:51:20,238 --> 00:51:21,859
are coming down from London.

1127
00:51:21,943 --> 00:51:23,423
I note you list Mr. Barrow

1128
00:51:23,507 --> 00:51:25,523
between Mr. Dexter and Mr. Coward.

1129
00:51:25,607 --> 00:51:27,791
Will he attend the dinner, too?

1130
00:51:27,875 --> 00:51:29,297
MRS. HUGHES:
I shouldn't think so, Charlie.

1131
00:51:29,381 --> 00:51:31,037
But please don't be unkind about him.

1132
00:51:31,121 --> 00:51:33,101
I hope Mr. Molesley doesn't get too excited

1133
00:51:33,185 --> 00:51:34,673
that Mr. Coward is coming.

1134
00:51:34,757 --> 00:51:35,937
Let's not mention it.

1135
00:51:36,021 --> 00:51:37,235
- Hmm.
- Hmm.

1136
00:51:37,319 --> 00:51:39,111
Your last dinner.

1137
00:51:39,195 --> 00:51:42,010
Yes, but shouldn't we make it
the first dinner

1138
00:51:42,094 --> 00:51:43,881
where Daisy's in charge?

1139
00:51:43,965 --> 00:51:45,514
Well, I'll be here, of course,

1140
00:51:45,598 --> 00:51:48,316
but, oh, I'd like to see her
in action before I go.

1141
00:51:48,400 --> 00:51:50,690
Are you looking forward to leaving?

1142
00:51:50,774 --> 00:51:53,058
Oh, I don't know the answer.

1143
00:51:53,142 --> 00:51:56,310
I'll have Mr. Mason, so I won't be lonely.

1144
00:51:59,915 --> 00:52:01,866
None of you can stay away!

1145
00:52:01,950 --> 00:52:03,570
Ah, Mr. Molesley.

1146
00:52:03,654 --> 00:52:05,366
How nice to see you.

1147
00:52:05,450 --> 00:52:07,235
I thought I'd look in to say hello.

1148
00:52:07,319 --> 00:52:08,634
We've read about your latest film.

1149
00:52:08,718 --> 00:52:11,201
- We're all so proud of you.
- Oh, well.

1150
00:52:11,285 --> 00:52:14,235
We're just talking about plans
for Daisy's first big dinner.

1151
00:52:14,261 --> 00:52:15,879
Mr. Dexter and Mr. Barrow are coming.

1152
00:52:15,963 --> 00:52:18,464
And Mr. Coward, too.

1153
00:52:20,934 --> 00:52:22,719
Noël Coward?

1154
00:52:22,803 --> 00:52:24,657
At Downton?

1155
00:52:24,741 --> 00:52:27,176
It just slipped out.

1156
00:52:30,805 --> 00:52:33,425
Well, of course, they won't invite us.

1157
00:52:33,509 --> 00:52:34,824
You can't expect Her Ladyship

1158
00:52:34,908 --> 00:52:36,428
to ask her own lady's maid to dinner.

1159
00:52:36,512 --> 00:52:38,397
This isn't Russia, Mr. Molesley,

1160
00:52:38,481 --> 00:52:40,266
and we are not Bolsheviks.

1161
00:52:40,350 --> 00:52:41,400
Oh, I've had an idea.

1162
00:52:41,418 --> 00:52:42,918
You haven't got a footman now,

1163
00:52:42,951 --> 00:52:45,242
so why can't I be your footman for the night?

1164
00:52:45,326 --> 00:52:46,944
You're not a servant now, Joseph.

1165
00:52:47,028 --> 00:52:49,045
You've left all that behind.

1166
00:52:49,129 --> 00:52:50,444
No, no, but don't you see?

1167
00:52:50,528 --> 00:52:52,128
I'll come in with the first dish,

1168
00:52:52,132 --> 00:52:54,385
and when I get to Mr. Dexter,

1169
00:52:54,469 --> 00:52:56,948
he'll recognize me
and introduce me to Mr. Coward.

1170
00:52:57,032 --> 00:52:58,955
Even if he doesn't,
I could use some extra help

1171
00:52:59,039 --> 00:53:00,521
in the dining room to...

1172
00:53:00,605 --> 00:53:03,191
No, he will, he will, and it'll be fun.

1173
00:53:03,275 --> 00:53:04,725
See, this is what writers do.

1174
00:53:04,741 --> 00:53:07,095
We-we make things up to entertain people.

1175
00:53:07,179 --> 00:53:08,928
Oh!

1176
00:53:09,012 --> 00:53:11,570
They'll-they'll be telling
this story for years to come.

1177
00:53:17,058 --> 00:53:18,738
You've a horse running at Ascot?

1178
00:53:18,822 --> 00:53:20,604
Oh, which day?
We'll be there on the Thursday.

1179
00:53:20,688 --> 00:53:21,981
My horse is in the Gold Cup,

1180
00:53:22,065 --> 00:53:23,540
so you'll be able to cheer it on.

1181
00:53:23,624 --> 00:53:24,916
Oh, not me.

1182
00:53:25,000 --> 00:53:26,547
I'm no racing man, I'm afraid.

1183
00:53:26,631 --> 00:53:28,588
Some bad bets at Belmont cured me for good.

1184
00:53:28,672 --> 00:53:30,635
If only it had.

1185
00:53:31,734 --> 00:53:33,855
All right, if we're talking about it,

1186
00:53:33,939 --> 00:53:37,290
I'd like you all to hear Gus
on how to deal with the losses.

1187
00:53:37,374 --> 00:53:39,196
You mean y-your losses?

1188
00:53:39,280 --> 00:53:40,980
Discussing money over dinner?

1189
00:53:40,984 --> 00:53:42,164
Granny would not have approved.

1190
00:53:42,248 --> 00:53:44,435
Pay no attention. Go on, Gus.

1191
00:53:44,519 --> 00:53:47,766
Well, I'm sure you know,
the crash changed everything.

1192
00:53:47,850 --> 00:53:50,310
Fortunes were lost, men killed themselves.

1193
00:53:50,394 --> 00:53:52,903
It was a terrible time, and
we're still living with that.

1194
00:53:52,987 --> 00:53:55,615
But Cora's money was not lost in the crash.

1195
00:53:55,699 --> 00:53:56,978
Thanks to Gus.

1196
00:53:57,062 --> 00:53:58,747
Mm, maybe,

1197
00:53:58,831 --> 00:54:01,447
but things changed, and we have
to deal with that change.

1198
00:54:01,531 --> 00:54:03,289
You have a house in Newport,

1199
00:54:03,373 --> 00:54:06,023
which is not as sought-after
as it was before the war.

1200
00:54:06,069 --> 00:54:09,457
So Harold should sell it
before its value sinks further?

1201
00:54:09,541 --> 00:54:11,021
You could recover some of the losses

1202
00:54:11,105 --> 00:54:13,491
and use part of it
for the work going on here.

1203
00:54:13,575 --> 00:54:15,075
And repay you, I imagine?

1204
00:54:16,716 --> 00:54:20,305
But if we're speaking openly,
Harold has not done well

1205
00:54:20,389 --> 00:54:23,369
since Lady Grantham asked him
to manage things.

1206
00:54:23,453 --> 00:54:25,210
He was extremely unlucky.

1207
00:54:25,294 --> 00:54:27,607
If you want big gains, you have to be bold.

1208
00:54:27,691 --> 00:54:31,348
But the market is not safe, even now.

1209
00:54:31,432 --> 00:54:33,710
- I'd stay in bricks and mortar.
- I agree.

1210
00:54:33,794 --> 00:54:35,445
Lady Mary, what do you think?

1211
00:54:40,143 --> 00:54:41,751
I think Mama knows what she's doing,

1212
00:54:41,835 --> 00:54:43,741
and I'd back her instincts.

1213
00:54:49,782 --> 00:54:52,302
I'm sorry, Your Ladyship,
Lady Mary's not come up yet.

1214
00:54:52,386 --> 00:54:54,800
Oh, no, it was you I wanted to see.

1215
00:54:54,884 --> 00:54:57,543
Did you know that Her Ladyship

1216
00:54:57,627 --> 00:55:00,410
planned the dinner for Lady Mary
before Mr. Coward was invited,

1217
00:55:00,494 --> 00:55:03,299
but that all of our local friends refused?

1218
00:55:04,297 --> 00:55:05,978
Miss Baxter did mention it.

1219
00:55:06,062 --> 00:55:09,418
My plan, if Mr. Coward
and Mr. Dexter agreed to come,

1220
00:55:09,502 --> 00:55:11,282
was that they'd change their mind.

1221
00:55:11,366 --> 00:55:15,410
But now that I've managed it,
I'm not sure how to tell them.

1222
00:55:16,443 --> 00:55:18,258
Can you leave this with me, milady?

1223
00:55:18,342 --> 00:55:20,325
Thank you, Anna.

1224
00:55:27,421 --> 00:55:29,340
Are you interested in art?

1225
00:55:29,424 --> 00:55:31,591
Well, I'm interested in a lot of things.

1226
00:55:33,158 --> 00:55:34,781
Good night.

1227
00:55:34,865 --> 00:55:36,380
But I was a little sad

1228
00:55:36,464 --> 00:55:38,514
that you didn't stick up for me at dinner.

1229
00:55:38,595 --> 00:55:40,616
I'm sure you don't need my help.

1230
00:55:40,700 --> 00:55:43,047
Well, maybe not,
but I thought we were friends.

1231
00:55:43,131 --> 00:55:45,187
What would happen
if I told them we were lovers

1232
00:55:45,271 --> 00:55:47,193
on the day that we met?

1233
00:55:47,277 --> 00:55:49,521
That would put a cat among the pigeons.

1234
00:55:49,605 --> 00:55:51,197
Are you threatening me?

1235
00:55:51,281 --> 00:55:53,231
Just, the English are so easily shocked,

1236
00:55:53,280 --> 00:55:54,563
the thought of their expressions

1237
00:55:54,647 --> 00:55:57,012
if I just blurted it out, it's tempting.

1238
00:55:58,213 --> 00:56:01,357
Then it's a temptation
you must resist, Mr. Sambrook.

1239
00:56:07,156 --> 00:56:09,976
I wish I understood
Sambrook's part in all this.

1240
00:56:10,060 --> 00:56:13,150
I suppose he's making sure
he gets his cash back,

1241
00:56:13,234 --> 00:56:15,354
but Tom's going to look into it.

1242
00:56:15,438 --> 00:56:18,704
I didn't like him fishing for Mary's support.

1243
00:56:19,906 --> 00:56:22,153
- How's she doing, do you think?
- Well, you know Mary.

1244
00:56:22,237 --> 00:56:25,579
She likes to look in control,
whether she is or not.

1245
00:56:26,814 --> 00:56:29,661
Don't tell her, but we're
giving rather a special party

1246
00:56:29,745 --> 00:56:31,496
to take her mind off things.

1247
00:56:31,580 --> 00:56:33,036
Will anyone come?

1248
00:56:33,120 --> 00:56:34,770
Oh, they'll come.

1249
00:56:34,854 --> 00:56:37,723
Mary may have lost her footing
lately, but I haven't.

1250
00:56:40,824 --> 00:56:43,016
There she is.

1251
00:56:43,100 --> 00:56:44,983
Hello, Miss Grant. How are you?

1252
00:56:45,067 --> 00:56:46,417
Very well, Mrs. Bates.

1253
00:56:46,501 --> 00:56:47,786
You remember Miss Grant,
Lady Osborne's maid?

1254
00:56:47,870 --> 00:56:49,588
Of course.

1255
00:56:49,672 --> 00:56:51,583
I'm sorry she isn't able to
come to Her Ladyship's dinner.

1256
00:56:51,667 --> 00:56:53,357
They were sorry, too,

1257
00:56:53,441 --> 00:56:55,528
but I'm sure
I don't have to explain.

1258
00:56:55,612 --> 00:56:58,856
But it is a pity they'll miss
meeting Noël Coward.

1259
00:56:58,940 --> 00:57:00,624
Noël Coward's coming to Downton?

1260
00:57:00,708 --> 00:57:01,759
Hmm.

1261
00:57:01,843 --> 00:57:03,894
And the film star Guy Dexter.

1262
00:57:03,978 --> 00:57:05,762
So, it'll be fun for us anyway.

1263
00:57:05,846 --> 00:57:08,205
Oh, it certainly will be.

1264
00:57:08,289 --> 00:57:10,500
I should get a move on. Goodbye.

1265
00:57:10,584 --> 00:57:12,252
Bye.

1266
00:57:14,529 --> 00:57:16,608
I'd say Lady Osborne will have telephoned

1267
00:57:16,692 --> 00:57:18,344
by the time we get home.

1268
00:57:35,283 --> 00:57:36,832
I don't know.

1269
00:57:36,916 --> 00:57:38,964
It looks more like a funfair
than a County Show.

1270
00:57:39,048 --> 00:57:40,966
Well done, Mrs. Parker.

1271
00:57:41,050 --> 00:57:43,038
I hope you'll be here early on the day.

1272
00:57:43,122 --> 00:57:45,706
I'll do my best, but I've got
a big dinner the night before.

1273
00:57:45,790 --> 00:57:47,313
Oh, that's still happening, is it?

1274
00:57:47,397 --> 00:57:48,981
Certainly is.
We've got Noël Coward

1275
00:57:49,065 --> 00:57:50,810
and all sorts coming.

1276
00:57:50,894 --> 00:57:52,812
Noël Coward will be at the dinner?

1277
00:57:52,896 --> 00:57:54,816
To me, the whole thing looks wrong.

1278
00:57:54,900 --> 00:57:56,553
I hate to contradict you, Sir Hector,

1279
00:57:56,637 --> 00:57:58,590
but aren't we giving them a proper day out

1280
00:57:58,674 --> 00:58:02,258
with good food and rides
for the children to enjoy?

1281
00:58:02,342 --> 00:58:04,062
These people work hard.

1282
00:58:04,146 --> 00:58:05,861
Don't they deserve it?

1283
00:58:05,945 --> 00:58:08,995
You see, Carson, we'll make
a socialist of you yet.

1284
00:58:09,079 --> 00:58:12,270
You will not, milady.

1285
00:58:12,354 --> 00:58:13,904
We're turning it into a circus.

1286
00:58:13,918 --> 00:58:16,199
It may come as a surprise,
Sir Hector,

1287
00:58:16,283 --> 00:58:18,508
but we want our visitors to have a good time.

1288
00:58:18,592 --> 00:58:20,113
- Oh.
- Oh.

1289
00:58:20,197 --> 00:58:21,748
Steady.

1290
00:58:23,366 --> 00:58:24,878
Lady Manville was on the telephone,

1291
00:58:24,962 --> 00:58:26,949
and Lady Osborne and lots of the others,

1292
00:58:27,033 --> 00:58:29,385
saying things have changed
and they can come after all.

1293
00:58:29,469 --> 00:58:31,387
Well, you know the reason.

1294
00:58:31,471 --> 00:58:33,554
Mr. Levinson telephoned, milady.

1295
00:58:33,638 --> 00:58:35,118
He said he and Mr. Sambrook

1296
00:58:35,202 --> 00:58:37,226
won't be back in time for dinner.

1297
00:58:37,310 --> 00:58:38,924
Thank you, Parker.

1298
00:58:39,008 --> 00:58:40,900
Whip that into stiff peaks for me.

1299
00:58:40,984 --> 00:58:42,265
Hello, Charlie.

1300
00:58:42,349 --> 00:58:43,463
How was the meeting?

1301
00:58:43,547 --> 00:58:44,765
Oh, uh, fine.

1302
00:58:44,849 --> 00:58:46,296
Uh, but I noticed in the dining room,

1303
00:58:46,380 --> 00:58:48,340
the dinner has been laid
with the Sèvres service,

1304
00:58:48,424 --> 00:58:50,438
so I've asked for the Meissen instead.

1305
00:58:50,522 --> 00:58:52,045
It's all right, Mabel.

1306
00:58:52,129 --> 00:58:54,006
Leave the Sèvres as it is.

1307
00:58:54,090 --> 00:58:56,379
I have no wish to undercut you, Mr. Parker,

1308
00:58:56,463 --> 00:58:58,384
but you may not understand.

1309
00:58:58,468 --> 00:59:00,816
The Sèvres is a soft-paste porcelain,

1310
00:59:00,900 --> 00:59:03,883
much more fragile
than the hard-paste Meissen.

1311
00:59:03,967 --> 00:59:06,391
I understand perfectly,
Mr. Carson.

1312
00:59:06,475 --> 00:59:09,324
Her Ladyship asked for the Sèvres.

1313
00:59:09,408 --> 00:59:11,338
Thank you, Mabel.

1314
00:59:12,214 --> 00:59:13,733
Let him do his job.

1315
00:59:13,817 --> 00:59:15,474
So be it.

1316
00:59:16,912 --> 00:59:18,128
It's nice to have a night off

1317
00:59:18,212 --> 00:59:20,337
from the watchful eyes of Mr. Sambrook.

1318
00:59:20,421 --> 00:59:21,970
He's very confident, isn't he?

1319
00:59:22,054 --> 00:59:24,334
- Rather a contrast to Harold.
- Let's be nice.

1320
00:59:24,418 --> 00:59:26,246
We'll cheer him on at Ascot,
then we'll go home

1321
00:59:26,330 --> 00:59:28,145
without a cross word being spoken.

1322
00:59:28,229 --> 00:59:29,613
Hmm.

1323
00:59:29,697 --> 00:59:31,308
Robert, you were asking about the sale.

1324
00:59:31,392 --> 00:59:33,051
It seems to have gone through very smoothly.

1325
00:59:33,135 --> 00:59:34,286
Hmm.

1326
00:59:34,370 --> 00:59:35,887
Henry's not been at all difficult.

1327
00:59:35,971 --> 00:59:37,822
Mm, hmm.

1328
00:59:37,906 --> 00:59:41,368
He asked about Downton, if
you were farming more cattle.

1329
00:59:42,344 --> 00:59:43,989
That doesn't sound like Henry.

1330
00:59:44,073 --> 00:59:45,824
He's not usually interested in anything

1331
00:59:45,908 --> 00:59:47,341
that doesn't run on petrol.

1332
00:59:48,308 --> 00:59:50,293
I told him I didn't know the answer.

1333
00:59:50,377 --> 00:59:52,130
There is no answer.

1334
00:59:52,214 --> 00:59:55,382
I have yet to decide what the answer will be.

1335
00:59:56,258 --> 00:59:57,835
I know what this is.

1336
00:59:57,919 --> 00:59:58,978
What you're all thinking.

1337
00:59:59,062 --> 01:00:00,280
I bet you don't.

1338
01:00:00,364 --> 01:00:01,609
Have you put them up to this, Mary?

1339
01:00:01,693 --> 01:00:03,411
So you can have it your way?

1340
01:00:03,495 --> 01:00:04,978
Oh, really, Papa?

1341
01:00:05,062 --> 01:00:07,310
You told me I was captain of the ship now,

1342
01:00:07,394 --> 01:00:09,803
or has the divorce somehow ruled me out?

1343
01:00:17,275 --> 01:00:20,562
Robert, you've worked hard
for this family for many years.

1344
01:00:20,646 --> 01:00:22,300
It's time to put your feet up.

1345
01:00:22,384 --> 01:00:23,861
Leave the heavy lifting to Mary.

1346
01:00:23,945 --> 01:00:25,367
And what am I to do?

1347
01:00:25,451 --> 01:00:26,799
What is my job?

1348
01:00:26,883 --> 01:00:28,575
To walk around in my tweeds,

1349
01:00:28,659 --> 01:00:31,642
smiling hello at the tenants
so that when I'm dead

1350
01:00:31,726 --> 01:00:33,871
everyone can say what a nice chap I was?

1351
01:00:33,955 --> 01:00:35,224
As long as they do.

1352
01:00:36,661 --> 01:00:38,711
Oh, speak up, Bertie.

1353
01:00:38,795 --> 01:00:40,815
You're nodding away.

1354
01:00:40,899 --> 01:00:43,100
Thank you, Parker.

1355
01:00:45,974 --> 01:00:48,858
I got Brancaster when I was
young enough to make changes.

1356
01:00:48,942 --> 01:00:51,824
I'd say the place
and the people who live there

1357
01:00:51,908 --> 01:00:54,997
are better off as a result.

1358
01:00:55,081 --> 01:00:57,498
When you took charge,
there were emperors in Moscow,

1359
01:00:57,582 --> 01:00:59,097
Vienna and Berlin,

1360
01:00:59,181 --> 01:01:00,931
and your parents were king and queen

1361
01:01:00,989 --> 01:01:03,368
of this part of the county,
but that world is gone now.

1362
01:01:03,452 --> 01:01:05,536
- It's a different place.
- Oh, so everyone keeps saying.

1363
01:01:05,620 --> 01:01:07,414
And it's not different
because we can get to Cape Town

1364
01:01:07,498 --> 01:01:10,248
in a few days instead of half a year.

1365
01:01:10,332 --> 01:01:11,878
We're changing, too.

1366
01:01:11,962 --> 01:01:14,946
The way we talk, the way we dress,

1367
01:01:15,030 --> 01:01:17,585
the way we deal with each other.

1368
01:01:17,669 --> 01:01:19,888
This is Mary's time.

1369
01:01:19,972 --> 01:01:22,186
She's in step with how to run this estate

1370
01:01:22,270 --> 01:01:24,023
in the '30s, the '40s and the '50s.

1371
01:01:24,107 --> 01:01:25,927
- And I'm not?
- You know this system

1372
01:01:26,011 --> 01:01:27,767
doesn't work if people hold on too long.

1373
01:01:27,851 --> 01:01:31,511
I'm pleasantly surprised you
think the system works at all.

1374
01:01:33,223 --> 01:01:35,274
I have something to add.

1375
01:01:35,358 --> 01:01:37,544
The missing detail in this

1376
01:01:37,628 --> 01:01:39,893
is that we all, every one of us, loves you.

1377
01:01:41,658 --> 01:01:43,378
Very much.

1378
01:01:57,507 --> 01:02:00,432
MRS. HUGHES: They're all coming,
Her Ladyship's told me.

1379
01:02:00,516 --> 01:02:01,797
- Oh, thank you.
- Thank you.

1380
01:02:01,881 --> 01:02:04,637
And some are angling for invitations

1381
01:02:04,721 --> 01:02:07,066
when they weren't asked in the first place.

1382
01:02:07,150 --> 01:02:08,607
- Then well done to us.
- Sad, though.

1383
01:02:08,691 --> 01:02:10,443
They were happy to throw over Lady Mary,

1384
01:02:10,527 --> 01:02:12,377
though they've known her all her life.

1385
01:02:12,390 --> 01:02:14,074
Now they'll do anything to
have dinner with a famous face.

1386
01:02:14,158 --> 01:02:15,780
That's the way the world is these days.

1387
01:02:15,864 --> 01:02:17,748
There's not a lot of point
in objecting to it.

1388
01:02:17,832 --> 01:02:19,145
- Oh, thank you.
- Mr. Branson was

1389
01:02:19,229 --> 01:02:21,611
really giving it to His Lordship at dinner.

1390
01:02:21,695 --> 01:02:23,753
It's funny to think
he used to clean their cars.

1391
01:02:23,837 --> 01:02:25,487
I'm sorry for His Lordship.

1392
01:02:25,500 --> 01:02:27,416
He's always done his best.

1393
01:02:27,500 --> 01:02:30,273
MRS. HUGHES:
Oh, Mr. Mason, come in.

1394
01:02:31,407 --> 01:02:34,792
These are happy times,
getting your wife back.

1395
01:02:34,876 --> 01:02:36,533
Oh, it is.

1396
01:02:36,617 --> 01:02:38,362
But she'll miss all of you.

1397
01:02:38,446 --> 01:02:41,807
It'll be odd to cook for two instead of 22,

1398
01:02:41,891 --> 01:02:44,043
and in silence rather than
the running commentary.

1399
01:02:45,585 --> 01:02:47,585
Oh. I'll be back soon.

1400
01:02:48,462 --> 01:02:49,779
So many changes.

1401
01:02:49,863 --> 01:02:51,547
And we do need a new footman, you know.

1402
01:02:51,631 --> 01:02:52,881
Andy can't do everything.

1403
01:02:52,932 --> 01:02:55,181
I'm not sure
Lady Mary would agree.

1404
01:02:55,265 --> 01:02:57,784
She's looking to economize wherever she can

1405
01:02:57,868 --> 01:02:59,192
when she takes over.

1406
01:02:59,276 --> 01:03:00,476
It won't be easy for her

1407
01:03:00,544 --> 01:03:02,828
with that divorce round her neck.

1408
01:03:02,912 --> 01:03:06,530
Well, then, we must all show
that we support her

1409
01:03:06,614 --> 01:03:08,567
- where we can.
- I agree.

1410
01:03:08,651 --> 01:03:10,401
- Here we are.
- MRS. PATMORE: Oh...

1411
01:03:10,445 --> 01:03:11,897
Thank you, Daisy.

1412
01:03:11,981 --> 01:03:13,563
This looks delicious.

1413
01:03:13,647 --> 01:03:15,897
MR. MASON: Splendid.

1414
01:03:16,622 --> 01:03:18,001
To Mrs. Patmore.

1415
01:03:18,085 --> 01:03:19,410
To Mrs. Mason.

1416
01:03:21,155 --> 01:03:22,605
Mrs. Mason.

1417
01:03:22,689 --> 01:03:24,989
Now, are you quite set
for Mr. Coward's dinner?

1418
01:03:25,060 --> 01:03:26,211
MRS. HUGHES:
Oh.

1419
01:03:26,295 --> 01:03:28,079
When my time ends and yours begins.

1420
01:03:28,163 --> 01:03:30,213
Does that make you feel sad?

1421
01:03:30,297 --> 01:03:33,590
A bit, but I don't fight it.

1422
01:03:33,674 --> 01:03:35,518
Our lives are lived in chapters,

1423
01:03:35,602 --> 01:03:37,725
and nothing's wrong when a chapter is done

1424
01:03:37,809 --> 01:03:39,827
and a new one begins.

1425
01:03:39,911 --> 01:03:42,195
It's your time now, and I...

1426
01:03:42,279 --> 01:03:45,645
And I'm prouder of that than anything.

1427
01:03:46,687 --> 01:03:49,088
You're the daughter I never had.

1428
01:03:50,020 --> 01:03:51,967
I'll treasure those words.

1429
01:03:52,051 --> 01:03:53,653
I will.

1430
01:03:58,434 --> 01:04:00,219
Milady, telephone call.

1431
01:04:00,303 --> 01:04:01,694
Lady Falmouth.

1432
01:04:03,267 --> 01:04:05,665
See they get coffee when they come in.

1433
01:04:08,271 --> 01:04:10,129
Edith, can I grab you for a moment?

1434
01:04:10,213 --> 01:04:11,757
If you like.

1435
01:04:21,051 --> 01:04:23,741
Am I in for another pummeling?

1436
01:04:23,825 --> 01:04:26,071
No more pummeling.

1437
01:04:26,155 --> 01:04:27,870
But I know how things are,

1438
01:04:27,954 --> 01:04:29,777
and I wondered if the money
from the sale of the business

1439
01:04:29,861 --> 01:04:31,493
might help tide you over.

1440
01:04:32,498 --> 01:04:34,145
Oh, Tom.

1441
01:04:34,229 --> 01:04:36,322
My dear chap, don't think of it.

1442
01:04:36,406 --> 01:04:38,056
I'm serious.

1443
01:04:38,140 --> 01:04:40,657
You and all of Sybil's family
have given me everything.

1444
01:04:40,741 --> 01:04:42,386
Isn't that worth something?

1445
01:04:42,470 --> 01:04:45,210
It's worth a great deal, but not money.

1446
01:04:46,409 --> 01:04:48,666
Now help yourself to some port and pass it on

1447
01:04:48,750 --> 01:04:50,434
before we all burst into tears.

1448
01:04:53,083 --> 01:04:55,498
You went to bed with a stranger?

1449
01:04:55,582 --> 01:04:56,805
Well, of course it sounds terrible

1450
01:04:56,889 --> 01:04:58,003
when you put it like that.

1451
01:04:58,087 --> 01:04:59,411
How should I put it?

1452
01:04:59,495 --> 01:05:00,720
He's not Turkish, is he?

1453
01:05:01,728 --> 01:05:03,314
I found him attractive.

1454
01:05:03,398 --> 01:05:04,816
I still do,

1455
01:05:04,900 --> 01:05:07,786
but I think he feels he has a hold over me.

1456
01:05:07,870 --> 01:05:09,818
He wants me to help him convince Mama,

1457
01:05:09,902 --> 01:05:11,248
which, of course, I won't.

1458
01:05:11,332 --> 01:05:13,017
Why are you telling me this?

1459
01:05:13,101 --> 01:05:14,734
I'm not sure.

1460
01:05:15,743 --> 01:05:18,988
The truth is, I'm in a fix,

1461
01:05:19,072 --> 01:05:21,499
and a great lady like you might
have an opinion worth hearing.

1462
01:05:21,583 --> 01:05:22,862
Don't patronize me.

1463
01:05:22,946 --> 01:05:24,601
I wouldn't dare.

1464
01:05:24,685 --> 01:05:26,301
But what do you think?

1465
01:05:26,385 --> 01:05:29,636
Should I try to placate
Sambrook or just ignore him?

1466
01:05:31,418 --> 01:05:32,775
Can I ask Bertie about it?

1467
01:05:32,859 --> 01:05:35,178
- Must you?
- I think I must.

1468
01:05:35,262 --> 01:05:37,514
If he gives me funny looks
for the rest of my life,

1469
01:05:37,598 --> 01:05:38,890
I shall blame you.

1470
01:05:41,364 --> 01:05:44,555
Tom offered us the money from his sale.

1471
01:05:46,271 --> 01:05:49,024
Of course, I said no, but I was touched.

1472
01:05:49,108 --> 01:05:51,396
- And it's made me think.
- What about?

1473
01:05:51,480 --> 01:05:52,772
Mary is right.

1474
01:05:53,983 --> 01:05:56,534
We have no option but to sell Grantham House.

1475
01:05:56,618 --> 01:05:58,627
It's time to move on.

1476
01:05:58,711 --> 01:06:00,634
Does she know you've seen the light?

1477
01:06:00,718 --> 01:06:01,990
Not yet.

1478
01:06:04,651 --> 01:06:06,411
And what about her running Downton?

1479
01:06:06,495 --> 01:06:07,746
What about it?

1480
01:06:07,830 --> 01:06:09,206
I don't wear a sack over my head.

1481
01:06:09,290 --> 01:06:10,912
I see how you treat her.

1482
01:06:10,996 --> 01:06:12,627
Don't you want her in command?

1483
01:06:13,635 --> 01:06:15,828
No, I do. I've said so.

1484
01:06:17,497 --> 01:06:19,351
But now the moment's come...

1485
01:06:19,435 --> 01:06:21,335
You can't bear to relinquish the crown.

1486
01:06:27,608 --> 01:06:29,999
Well, I hope it won't overload you.

1487
01:06:30,083 --> 01:06:32,398
And you have the show the next day.

1488
01:06:32,482 --> 01:06:35,500
Lady Merton let me make a real difference.

1489
01:06:35,584 --> 01:06:36,773
If you're clear about your arguments,

1490
01:06:36,857 --> 01:06:38,538
you can make things happen.

1491
01:06:38,622 --> 01:06:41,072
Even with His Serene Highness
Sir Hector Moreland.

1492
01:06:41,094 --> 01:06:43,279
I knew you would more than hold your own.

1493
01:06:43,363 --> 01:06:46,614
No wonder you say
you won't always be in service.

1494
01:06:46,698 --> 01:06:49,784
Well, I won't, but I don't have
bad memories of my time here.

1495
01:06:59,277 --> 01:07:01,824
This is a, a great honor, milord.

1496
01:07:01,908 --> 01:07:05,603
I don't know about that, but the truth is, I...

1497
01:07:05,687 --> 01:07:07,536
I need your advice.

1498
01:07:07,620 --> 01:07:08,936
Uh...

1499
01:07:09,020 --> 01:07:11,101
How? Uh, about what?

1500
01:07:11,185 --> 01:07:13,556
Oh, do sit.

1501
01:07:15,395 --> 01:07:19,048
We were young men
when you first came to Downton.

1502
01:07:19,132 --> 01:07:21,085
You were by my side when I inherited,

1503
01:07:21,169 --> 01:07:23,714
and here we still are
however many years later.

1504
01:07:23,798 --> 01:07:26,589
I've enjoyed a good life
in your service, milord.

1505
01:07:26,673 --> 01:07:28,387
I hope so.

1506
01:07:28,471 --> 01:07:30,271
You've run the house well, of course,

1507
01:07:30,344 --> 01:07:34,060
but I believe you've made it
a happy place, too.

1508
01:07:34,144 --> 01:07:36,066
That's important to me.

1509
01:07:36,150 --> 01:07:38,670
We were well suited to each other, milord,

1510
01:07:38,754 --> 01:07:40,847
which was our good fortune.

1511
01:07:43,717 --> 01:07:47,171
Have you come to discuss Lady Mary?

1512
01:07:49,094 --> 01:07:51,147
You're ahead of me as usual,

1513
01:07:51,231 --> 01:07:54,552
and you'll know
Lady Mary thinks it's time

1514
01:07:54,636 --> 01:07:56,848
that I hand over.

1515
01:07:56,932 --> 01:08:01,191
Her Ladyship agrees, and so,
I suspect, does Lady Hexham.

1516
01:08:01,275 --> 01:08:05,156
More surprisingly...
maybe I do, too.

1517
01:08:05,240 --> 01:08:08,726
But do you really?

1518
01:08:08,810 --> 01:08:11,870
You think I'm foolish to drag my feet?

1519
01:08:11,954 --> 01:08:14,104
I'd never say that, milord, never.

1520
01:08:14,188 --> 01:08:17,302
But I do believe that you could enjoy...

1521
01:08:17,386 --> 01:08:19,544
A calmer time from now on,

1522
01:08:19,628 --> 01:08:21,459
free from worry.

1523
01:08:22,422 --> 01:08:24,147
But I do worry.

1524
01:08:24,231 --> 01:08:26,514
I worry the divorce has changed things.

1525
01:08:26,598 --> 01:08:29,915
Can she play her role in
the county as a social pariah?

1526
01:08:29,999 --> 01:08:31,884
Or...

1527
01:08:33,372 --> 01:08:36,221
...should I s-stay on for a few years

1528
01:08:36,305 --> 01:08:37,722
until things settle down?

1529
01:08:37,806 --> 01:08:40,660
Lady Mary will be a kind
and reliable landlord,

1530
01:08:40,744 --> 01:08:44,428
so her place in the county
will soon be secure again.

1531
01:08:44,512 --> 01:08:46,238
You think she could manage?

1532
01:08:46,322 --> 01:08:50,838
I know she could manage very
well, milord, and so do you.

1533
01:09:06,702 --> 01:09:08,605
Why don't you grab that one on the end?

1534
01:09:09,670 --> 01:09:11,509
<i>- Pickwick Papers,</i> sir.
- Oh.

1535
01:09:20,116 --> 01:09:21,618
Excuse me.

1536
01:09:22,755 --> 01:09:24,109
Really.

1537
01:09:24,193 --> 01:09:27,239
I think a day at Ascot
will be good for us all.

1538
01:09:27,323 --> 01:09:28,939
Not for me.

1539
01:09:29,023 --> 01:09:31,717
The gates of the Royal
Enclosure will be firmly shut.

1540
01:09:31,801 --> 01:09:33,080
But you must come.

1541
01:09:33,164 --> 01:09:34,748
Uh, tell her, Bertie.

1542
01:09:34,832 --> 01:09:37,155
I'm, I'm going to arrange
lunch for us in White's tent.

1543
01:09:37,239 --> 01:09:39,449
So you won't have to go near the Enclosure.

1544
01:09:39,533 --> 01:09:40,883
I'll keep you company.

1545
01:09:40,967 --> 01:09:42,817
The Enclosure holds no delight for me.

1546
01:09:42,878 --> 01:09:44,589
What about you, Mr. Sambrook?

1547
01:09:44,673 --> 01:09:46,631
Do you enjoy these odd
English rituals?

1548
01:09:46,715 --> 01:09:48,628
I do. Very much.

1549
01:09:48,712 --> 01:09:51,064
Edith will line up plenty of Royal Highnesses

1550
01:09:51,148 --> 01:09:52,364
to add to the fun.

1551
01:09:52,448 --> 01:09:54,734
Boy, I'm feeling rather jealous,

1552
01:09:54,818 --> 01:09:57,441
but, uh, not jealous enough
to risk joining you.

1553
01:09:57,525 --> 01:10:00,723
No, I'm gonna stay here
and peruse Mr. Charles Dickens.

1554
01:10:07,896 --> 01:10:09,351
- Ten shillings on...
- There you go, sir.

1555
01:10:09,435 --> 01:10:11,899
Come on, ladies and gentlemen!
Here we go!

1556
01:10:57,385 --> 01:10:59,034
Columbus Boy seems to be doing terribly well.

1557
01:10:59,118 --> 01:11:00,882
Is that the one there?

1558
01:11:08,024 --> 01:11:10,824
- Green and white. The green and white.
- Green and white.

1559
01:11:13,198 --> 01:11:14,443
Come on, Meadows Barron!

1560
01:11:34,788 --> 01:11:35,906
Oh.

1561
01:11:37,618 --> 01:11:39,235
Was he the favorite?

1562
01:11:39,319 --> 01:11:41,880
Shouldn't you wait to see
if there's a steward's inquiry?

1563
01:11:41,964 --> 01:11:43,506
Not when it's second last.

1564
01:11:47,532 --> 01:11:48,879
Shall we go to the Royal Enclosure?

1565
01:11:48,963 --> 01:11:50,980
Don't make him wait any longer, Bertie.

1566
01:11:51,064 --> 01:11:52,648
He's panting for it.

1567
01:11:52,732 --> 01:11:53,935
I would like to see it.

1568
01:11:55,669 --> 01:11:57,388
Uh, go, all of you.

1569
01:11:57,472 --> 01:11:58,959
We'll stay here.

1570
01:11:59,043 --> 01:12:00,092
You sure?

1571
01:12:00,176 --> 01:12:01,877
I am.

1572
01:12:08,291 --> 01:12:10,741
- Two pounds on Bosworth to win.
- Bosworth it is.

1573
01:12:15,159 --> 01:12:16,378
Tom Branson.

1574
01:12:16,462 --> 01:12:17,841
John Bevan, as I live and breathe.

1575
01:12:17,925 --> 01:12:19,349
I thought you were still in New York.

1576
01:12:19,433 --> 01:12:21,714
Well, so I was till about a month ago.

1577
01:12:21,798 --> 01:12:23,748
Tell me, that man you were with earlier,

1578
01:12:23,767 --> 01:12:25,791
does he still call himself
Gus Sambrook?

1579
01:12:25,875 --> 01:12:27,354
Why? Do you know him?

1580
01:12:27,438 --> 01:12:29,135
I'm very sorry to say I do.

1581
01:12:34,681 --> 01:12:37,616
Can I give you a card in case
you're ever in New York?

1582
01:12:38,548 --> 01:12:39,830
If we'd known you were coming,

1583
01:12:39,914 --> 01:12:41,569
we could have given you all luncheon.

1584
01:12:41,653 --> 01:12:43,265
Don't worry,
Your Royal Highness.

1585
01:12:43,349 --> 01:12:45,635
We were happy in White's tent
with my father-in-law.

1586
01:12:45,719 --> 01:12:47,375
Is Lord Grantham here?

1587
01:12:47,459 --> 01:12:49,744
He's with Lady Hexham's sister.

1588
01:12:49,828 --> 01:12:52,616
I'm afraid Lady Mary is having
rather a difficult time.

1589
01:12:52,700 --> 01:12:55,447
We shouldn't talk about that
in front of Lady Petersfield.

1590
01:12:55,531 --> 01:12:57,219
I did what I had to do.

1591
01:12:57,303 --> 01:12:58,919
Lady Mary will be just fine.

1592
01:12:59,003 --> 01:13:02,641
Of course she will, but those
are the rules we live by.

1593
01:13:03,646 --> 01:13:04,830
Cora.

1594
01:13:04,914 --> 01:13:06,164
Tom, where have you been?

1595
01:13:06,245 --> 01:13:07,658
What's wrong?

1596
01:13:07,742 --> 01:13:09,626
I have some news for all of you.

1597
01:13:09,710 --> 01:13:11,177
It's about Sambrook.

1598
01:13:13,884 --> 01:13:15,537
He's a confidence trickster
of the worst sort,

1599
01:13:15,621 --> 01:13:17,238
and it looks like Harold has been his target

1600
01:13:17,322 --> 01:13:18,606
and his latest victim.

1601
01:13:18,690 --> 01:13:20,445
- Why hasn't he been prosecuted?
- He was.

1602
01:13:20,529 --> 01:13:22,508
Some sharp lawyers got him off
on a technicality,

1603
01:13:22,592 --> 01:13:24,345
but he's a crook all the same.

1604
01:13:24,429 --> 01:13:26,110
He should have done ten years.

1605
01:13:26,194 --> 01:13:28,854
He kept Harold out
of the crash to gain his trust,

1606
01:13:28,938 --> 01:13:30,288
then stole the money.

1607
01:13:30,372 --> 01:13:32,223
And now he's trying to get more from us.

1608
01:13:32,307 --> 01:13:33,785
- You're sure of all this?
- Quite sure.

1609
01:13:33,869 --> 01:13:35,688
Bevan was a witness at the trial.

1610
01:13:35,772 --> 01:13:38,578
I'm going to speak to Mr. Sambrook.

1611
01:13:39,610 --> 01:13:41,263
What formidable daughters we have.

1612
01:13:41,347 --> 01:13:42,825
Have you only just noticed?

1613
01:13:42,909 --> 01:13:44,803
Tom, let's get you a drink.

1614
01:13:44,887 --> 01:13:46,883
You've earned it.

1615
01:13:49,657 --> 01:13:53,141
Are you surprised Sambrook's
turned out to be a bad'n?

1616
01:13:53,225 --> 01:13:55,046
I can't decide.

1617
01:13:55,130 --> 01:13:57,481
I feel sorry for Uncle Harold.

1618
01:13:57,565 --> 01:14:00,381
Sambrook could probably
have fooled any of us.

1619
01:14:00,465 --> 01:14:03,031
He certainly nearly fooled me.

1620
01:14:06,103 --> 01:14:08,953
I know you're not going back
to Downton tonight with Mama.

1621
01:14:09,037 --> 01:14:10,962
She said you want a second look at a house

1622
01:14:11,046 --> 01:14:13,074
you've found for us all.

1623
01:14:14,080 --> 01:14:15,425
Not a house.

1624
01:14:15,509 --> 01:14:16,814
A flat.

1625
01:14:20,651 --> 01:14:23,535
I might stay and come with you.

1626
01:14:23,619 --> 01:14:24,875
Would you like that?

1627
01:14:24,959 --> 01:14:27,243
Very much.

1628
01:14:27,327 --> 01:14:29,805
But please be open-minded.

1629
01:14:29,889 --> 01:14:31,849
You can be when you try.

1630
01:14:31,933 --> 01:14:33,930
I will try.

1631
01:14:35,101 --> 01:14:36,504
Very hard.

1632
01:14:42,642 --> 01:14:44,391
You have a horse in the next race?

1633
01:14:44,475 --> 01:14:45,645
That's right.

1634
01:14:46,773 --> 01:14:48,695
There she is.

1635
01:14:48,779 --> 01:14:50,379
I do hope you've enjoyed today...

1636
01:14:51,318 --> 01:14:53,500
...But please enlighten me.

1637
01:14:53,584 --> 01:14:55,173
I'm told you not only stole

1638
01:14:55,257 --> 01:14:57,005
the money Harold entrusted to you

1639
01:14:57,089 --> 01:15:00,344
but that you now plan to steal
what's left of Mama's estate.

1640
01:15:00,428 --> 01:15:03,074
And it's not the first time, is it?

1641
01:15:03,158 --> 01:15:05,448
I'm told you used the chaos after the crash

1642
01:15:05,532 --> 01:15:07,583
to cheat your way into a fortune.

1643
01:15:07,667 --> 01:15:09,847
I'm sure you know how preposterous that is.

1644
01:15:09,931 --> 01:15:11,590
Furthermore, according to some,

1645
01:15:11,674 --> 01:15:14,118
you were nearly convicted
of theft and fraud in New York.

1646
01:15:14,202 --> 01:15:16,059
I was not convicted.
I was found not guilty.

1647
01:15:16,143 --> 01:15:18,055
On a technicality.

1648
01:15:18,139 --> 01:15:20,530
Now Mary says you slept with her in London

1649
01:15:20,614 --> 01:15:23,426
and you're threatening to tell the world.

1650
01:15:23,510 --> 01:15:27,070
She doesn't care, of course--
Classic Mary-- but I care.

1651
01:15:27,154 --> 01:15:28,271
I didn't threaten.

1652
01:15:28,355 --> 01:15:29,635
I was joking.

1653
01:15:29,719 --> 01:15:31,301
She must have misunderstood.

1654
01:15:31,385 --> 01:15:33,237
I know you think we're all
much stupider than you.

1655
01:15:33,321 --> 01:15:35,546
- I've never suggested that.
- But I'm sure you realize

1656
01:15:35,630 --> 01:15:38,615
Lord Hexham and I have a little social power.

1657
01:15:38,699 --> 01:15:41,712
Maybe in a perfect world
we wouldn't, but we do.

1658
01:15:41,796 --> 01:15:43,721
What are you saying?

1659
01:15:43,805 --> 01:15:46,755
Only that if I hear of any
threat from you to my mother,

1660
01:15:46,839 --> 01:15:50,826
to my uncle, to my sister,
to anyone, in fact,

1661
01:15:50,910 --> 01:15:53,892
I promise Lord Hexham
will make you untouchable.

1662
01:15:53,976 --> 01:15:55,624
- You wouldn't do that.
- Wouldn't we?

1663
01:15:55,708 --> 01:15:57,331
Try us.

1664
01:15:59,216 --> 01:16:01,502
Then you have to find another
place for your playground.

1665
01:16:01,586 --> 01:16:04,333
England will be dead to you.

1666
01:16:04,417 --> 01:16:06,738
So the new contacts
you've been making all day

1667
01:16:06,822 --> 01:16:09,025
will avail you to nothing.

1668
01:16:09,989 --> 01:16:12,567
Have I made myself clear?

1669
01:16:14,661 --> 01:16:16,245
Oh, dear.

1670
01:16:16,329 --> 01:16:18,858
It's not your lucky day, is it, Mr. Sambrook?

1671
01:16:20,176 --> 01:16:22,154
Your race is about to begin.

1672
01:16:22,238 --> 01:16:24,324
Maybe your horse will turn
things around for you.

1673
01:16:46,893 --> 01:16:47,965
See that one!

1674
01:16:50,301 --> 01:16:51,936
Come on!

1675
01:17:03,809 --> 01:17:04,883
Come on.

1676
01:17:06,913 --> 01:17:08,447
Come on, Hasteway!

1677
01:17:12,986 --> 01:17:14,837
Come on, Hasteway, go!

1678
01:17:19,061 --> 01:17:21,514
Which one were you,
Mr. Sambrook?

1679
01:17:21,598 --> 01:17:23,421
The guy in spots.

1680
01:17:23,505 --> 01:17:26,740
Oh, well, better luck next time, eh?

1681
01:17:40,685 --> 01:17:42,237
I'm glad I found you.

1682
01:17:42,321 --> 01:17:44,038
I'm leaving,

1683
01:17:44,122 --> 01:17:47,003
and you're the only one
I wanted to say goodbye to.

1684
01:17:47,087 --> 01:17:49,514
Do you know what saddens me?

1685
01:17:49,598 --> 01:17:51,550
You probably don't even remember the names

1686
01:17:51,634 --> 01:17:53,517
of the men and women
whose lives you've ruined.

1687
01:17:53,601 --> 01:17:56,132
Well, I hope I haven't ruined yours.

1688
01:17:58,339 --> 01:18:00,354
Goodbye, Mr. Sambrook.

1689
01:18:32,237 --> 01:18:35,223
Oy, no one could say <i>The
Pickwick Papers</i> is too short.

1690
01:18:35,307 --> 01:18:36,594
No, sir.

1691
01:18:36,678 --> 01:18:39,288
Is there a murder mystery
I could read?

1692
01:18:39,372 --> 01:18:41,191
Agatha Christie, something like that?

1693
01:18:41,275 --> 01:18:43,047
There might be some in the nursery.

1694
01:18:46,080 --> 01:18:48,302
They're catching the last train,

1695
01:18:48,386 --> 01:18:51,644
so they don't want dinner, just
sandwiches and a glass of wine.

1696
01:18:51,728 --> 01:18:54,028
So, what's Mr. Levinson
gonna do with all this?

1697
01:18:55,488 --> 01:18:57,588
I should think he'll make light work of it.

1698
01:19:03,404 --> 01:19:05,102
This one over here.

1699
01:19:17,879 --> 01:19:19,061
Please come in.

1700
01:19:19,145 --> 01:19:20,302
Thank you.

1701
01:19:29,223 --> 01:19:32,583
So, this is how the world ends.

1702
01:19:32,667 --> 01:19:34,982
Not with a bang but with a whimper.

1703
01:19:35,066 --> 01:19:37,266
What's that?

1704
01:19:38,570 --> 01:19:40,225
I don't know.

1705
01:19:40,309 --> 01:19:41,699
The family upstairs.

1706
01:19:42,641 --> 01:19:44,559
"The family upstairs"?

1707
01:19:44,643 --> 01:19:46,693
What about downstairs?

1708
01:19:46,777 --> 01:19:48,399
Is a family there, too?

1709
01:19:48,483 --> 01:19:49,827
I don't know if it's a family.

1710
01:19:49,911 --> 01:19:51,360
How peculiar.

1711
01:19:51,444 --> 01:19:54,804
A sort of layer cake of strangers.

1712
01:19:54,888 --> 01:19:57,298
And what about when I want to go up to bed?

1713
01:19:57,382 --> 01:20:00,124
You don't go up. You go along.

1714
01:20:02,365 --> 01:20:04,392
Extraordinary.

1715
01:20:06,331 --> 01:20:10,984
Isn't it odd to live in
a building full of strangers?

1716
01:20:11,068 --> 01:20:12,917
You sleep in a house of strangers

1717
01:20:13,001 --> 01:20:14,989
at every shooting party.

1718
01:20:15,073 --> 01:20:17,659
I know you think
I've been holding you back.

1719
01:20:17,743 --> 01:20:20,032
- Well, I...
- You're right.

1720
01:20:20,116 --> 01:20:21,324
So is Tom.

1721
01:20:21,408 --> 01:20:24,098
I did encourage you to take control,

1722
01:20:24,182 --> 01:20:27,679
but it's hard to accept that it's time to go.

1723
01:20:29,319 --> 01:20:31,875
Families like ours
must keep moving to survive.

1724
01:20:31,959 --> 01:20:35,578
One day, George will say
it's time for me to go.

1725
01:20:35,662 --> 01:20:37,274
I won't be spared, either.

1726
01:20:37,358 --> 01:20:39,808
You're not very sentimental, are you?

1727
01:20:39,892 --> 01:20:42,554
The hereditary system
can't afford to be sentimental.

1728
01:20:42,638 --> 01:20:44,279
But now it's time to think of things

1729
01:20:44,363 --> 01:20:45,917
for you and Mama to enjoy.

1730
01:20:46,001 --> 01:20:48,787
More travel, more London.

1731
01:20:48,871 --> 01:20:50,292
No more Downton.

1732
01:20:50,376 --> 01:20:51,528
Nonsense.

1733
01:20:51,612 --> 01:20:53,365
You'll be the éminence grise,

1734
01:20:53,449 --> 01:20:55,958
the power behind the throne.

1735
01:20:56,042 --> 01:20:58,149
No, I won't.

1736
01:20:59,182 --> 01:21:01,856
You'll be the power on the throne.

1737
01:21:05,691 --> 01:21:06,872
Thank you.

1738
01:21:06,956 --> 01:21:08,439
We'll let you know...

1739
01:21:08,523 --> 01:21:11,140
If you can sell Grantham House,
we'll take it.

1740
01:21:11,224 --> 01:21:12,361
Very good, my lord.

1741
01:21:14,329 --> 01:21:16,247
If Lady Mary does take over,

1742
01:21:16,331 --> 01:21:18,048
will she want her parents to move out?

1743
01:21:18,132 --> 01:21:19,382
You'll have to ask her.

1744
01:21:19,466 --> 01:21:21,490
You mean you're not gonna tell me?

1745
01:21:21,574 --> 01:21:24,158
But is that right?

1746
01:21:24,242 --> 01:21:26,164
Should wives have secrets
from their husbands?

1747
01:21:26,248 --> 01:21:27,322
Definitely.

1748
01:21:27,406 --> 01:21:29,168
But not the other way around.

1749
01:21:31,479 --> 01:21:34,632
If they do go, where would that leave us,

1750
01:21:34,716 --> 01:21:38,538
with you working for Lady Mary
and me with His Lordship?

1751
01:21:40,721 --> 01:21:45,015
Whatever happens, we'll find
a way to make it work.

1752
01:21:45,099 --> 01:21:48,749
After all, we'll soon have
a new life to think of.

1753
01:21:48,833 --> 01:21:50,422
Very true, Mrs. Bates.

1754
01:21:52,869 --> 01:21:54,955
There they are.

1755
01:21:58,243 --> 01:22:00,662
We need to decide
who'll present the final cup

1756
01:22:00,746 --> 01:22:02,357
for the Local Hero.

1757
01:22:02,441 --> 01:22:04,100
Have you a candidate in mind?

1758
01:22:04,184 --> 01:22:05,763
I thought perhaps that
this year I might present it.

1759
01:22:05,847 --> 01:22:06,867
Oh, no.

1760
01:22:06,951 --> 01:22:08,401
We couldn't possibly ask you.

1761
01:22:08,417 --> 01:22:09,840
Not with everything else you have to do.

1762
01:22:09,924 --> 01:22:12,937
No, I thought I would ask
Lady Mary Talbot.

1763
01:22:13,021 --> 01:22:14,639
Definitely not.

1764
01:22:14,723 --> 01:22:18,113
She is known for her interest
in the future of farming.

1765
01:22:18,197 --> 01:22:20,280
She's also a divorcée
and a figure of scandal.

1766
01:22:20,364 --> 01:22:22,281
I should think her very presence at the show

1767
01:22:22,365 --> 01:22:24,690
would make most decent women feel uneasy.

1768
01:22:24,774 --> 01:22:26,615
Decent women are tougher than you think,

1769
01:22:26,699 --> 01:22:29,151
and marriages fail in the best society.

1770
01:22:29,235 --> 01:22:30,995
Ask Henry VIII.

1771
01:22:31,079 --> 01:22:33,730
I see. So we're living in
a moral cesspit now, are we?

1772
01:22:33,814 --> 01:22:35,490
Lady Mary Talbot is a responsible,

1773
01:22:35,574 --> 01:22:37,293
intelligent and generous woman.

1774
01:22:37,377 --> 01:22:39,669
We would be lucky to have her.

1775
01:22:39,753 --> 01:22:41,066
Don't you agree, Mrs. Parker?

1776
01:22:41,150 --> 01:22:42,550
Well, I work in the kitchen,

1777
01:22:42,616 --> 01:22:44,137
so I don't know her as Mr. Carson does,

1778
01:22:44,221 --> 01:22:45,468
but I haven't got any complaints.

1779
01:22:45,552 --> 01:22:47,202
I'm not interested in the opinions

1780
01:22:47,260 --> 01:22:49,978
of a toadying kitchen maid
or a bootlicking butler,

1781
01:22:50,062 --> 01:22:51,675
and it will be a cold day in hell

1782
01:22:51,759 --> 01:22:54,309
before Lady Merton's divorced
ex-daughter-in-law

1783
01:22:54,393 --> 01:22:57,070
gives away our prizes.

1784
01:22:58,597 --> 01:23:01,823
Please, say what you really think.

1785
01:23:01,907 --> 01:23:03,901
I doubt you're ready for that.

1786
01:23:04,906 --> 01:23:06,310
Humph.

1787
01:23:15,514 --> 01:23:17,408
Never leave me alone with him.

1788
01:23:17,492 --> 01:23:18,936
I'm not much help.

1789
01:23:19,020 --> 01:23:21,237
He hates me.

1790
01:23:21,321 --> 01:23:23,162
But you're a great help.

1791
01:23:26,461 --> 01:23:30,019
Oh, you should have rung, milady.

1792
01:23:30,103 --> 01:23:31,280
I wanted to ask if everything's ready

1793
01:23:31,364 --> 01:23:32,947
for Mr. Coward's dinner.

1794
01:23:33,031 --> 01:23:35,631
If Daisy cooked blindfold
for the king in his palace,

1795
01:23:35,677 --> 01:23:36,992
she'd not let anyone down.

1796
01:23:37,076 --> 01:23:39,558
High praise from you,
Mrs. Patmore.

1797
01:23:39,642 --> 01:23:42,733
Only it's our first party
since Lady Mary's troubles,

1798
01:23:42,817 --> 01:23:44,702
and I do want it to be a success.

1799
01:23:44,786 --> 01:23:47,101
But she didn't come back with you?

1800
01:23:47,185 --> 01:23:48,531
She's showing His Lordship a flat.

1801
01:23:48,615 --> 01:23:51,209
Oh, th-that sounds like a big step.

1802
01:23:51,293 --> 01:23:52,977
It is.

1803
01:23:53,061 --> 01:23:54,940
Might we have tea
on the terrace, do you think?

1804
01:23:55,024 --> 01:23:56,690
Of course, milady.

1805
01:24:02,502 --> 01:24:04,051
Um...

1806
01:24:04,135 --> 01:24:06,919
It's a big step for me and all.

1807
01:24:07,003 --> 01:24:08,987
Oh. Retiring?

1808
01:24:09,071 --> 01:24:10,919
After 50 years

1809
01:24:11,003 --> 01:24:13,662
and going to live
in your cottage with Mr. Mason.

1810
01:24:13,746 --> 01:24:15,097
I should think so.

1811
01:24:15,181 --> 01:24:18,326
Mm, no. That's-that's not what I meant.

1812
01:24:18,410 --> 01:24:19,468
What did you mean?

1813
01:24:21,084 --> 01:24:22,332
Well, you're right.

1814
01:24:22,416 --> 01:24:24,772
I've never lived with Mr. Mason.

1815
01:24:24,856 --> 01:24:27,886
Not... properly.

1816
01:24:29,628 --> 01:24:31,263
Not yet.

1817
01:24:32,224 --> 01:24:33,581
Oh.

1818
01:24:33,665 --> 01:24:35,185
I see.

1819
01:24:35,269 --> 01:24:37,654
And I wondered,
since you sent me to Mr. Carson

1820
01:24:37,738 --> 01:24:38,955
all that time ago...

1821
01:24:39,039 --> 01:24:41,426
I'm not going to question
Mr. Mason.

1822
01:24:41,510 --> 01:24:43,961
Only I'm nervous.

1823
01:24:44,045 --> 01:24:46,326
If he should want us to...
You know, uh...

1824
01:24:46,410 --> 01:24:49,028
And from what he's said,
I think he might.

1825
01:24:49,112 --> 01:24:51,500
You mustn't be nervous.

1826
01:24:51,584 --> 01:24:52,527
Why not?

1827
01:24:52,611 --> 01:24:54,979
Because I'll tell you one thing.

1828
01:24:56,118 --> 01:24:58,839
It's terrific fun.

1829
01:25:04,294 --> 01:25:05,957
Oh, yes.

1830
01:25:06,964 --> 01:25:08,182
Are you sure?

1831
01:25:08,266 --> 01:25:09,846
Tom knows what he's talking about.

1832
01:25:09,930 --> 01:25:12,991
If Sambrook isn't a convicted
felon, he should be.

1833
01:25:13,075 --> 01:25:15,124
How did he convince you to part with so much?

1834
01:25:15,208 --> 01:25:18,541
It was the Argentinian currency.

1835
01:25:19,873 --> 01:25:22,366
Gus said the exchange rates
from gold to paper

1836
01:25:22,450 --> 01:25:26,233
offered by the Banco de Córdoba
were yielding far higher profits

1837
01:25:26,317 --> 01:25:28,134
than anything on the stock market.

1838
01:25:28,218 --> 01:25:30,241
And you took his word for it?

1839
01:25:30,325 --> 01:25:32,306
Well, he was very convincing,
so I gave him the money

1840
01:25:32,390 --> 01:25:34,340
to put into the company making the deal.

1841
01:25:35,161 --> 01:25:36,708
But shortly afterwards, he told me

1842
01:25:36,792 --> 01:25:38,674
the company had collapsed
and all the money was gone.

1843
01:25:38,758 --> 01:25:40,852
Who knows if there was a company?

1844
01:25:40,936 --> 01:25:42,649
But we can be sure

1845
01:25:42,733 --> 01:25:44,713
that the money made its way
into Mr. Sambrook's pockets.

1846
01:25:44,797 --> 01:25:46,858
Why did you bring him to England?

1847
01:25:46,942 --> 01:25:48,483
Well, he had his horse, as you know,

1848
01:25:48,567 --> 01:25:50,995
and he said if we...

1849
01:25:51,079 --> 01:25:52,928
Persuaded Cora to give us what was left,

1850
01:25:53,012 --> 01:25:54,896
he'd double the amount I'd lost.

1851
01:25:54,980 --> 01:25:56,530
Can we take him to law?

1852
01:25:56,614 --> 01:25:59,905
Prosecution in this sort
of case is notoriously hard.

1853
01:25:59,989 --> 01:26:01,771
After all,
Harold agreed to everything.

1854
01:26:01,855 --> 01:26:04,105
I'm afraid it's gone.

1855
01:26:04,189 --> 01:26:06,402
I can't believe I was so naive.

1856
01:26:08,323 --> 01:26:10,246
Oh, here they are now.

1857
01:26:10,330 --> 01:26:12,411
Well, you must be worn out
after your journey.

1858
01:26:12,495 --> 01:26:14,884
- I am.
- Well, Robert, how was it?

1859
01:26:14,968 --> 01:26:16,715
Are you all right, Uncle Harold?

1860
01:26:16,799 --> 01:26:19,220
Not when I've been
as big a fool as a man can be.

1861
01:26:19,304 --> 01:26:22,024
Mm. It was rather a shock to us all.

1862
01:26:22,108 --> 01:26:23,722
We'll find a way to cheer you up.

1863
01:26:23,806 --> 01:26:25,724
Some neighbors are coming
for dinner before the show.

1864
01:26:25,808 --> 01:26:28,225
Won't they take one look at me
and run for the hills?

1865
01:26:28,309 --> 01:26:29,467
Don't be silly.

1866
01:26:37,350 --> 01:26:39,116
Thank you.

1867
01:26:43,227 --> 01:26:46,050
The stately homes of England.

1868
01:26:46,134 --> 01:26:48,829
How beautiful they stand.

1869
01:26:50,035 --> 01:26:51,634
Where are you going?

1870
01:26:52,701 --> 01:26:55,223
In this house, my place is in the kitchens.

1871
01:26:55,307 --> 01:26:57,640
Well, then we'll all go together.

1872
01:27:05,744 --> 01:27:07,772
- Good afternoon.
- Oh, Thomas.

1873
01:27:09,355 --> 01:27:11,338
- Oh, Mr. Dexter.
- Hello.

1874
01:27:11,422 --> 01:27:13,909
Mr. Coward, this is a great honor.

1875
01:27:13,993 --> 01:27:15,376
Not at all.

1876
01:27:15,460 --> 01:27:17,280
We had to meet Thomas's partners in crime.

1877
01:27:17,364 --> 01:27:20,080
You should say hello
to Lord and Lady Grantham.

1878
01:27:20,164 --> 01:27:21,916
Did you work with Thomas?

1879
01:27:22,000 --> 01:27:23,018
I did.

1880
01:27:23,102 --> 01:27:24,787
Mr. Parker has just started.

1881
01:27:24,871 --> 01:27:26,122
As the butler.

1882
01:27:26,206 --> 01:27:27,985
So you've retired now,
Mr. Carson?

1883
01:27:28,069 --> 01:27:30,359
Well, you wouldn't think it
from the time he spends here.

1884
01:27:30,443 --> 01:27:32,664
At least you're still around,
Mrs. Patmore.

1885
01:27:32,748 --> 01:27:34,525
Oh, only until now.

1886
01:27:34,609 --> 01:27:36,959
Daisy's cooking dinner tonight.

1887
01:27:37,043 --> 01:27:39,035
By tomorrow morning,
I'll have retired as well.

1888
01:27:39,119 --> 01:27:40,700
So bring your complaints to me.

1889
01:27:40,784 --> 01:27:42,939
What a merry-go-round.

1890
01:27:43,023 --> 01:27:44,536
Daisy, you look very familiar.

1891
01:27:44,620 --> 01:27:46,876
- I'm sure I don't.
- Yes, you do.

1892
01:27:46,960 --> 01:27:48,394
Very familiar indeed.

1893
01:27:49,225 --> 01:27:51,277
You should go up.

1894
01:27:51,361 --> 01:27:53,010
And you're staying down here?

1895
01:27:53,094 --> 01:27:56,347
Well, we can't change how
England works in one afternoon.

1896
01:27:56,431 --> 01:27:57,682
We'll see about that.

1897
01:28:00,274 --> 01:28:01,682
They'll be in the music room at 8:00.

1898
01:28:01,766 --> 01:28:03,795
I'll let Mr. Dexter know.

1899
01:28:03,879 --> 01:28:06,059
Goodness.

1900
01:28:06,143 --> 01:28:07,526
Have they arrived?

1901
01:28:07,610 --> 01:28:08,900
Mr. Molesley, you're in good time.

1902
01:28:08,984 --> 01:28:09,965
You've just missed them.

1903
01:28:10,049 --> 01:28:11,898
Mr. Dexter remembered me.

1904
01:28:11,982 --> 01:28:14,671
Well, I look forward to him
introducing me to Noël Coward.

1905
01:28:25,261 --> 01:28:27,609
Oh, I'm so sorry.

1906
01:28:27,693 --> 01:28:29,216
I must have miscounted.

1907
01:28:29,300 --> 01:28:30,650
I thought this was my room.

1908
01:28:30,729 --> 01:28:32,224
I don't believe so.

1909
01:28:32,308 --> 01:28:34,892
Unless they're planning
a cozy night for us both.

1910
01:28:34,976 --> 01:28:36,888
Oh. Mr. Coward.

1911
01:28:36,972 --> 01:28:39,424
You know, it's good of you
to come all this way.

1912
01:28:39,508 --> 01:28:41,059
It'll make a real difference.

1913
01:28:41,143 --> 01:28:42,426
Oh?

1914
01:28:42,510 --> 01:28:43,935
Oh, to Mary's rebirth.

1915
01:28:44,019 --> 01:28:46,100
Was she punished for her divorce?

1916
01:28:46,184 --> 01:28:47,734
It hasn't been easy,

1917
01:28:47,818 --> 01:28:49,707
but you're about to make it
a whole lot easier.

1918
01:28:49,791 --> 01:28:51,009
That's my role.

1919
01:28:51,093 --> 01:28:52,905
To spread sunshine wherever I go.

1920
01:28:52,989 --> 01:28:56,276
Edith tells me no one can refuse
the chance of meeting you.

1921
01:28:56,360 --> 01:28:57,510
The sprat to catch the mackerel.

1922
01:28:57,594 --> 01:28:59,630
Mm, the mackerel to catch the sprats.

1923
01:29:00,593 --> 01:29:01,883
See you at dinner.

1924
01:29:10,612 --> 01:29:12,005
Milady.

1925
01:29:17,117 --> 01:29:18,729
What are these?

1926
01:29:18,813 --> 01:29:21,146
I wanted ideas for the Dower House.

1927
01:29:22,118 --> 01:29:23,456
Really?

1928
01:29:24,453 --> 01:29:25,609
You may want to sit down.

1929
01:29:27,025 --> 01:29:28,692
If you like.

1930
01:29:30,593 --> 01:29:32,531
But I'm not going to fight you.

1931
01:29:33,393 --> 01:29:34,413
On what?

1932
01:29:34,497 --> 01:29:36,447
Our moving into the Dower House.

1933
01:29:36,531 --> 01:29:38,215
That is a surprise.

1934
01:29:38,299 --> 01:29:39,416
Why?

1935
01:29:39,500 --> 01:29:41,056
It's a good idea.

1936
01:29:41,140 --> 01:29:42,386
When will it be ready?

1937
01:29:42,470 --> 01:29:43,955
It's ready now.

1938
01:29:44,039 --> 01:29:46,389
I've had it cleaned
and put all the things back.

1939
01:29:46,907 --> 01:29:48,929
Oh. You have been busy.

1940
01:29:49,013 --> 01:29:50,732
I have,

1941
01:29:50,816 --> 01:29:52,836
and your understanding makes
things a great deal easier.

1942
01:29:54,685 --> 01:29:56,571
I'd say my favorite is Madeleine Carroll.

1943
01:29:56,655 --> 01:29:59,109
She's never let the stardom go to her head.

1944
01:29:59,193 --> 01:30:00,971
I saw her in <i>American Prisoner.</i>

1945
01:30:01,055 --> 01:30:03,814
Mm. We talk about England
whenever we're together.

1946
01:30:03,898 --> 01:30:04,839
The three of us.

1947
01:30:04,923 --> 01:30:06,780
And Miss Dalgleish, is she well?

1948
01:30:06,864 --> 01:30:09,615
Yes, but she doesn't mingle
with the English much.

1949
01:30:09,699 --> 01:30:12,583
She has been reborn as an American.

1950
01:30:12,667 --> 01:30:14,992
Do you dine with these people?

1951
01:30:15,076 --> 01:30:16,821
Of course I do, Mr. Carson.

1952
01:30:16,905 --> 01:30:18,028
It's a bit unconventional,
Mr. Barrow.

1953
01:30:18,112 --> 01:30:19,827
You can allow Mr. Carson that.

1954
01:30:19,911 --> 01:30:23,760
I suppose actors and servants
are not so very far removed.

1955
01:30:23,844 --> 01:30:25,434
Mr. Barrow isn't a servant now.

1956
01:30:25,518 --> 01:30:26,696
Well, I'm still the organizer.

1957
01:30:26,780 --> 01:30:28,829
I make sure things run smoothly.

1958
01:30:28,913 --> 01:30:30,205
What would you call that?

1959
01:30:30,289 --> 01:30:31,840
I've got a few suggestions.

1960
01:30:31,924 --> 01:30:32,867
Charlie.

1961
01:30:32,951 --> 01:30:34,551
I'd better get back to the duck.

1962
01:30:41,267 --> 01:30:43,153
Good. You look just right.

1963
01:30:43,237 --> 01:30:45,447
Are you checking before I go down?

1964
01:30:45,531 --> 01:30:47,018
Maybe.

1965
01:30:47,102 --> 01:30:49,457
I didn't want any trace
of sackcloth and ashes.

1966
01:30:49,541 --> 01:30:51,126
You mean you're trying to relaunch me

1967
01:30:51,210 --> 01:30:53,190
as socially desirable?

1968
01:30:53,274 --> 01:30:57,125
Why are you always in a contest
for who wins the prize?

1969
01:30:57,209 --> 01:30:59,599
You're much tougher than you used to be.

1970
01:30:59,683 --> 01:31:02,505
Has being a great lady given you armor?

1971
01:31:02,589 --> 01:31:05,473
So you could force Sambrook
not to cheat Mama?

1972
01:31:05,557 --> 01:31:08,277
I almost feel sorry for him.
Almost.

1973
01:31:08,361 --> 01:31:10,411
You can't be grateful, can you?

1974
01:31:10,495 --> 01:31:12,742
Ooh. Are we going to have a fight?

1975
01:31:12,826 --> 01:31:14,075
There's no point fighting you.

1976
01:31:14,159 --> 01:31:15,766
You never admit when you've lost.

1977
01:31:16,762 --> 01:31:18,981
I'll admit it now.

1978
01:31:19,065 --> 01:31:22,150
I've been very lost for a while...

1979
01:31:22,234 --> 01:31:24,896
But I think I'm coming out of it at last.

1980
01:31:24,980 --> 01:31:27,025
Thank God for that.

1981
01:31:27,109 --> 01:31:29,864
A perfect martini is made
by filling a glass with gin

1982
01:31:29,948 --> 01:31:32,396
and then waving it in
the general direction of Italy.

1983
01:31:35,650 --> 01:31:37,100
- Mr. Levinson.
- Oh.

1984
01:31:37,184 --> 01:31:39,444
No, no, no, these things
really are delicious.

1985
01:31:39,528 --> 01:31:42,028
- Never too early for a cocktail.
- Finally.

1986
01:31:42,495 --> 01:31:43,709
What's Molesley doing here?

1987
01:31:43,793 --> 01:31:45,443
Isn't he writing films these days?

1988
01:31:45,526 --> 01:31:47,011
Search me.

1989
01:31:47,095 --> 01:31:49,445
- Who knows?
- Lady Mary.

1990
01:31:50,005 --> 01:31:51,520
Come and meet Noël.

1991
01:31:51,604 --> 01:31:53,720
Oh, I thought it was just a few locals.

1992
01:31:53,804 --> 01:31:55,693
It's so good of you to come all this way.

1993
01:31:55,777 --> 01:31:59,794
It's wonderful to be back here
and to see you looking so well.

1994
01:31:59,878 --> 01:32:03,395
I was talking earlier to
your uncle about your divorce.

1995
01:32:03,479 --> 01:32:05,228
What happened?

1996
01:32:05,312 --> 01:32:07,368
Well, I doubt I'll be asked
that again tonight.

1997
01:32:07,452 --> 01:32:09,740
Or is it research for a play?

1998
01:32:09,824 --> 01:32:11,199
Maybe.

1999
01:32:11,283 --> 01:32:12,976
But don't worry if you'd rather not say.

2000
01:32:13,060 --> 01:32:14,275
No, I'll say.

2001
01:32:14,359 --> 01:32:16,211
We fought like cats.

2002
01:32:16,295 --> 01:32:18,406
He wanted to be kingpin,

2003
01:32:18,490 --> 01:32:20,984
but I was the heiress
and he was just the husband.

2004
01:32:21,068 --> 01:32:22,447
He hated that.

2005
01:32:22,531 --> 01:32:24,118
How intriguing.

2006
01:32:29,136 --> 01:32:31,292
Mr. Coward must be used to being served

2007
01:32:31,376 --> 01:32:32,826
the best food in England.

2008
01:32:32,910 --> 01:32:34,463
Maybe, but Mr. Molesley read in <i>Picturegoer</i>

2009
01:32:34,547 --> 01:32:36,397
that his favorite is bangers and mash.

2010
01:32:36,417 --> 01:32:37,930
Well, tonight he's getting

2011
01:32:38,014 --> 01:32:38,827
coquilles Saint Jacques and Gressingham duck,

2012
01:32:38,911 --> 01:32:40,818
and he better like it.

2013
01:32:44,491 --> 01:32:47,469
Mr. Coward, can you say what's next?

2014
01:32:47,553 --> 01:32:49,977
- I have an idea for a sort
of spectacle with music.
- Mm.

2015
01:32:50,061 --> 01:32:51,745
With the <i>Titanic</i> on stage...

2016
01:32:51,829 --> 01:32:53,348
...and the world in the grip of the war.

2017
01:32:53,432 --> 01:32:55,683
Oh, I like the sound of that.

2018
01:32:55,767 --> 01:32:57,717
Uh, two of my cousins died on the <i>Titanic,</i>

2019
01:32:57,801 --> 01:32:59,456
so I may find it hard to sing along.

2020
01:32:59,540 --> 01:33:01,640
But we all lost people we loved in the war,

2021
01:33:01,708 --> 01:33:04,194
and yet wonderful plays have come out of it.

2022
01:33:04,278 --> 01:33:05,790
I'm sure you'll have a long run.

2023
01:33:05,874 --> 01:33:07,493
Oh, no. Noël hates long runs.

2024
01:33:07,577 --> 01:33:08,927
Only if I'm in them.

2025
01:33:09,011 --> 01:33:10,134
Three months, then on to the next thing.

2026
01:33:10,218 --> 01:33:11,695
- That's my way.
- Hmm.

2027
01:33:11,779 --> 01:33:13,202
- Excuse me.
- Oh.

2028
01:33:15,621 --> 01:33:17,902
I suppose this is all your doing.

2029
01:33:17,986 --> 01:33:21,122
Mine and Mama's, and Anna helped, too.

2030
01:33:22,188 --> 01:33:23,546
All to bring me in from the cold.

2031
01:33:23,630 --> 01:33:27,047
To show you still have a life in Yorkshire.

2032
01:33:27,131 --> 01:33:30,230
And with patience, you can
have one in London again, too.

2033
01:33:31,271 --> 01:33:33,615
I am very grateful.

2034
01:33:33,699 --> 01:33:35,223
Don't be.

2035
01:33:35,307 --> 01:33:37,105
You're my sister.

2036
01:33:39,378 --> 01:33:40,812
- I'm gonna...
- Bye.

2037
01:33:41,876 --> 01:33:43,650
- Ah.
- Thanks, old boy.

2038
01:33:48,653 --> 01:33:50,705
- Hurry up.
- Yes, Mrs. Parker.

2039
01:33:50,789 --> 01:33:53,102
There's lots to do.
I'm relying on you.

2040
01:33:53,186 --> 01:33:55,579
- Now quarter the melon.
- Right away.

2041
01:33:55,663 --> 01:33:58,013
They won't eat it, but make it look nice.

2042
01:33:58,056 --> 01:33:59,406
I hope your presence here

2043
01:33:59,490 --> 01:34:01,313
means you have happy memories of Downton.

2044
01:34:01,397 --> 01:34:02,647
Very.

2045
01:34:02,731 --> 01:34:05,017
Downton changed my life.

2046
01:34:05,101 --> 01:34:06,717
- I'm glad.
- I don't get it.

2047
01:34:06,801 --> 01:34:08,259
He's playing with me.

2048
01:34:08,343 --> 01:34:09,893
He's pretending not to know me.

2049
01:34:11,171 --> 01:34:13,424
I don't approve of long speeches,

2050
01:34:13,508 --> 01:34:16,929
you'll be happy to hear, but I
couldn't let this evening pass

2051
01:34:17,013 --> 01:34:20,231
without some thanks to you all for coming.

2052
01:34:20,315 --> 01:34:24,576
Mary has been through
some testing times lately,

2053
01:34:24,660 --> 01:34:28,378
and your friendship
has never meant more to her,

2054
01:34:28,462 --> 01:34:31,074
to all of us, than it does now.

2055
01:34:31,158 --> 01:34:34,176
You should know that from now on,

2056
01:34:34,260 --> 01:34:36,120
she will be the mistress of Downton.

2057
01:34:36,204 --> 01:34:38,489
You may even be glad

2058
01:34:38,573 --> 01:34:40,349
since you will no longer be dealing with me.

2059
01:34:40,433 --> 01:34:42,550
Cora and I have decided

2060
01:34:42,634 --> 01:34:46,595
to move into the Dower House
while Mary presides here.

2061
01:34:46,679 --> 01:34:49,926
She knows this estate better than I do

2062
01:34:50,010 --> 01:34:51,863
and loves it quite as much.

2063
01:34:51,947 --> 01:34:54,704
I can promise with all my heart

2064
01:34:54,788 --> 01:34:57,307
that she is more than worthy of the position

2065
01:34:57,391 --> 01:34:59,070
that she has been called to.

2066
01:34:59,154 --> 01:35:01,641
You've been good neighbors to Cora and me,

2067
01:35:01,725 --> 01:35:03,578
and I hope you still will be,

2068
01:35:03,662 --> 01:35:06,551
but the future of Downton Abbey

2069
01:35:06,635 --> 01:35:10,154
is now in Mary's and, later,
George's hands.

2070
01:35:10,238 --> 01:35:11,948
May God bless them.

2071
01:35:12,032 --> 01:35:15,368
I give you Mary and George.

2072
01:35:16,805 --> 01:35:19,504
Mary and George.

2073
01:35:20,846 --> 01:35:22,896
- That was marvelous.
- Well done, Robert.

2074
01:35:24,308 --> 01:35:26,736
Now let's go through together.

2075
01:35:26,820 --> 01:35:28,835
All this Queen Mary talk
kind of makes you forget

2076
01:35:28,919 --> 01:35:31,417
her grandfather was in dry goods.

2077
01:35:33,484 --> 01:35:34,805
Can I help you with anything more, sir?

2078
01:35:34,889 --> 01:35:36,139
Haven't we all finished?

2079
01:35:36,223 --> 01:35:37,981
I expect you're puzzled to see me.

2080
01:35:38,065 --> 01:35:39,512
Uh...

2081
01:35:39,596 --> 01:35:41,149
Joseph Molesley.

2082
01:35:41,233 --> 01:35:42,944
I...

2083
01:35:43,028 --> 01:35:44,682
I wrote the film.

2084
01:35:44,766 --> 01:35:45,917
Oh, of course.

2085
01:35:46,001 --> 01:35:48,368
But you're a footman again now.

2086
01:35:49,343 --> 01:35:50,425
Never mind, old chap.

2087
01:35:50,509 --> 01:35:51,854
It's a fickle business.

2088
01:35:51,938 --> 01:35:53,912
- Oh...
- Guy.

2089
01:35:55,108 --> 01:35:57,596
Go and invite Barrow to join us.

2090
01:35:57,680 --> 01:35:59,294
What? Upstairs?

2091
01:35:59,378 --> 01:36:01,300
Oh, he doesn't work here anymore,

2092
01:36:01,384 --> 01:36:05,043
and for you, he's clearly
more a friend than a servant.

2093
01:36:05,127 --> 01:36:06,844
You're right.

2094
01:36:06,928 --> 01:36:09,438
The old divisions don't seem
to mean as much as they did.

2095
01:36:09,522 --> 01:36:11,930
I'm not convinced
they ever meant much to you.

2096
01:36:12,927 --> 01:36:14,611
Can I come with you?

2097
01:36:14,695 --> 01:36:15,849
Why?

2098
01:36:15,933 --> 01:36:17,783
Well, he wants to see their faces

2099
01:36:17,867 --> 01:36:19,630
when you make the suggestion.

2100
01:36:20,604 --> 01:36:22,086
This way, Noël.

2101
01:36:22,170 --> 01:36:23,558
All I wanted was to meet Mr. Coward,

2102
01:36:23,642 --> 01:36:24,889
and now he thinks I'm a footman.

2103
01:36:24,973 --> 01:36:26,021
The last supper.

2104
01:36:26,105 --> 01:36:28,309
Oh, no, don't get up.

2105
01:36:29,977 --> 01:36:32,503
Thomas, Lady Mary wonders

2106
01:36:32,587 --> 01:36:35,118
if you'd like some coffee or a drink.

2107
01:36:39,795 --> 01:36:44,457
Lady Mary wants Mr. Barrow
to join her upstairs?

2108
01:36:45,466 --> 01:36:46,980
Well, he doesn't work here

2109
01:36:47,064 --> 01:36:49,594
and he's in the house now as a pal of mine.

2110
01:36:51,139 --> 01:36:52,855
That's true.

2111
01:36:52,939 --> 01:36:55,189
This really is the night
that shook the world.

2112
01:36:55,241 --> 01:36:56,417
Oh.

2113
01:36:56,501 --> 01:36:58,153
I suppose you think
Lady Mary's lost

2114
01:36:58,237 --> 01:37:00,722
her moral compass, Mr. Carson.

2115
01:37:00,806 --> 01:37:04,763
Perhaps we should all have
a different compass these days.

2116
01:37:04,847 --> 01:37:07,315
Well, are you coming?

2117
01:37:08,488 --> 01:37:10,240
Do you think I should?

2118
01:37:10,324 --> 01:37:11,868
I certainly do.

2119
01:37:14,590 --> 01:37:15,862
Right.

2120
01:37:24,735 --> 01:37:26,587
Cheer up, Mr. Molesley.

2121
01:37:26,671 --> 01:37:27,888
You've a good marriage.

2122
01:37:27,972 --> 01:37:28,853
You're a successful screenwriter.

2123
01:37:28,937 --> 01:37:30,694
Isn't that something?

2124
01:37:30,778 --> 01:37:33,427
Wait a minute.
So, you wrote <i>The Gambler?</i>

2125
01:37:33,511 --> 01:37:35,223
I did, yes.

2126
01:37:35,307 --> 01:37:36,899
Well, you were lucky with Guy.

2127
01:37:36,983 --> 01:37:38,732
Writers can wait years before they get a cast

2128
01:37:38,816 --> 01:37:40,204
that shows them at their best.

2129
01:37:40,288 --> 01:37:42,039
I-I do know that,

2130
01:37:42,123 --> 01:37:44,440
and I know that it's an honor
to have you here, Mr. Coward.

2131
01:37:44,524 --> 01:37:46,204
Oh.

2132
01:37:46,288 --> 01:37:47,907
I don't understand, if you're a writer,

2133
01:37:47,991 --> 01:37:50,744
then why are you a footman now?

2134
01:37:50,828 --> 01:37:53,179
Oh. It's a... it's a long story.

2135
01:37:53,263 --> 01:37:55,110
I hope you've enjoyed your stay at Downton.

2136
01:37:55,194 --> 01:37:56,529
Certainly.

2137
01:37:57,804 --> 01:37:59,404
And Lady Mary's given me an idea.

2138
01:37:59,472 --> 01:38:00,790
What do you mean?

2139
01:38:00,874 --> 01:38:02,450
Well, she was talking about her divorce,

2140
01:38:02,534 --> 01:38:04,460
and I can see the play in my head.

2141
01:38:04,544 --> 01:38:07,062
Oh, but is it right?

2142
01:38:07,146 --> 01:38:10,048
To use what people confide
about their private lives?

2143
01:38:11,847 --> 01:38:13,843
Private lives.

2144
01:38:14,849 --> 01:38:16,164
Very good.

2145
01:38:16,248 --> 01:38:18,254
Thank you, Mr. Molesley.

2146
01:38:19,261 --> 01:38:20,388
I'm grateful.

2147
01:38:21,396 --> 01:38:23,028
Until the next time.

2148
01:38:29,529 --> 01:38:32,190
But, Joseph, you've made a good life for us.

2149
01:38:32,274 --> 01:38:34,118
A lovely life.

2150
01:38:34,202 --> 01:38:37,108
Won't you please let us be happy?

2151
01:38:38,105 --> 01:38:40,297
I will try. I promise.

2152
01:38:40,381 --> 01:38:42,443
That's all I ask.

2153
01:38:48,246 --> 01:38:50,204
Are you all right?

2154
01:38:50,288 --> 01:38:52,542
I wish I was in the right clothes.

2155
01:38:52,626 --> 01:38:54,719
They look perfectly right to me.

2156
01:38:59,592 --> 01:39:01,142
- Good Lord.
- Who is that?

2157
01:39:01,226 --> 01:39:02,882
Is that Barrow?

2158
01:39:02,966 --> 01:39:04,729
Oh.

2159
01:39:05,796 --> 01:39:08,159
Yes, and you're not to make a thing of it.

2160
01:39:08,243 --> 01:39:10,075
Thank you.

2161
01:39:11,305 --> 01:39:13,688
They're very informal.

2162
01:39:13,772 --> 01:39:16,444
I suppose that comes with living in America.

2163
01:39:18,577 --> 01:39:21,066
We're all looking forward to the show.

2164
01:39:21,150 --> 01:39:22,450
Oh, I hope it's one

2165
01:39:22,515 --> 01:39:24,204
that Violet would have been proud of.

2166
01:39:24,288 --> 01:39:26,339
I feel it's the last thing
I could do for her.

2167
01:39:26,423 --> 01:39:28,471
She terrified the daylights out of me. -

2168
01:39:28,555 --> 01:39:31,713
Maybe, but in truth, she was kinder, funnier,

2169
01:39:31,797 --> 01:39:34,347
wiser than most people knew.

2170
01:39:34,431 --> 01:39:36,014
- Quite irreplaceable.
- Oh, I don't agree.

2171
01:39:36,098 --> 01:39:38,248
I think Mary will replace her,

2172
01:39:38,332 --> 01:39:40,317
- if she hasn't already.
- Mm.

2173
01:39:40,401 --> 01:39:41,856
I do wish you'd sing for us, Noël.

2174
01:39:41,940 --> 01:39:43,661
I never need to be asked twice.

2175
01:39:43,745 --> 01:39:45,557
Wonderful.
Should we gather round?

2176
01:39:45,641 --> 01:39:48,344
Noël's going to sing something for us. -

2177
01:39:49,309 --> 01:39:51,566
- Oh, Mr. Branson.
- Thomas.

2178
01:39:51,650 --> 01:39:53,448
Good to see you.

2179
01:39:55,755 --> 01:39:58,816
♪ Poor little rich girl ♪

2180
01:40:00,090 --> 01:40:02,678
♪ You're a bewitched girl ♪

2181
01:40:02,762 --> 01:40:04,446
♪ Better take care ♪

2182
01:40:10,495 --> 01:40:13,447
♪ Laughing at danger ♪

2183
01:40:13,531 --> 01:40:16,020
♪ Virtue a stranger ♪

2184
01:40:16,104 --> 01:40:17,693
♪ Better beware ♪

2185
01:40:17,777 --> 01:40:20,596
Is this funny or impertinent?

2186
01:40:20,680 --> 01:40:22,396
Find it funny, please.

2187
01:40:22,480 --> 01:40:27,203
♪ The life you lead
sets all your nerves a-jangle ♪

2188
01:40:27,287 --> 01:40:29,430
♪ Your love affairs are in ♪

2189
01:40:29,514 --> 01:40:32,138
♪ A hopeless tangle ♪

2190
01:40:32,222 --> 01:40:35,075
♪ Though you're a child, dear ♪

2191
01:40:35,159 --> 01:40:39,946
♪ Your life's a wild typhoon ♪

2192
01:40:42,362 --> 01:40:44,513
♪ Poor little rich girl ♪

2193
01:40:44,597 --> 01:40:49,650
♪ Don't drop a stitch too soon ♪

2194
01:40:49,734 --> 01:40:52,474
Very good, Mr. Coward.
Very good.

2195
01:40:53,978 --> 01:40:56,830
♪ You're only a baby ♪

2196
01:40:56,914 --> 01:40:58,869
♪ You're lonely ♪

2197
01:40:58,953 --> 01:41:03,683
♪ And maybe someday soon you'll know ♪

2198
01:41:04,925 --> 01:41:08,108
♪ The tears you are tasting ♪

2199
01:41:08,192 --> 01:41:11,010
♪ Are years you are wasting ♪

2200
01:41:11,094 --> 01:41:15,662
♪ Life's a bitter foe ♪

2201
01:41:18,303 --> 01:41:20,519
NOËL and GUY: ♪ Poor little rich girl ♪

2202
01:41:20,603 --> 01:41:24,122
♪ You're a bewitched girl, better take care ♪

2203
01:41:24,206 --> 01:41:26,627
Ooh.

2204
01:41:28,412 --> 01:41:31,964
♪ Laughing at danger, virtue a stranger ♪

2205
01:41:32,048 --> 01:41:34,770
♪ Better beware ♪

2206
01:41:34,854 --> 01:41:36,865
- Shall I join in?
- Yes.

2207
01:41:36,949 --> 01:41:40,710
♪ You're weaving love
into a mad jazz pattern ♪

2208
01:41:40,794 --> 01:41:45,374
♪ Ruled by pantaloon ♪

2209
01:41:47,427 --> 01:41:49,861
♪ Poor little rich girl ♪

2210
01:41:51,137 --> 01:41:57,451
♪ Don't drop a stitch too soon. ♪

2211
01:41:57,535 --> 01:41:59,222
Bravo!

2212
01:41:59,306 --> 01:42:01,522
- Bravo!
- Bravo!

2213
01:42:01,606 --> 01:42:04,216
- Bravo.
- Bravo!

2214
01:42:05,648 --> 01:42:08,133
We should be off, too,
after a really lovely evening.

2215
01:42:08,217 --> 01:42:10,036
But first I want to apologize.

2216
01:42:10,120 --> 01:42:12,205
Apologize, Anne? What for?

2217
01:42:12,289 --> 01:42:14,038
When you first asked, we hung back.

2218
01:42:14,122 --> 01:42:15,571
It was cowardly.

2219
01:42:15,655 --> 01:42:17,738
Convention makes cowards of us all.

2220
01:42:17,822 --> 01:42:20,347
Lady Osborne said her maid told her

2221
01:42:20,431 --> 01:42:23,243
Mr. Coward was coming, but how did she know?

2222
01:42:23,327 --> 01:42:26,187
Our servants always know more
about us than we do about them.

2223
01:42:26,271 --> 01:42:28,584
Mary's overcome her trials, and I'm glad.

2224
01:42:28,668 --> 01:42:31,342
I hope she'll thrive from now on.

2225
01:42:32,807 --> 01:42:35,899
I'm not sure I'm cut out
to be the prodigal daughter.

2226
01:42:35,983 --> 01:42:38,261
I want my virtues to be celebrated,

2227
01:42:38,345 --> 01:42:40,034
not my sins forgiven.

2228
01:42:40,118 --> 01:42:42,287
I should take what you can get.

2229
01:42:44,925 --> 01:42:46,703
You're leaving before the show?

2230
01:42:46,787 --> 01:42:49,107
Yeah. I'll have left
by the time you get home.

2231
01:42:49,191 --> 01:42:50,674
Dinner at Southampton,

2232
01:42:50,758 --> 01:42:53,109
then on board the <i>Leviathan</i> next morning.

2233
01:42:53,193 --> 01:42:55,345
Oh, Harold.

2234
01:42:55,429 --> 01:42:57,345
I hope I haven't let you down.

2235
01:42:57,429 --> 01:42:58,713
Don't be silly.

2236
01:42:58,797 --> 01:43:01,048
I'm the one who's let everyone down.

2237
01:43:01,132 --> 01:43:04,226
You trusted me, and I wasn't
worthy of that trust.

2238
01:43:04,310 --> 01:43:07,731
You're worthy of my love,
and that won't change.

2239
01:43:07,815 --> 01:43:10,800
Wish you weren't so far away.

2240
01:43:10,884 --> 01:43:13,060
Well, perhaps I'll move here.

2241
01:43:13,144 --> 01:43:16,132
I'm sure I'd be more English
than Robert in a trice.

2242
01:43:20,161 --> 01:43:22,479
Let's stay more in touch
in future, and we'll see.

2243
01:43:33,272 --> 01:43:35,990
The theater is a wonderful investment,

2244
01:43:36,074 --> 01:43:37,884
if you like a bit of a gamble.

2245
01:43:37,968 --> 01:43:39,589
Well, what's the name of your new show

2246
01:43:39,673 --> 01:43:41,832
with the-the <i>Titanic</i> and the war?

2247
01:43:41,916 --> 01:43:44,462
I think I'll call it <i>Cavalcade.</i>

2248
01:43:44,546 --> 01:43:48,229
Well, I might try my luck as an angel.

2249
01:43:48,313 --> 01:43:50,768
I'm very glad you found someone
to take over from Mrs. Patmore,

2250
01:43:50,852 --> 01:43:54,139
but isn't the time coming
when we cook for ourselves,

2251
01:43:54,223 --> 01:43:55,678
at least in London?

2252
01:43:55,762 --> 01:43:57,446
Certainly not.

2253
01:43:57,530 --> 01:43:59,447
One day, the 20th century
will catch up with you, Mary,

2254
01:43:59,531 --> 01:44:02,131
and swallow you whole in a single bite. -

2255
01:44:02,168 --> 01:44:04,501
Not if I see it coming.

2256
01:44:05,433 --> 01:44:08,021
Uh, here's a surprise for you.

2257
01:44:08,105 --> 01:44:09,785
I'd like to persuade Cora

2258
01:44:09,869 --> 01:44:11,654
we should invest in Mr. Coward's new play.

2259
01:44:11,738 --> 01:44:13,388
I hope you don't value your shirt.

2260
01:44:13,408 --> 01:44:15,524
Nonsense, Guy.

2261
01:44:15,608 --> 01:44:17,208
Haven't you heard? I'm a genius.

2262
01:44:17,280 --> 01:44:19,093
It's been a productive visit.

2263
01:44:19,177 --> 01:44:21,677
In fact, Lady Mary's given me
an idea for a comedy.

2264
01:44:21,756 --> 01:44:23,471
No, I can't think how.

2265
01:44:23,555 --> 01:44:25,534
It's about a divorced couple
who are still in love,

2266
01:44:25,618 --> 01:44:27,171
but they drive each other mad.

2267
01:44:27,255 --> 01:44:28,702
What do you think?

2268
01:44:28,786 --> 01:44:30,973
I think I'm not still in love,

2269
01:44:31,057 --> 01:44:34,282
and I'm not quite ready
to find divorce hilarious.

2270
01:44:34,366 --> 01:44:36,511
You know, I'm gonna miss
Downton when I go.

2271
01:44:36,595 --> 01:44:38,488
But you love America.

2272
01:44:38,572 --> 01:44:41,884
Oh, yes. And we're always being
told that Europe is yesterday

2273
01:44:41,968 --> 01:44:45,224
and America's tomorrow,
but, uh, I don't know.

2274
01:44:45,308 --> 01:44:46,808
Sometimes I feel like the past

2275
01:44:46,873 --> 01:44:48,730
is a more comfortable place than the future.

2276
01:45:07,562 --> 01:45:09,500
How proud your father would be.

2277
01:45:11,465 --> 01:45:13,857
I hope that's true.

2278
01:45:13,941 --> 01:45:15,983
Shouldn't you be at the show?

2279
01:45:16,067 --> 01:45:19,587
I came to ask my son for luck before I go.

2280
01:45:19,671 --> 01:45:21,359
Can I give you a lift?

2281
01:45:21,443 --> 01:45:23,646
That would be kind. Thank you.

2282
01:45:26,946 --> 01:45:29,102
Mr. Dexter must have been so grateful to you

2283
01:45:29,186 --> 01:45:30,703
for writing the film.

2284
01:45:30,787 --> 01:45:32,567
Well, the best playwright
in the world is nothing

2285
01:45:32,651 --> 01:45:34,108
without good actors.

2286
01:45:34,192 --> 01:45:36,207
I've learned that much at least.

2287
01:45:37,690 --> 01:45:39,175
Here we go.

2288
01:45:39,259 --> 01:45:40,674
Oh, oh.

2289
01:45:40,758 --> 01:45:42,444
Oh.

2290
01:45:47,537 --> 01:45:49,453
Uh...

2291
01:45:49,537 --> 01:45:50,956
Sorry.

2292
01:45:51,040 --> 01:45:52,125
Uh...

2293
01:45:59,650 --> 01:46:01,634
Good afternoon, ladies and gentlemen,

2294
01:46:01,718 --> 01:46:05,439
and welcome to the
Yorkshire County Show, 1930.

2295
01:46:05,523 --> 01:46:08,273
We hope you all have a wonderful afternoon.

2296
01:46:08,357 --> 01:46:09,976
Where have you been?

2297
01:46:16,331 --> 01:46:17,546
Are you all right?

2298
01:46:17,630 --> 01:46:19,789
You look a bit shaken.

2299
01:46:19,873 --> 01:46:21,588
Molesley drove me.

2300
01:46:21,672 --> 01:46:25,086
And on behalf of
our new president, Lady Merton,

2301
01:46:25,170 --> 01:46:27,956
we hope you're all enjoying
the new additions.

2302
01:46:28,040 --> 01:46:32,001
The fairground I see is proving very popular.

2303
01:46:32,085 --> 01:46:33,661
Oh.

2304
01:46:45,566 --> 01:46:48,316
The sheep shearing
demonstration is taking place

2305
01:46:48,359 --> 01:46:51,117
right now at the south end
of the County Show ground

2306
01:46:51,201 --> 01:46:53,616
in the sheep pens.

2307
01:46:59,345 --> 01:47:01,989
Nothing's changed here since 1850.

2308
01:47:02,073 --> 01:47:04,361
Well, you can see women's ankles now.

2309
01:47:06,086 --> 01:47:08,034
That's not much use to us.

2310
01:47:16,855 --> 01:47:18,442
Anna.

2311
01:47:18,526 --> 01:47:19,810
Afternoon.

2312
01:47:19,894 --> 01:47:21,612
Thank you for your help with the dinner.

2313
01:47:21,696 --> 01:47:22,911
It was everyone really, milady.

2314
01:47:22,995 --> 01:47:25,551
Well, then, please thank them all.

2315
01:47:25,635 --> 01:47:27,220
- I most certainly will.
- Good day.

2316
01:47:27,304 --> 01:47:30,358
In the main arena now,

2317
01:47:30,442 --> 01:47:33,062
the judging of the Highland cattle.

2318
01:47:33,146 --> 01:47:35,221
And in the lost children's tent,

2319
01:47:35,305 --> 01:47:37,663
there's a young girl dressed as Guinevere.

2320
01:47:37,747 --> 01:47:40,948
She's too shy to tell us her real name.

2321
01:47:41,887 --> 01:47:43,368
Mm.

2322
01:47:43,452 --> 01:47:44,665
That's you, that is.

2323
01:47:44,749 --> 01:47:45,908
Oh, look.

2324
01:47:45,992 --> 01:47:47,790
Want to pet him?

2325
01:47:49,921 --> 01:47:51,288
He's so lovely.

2326
01:47:52,462 --> 01:47:53,697
Hello, Raffi.

2327
01:47:57,768 --> 01:48:00,216
The main prize giving will take place

2328
01:48:00,300 --> 01:48:05,060
at the end of the show at 4:30
precisely in the marquee.

2329
01:48:05,144 --> 01:48:07,089
Take your seats early.

2330
01:48:07,173 --> 01:48:08,856
- Thank you.
- You have a lovely day.

2331
01:48:08,940 --> 01:48:10,161
Cora.

2332
01:48:10,245 --> 01:48:11,592
Mary.

2333
01:48:11,676 --> 01:48:13,067
Follow me.

2334
01:48:13,151 --> 01:48:14,502
Are you sure?

2335
01:48:14,586 --> 01:48:16,197
Shouldn't I just hover in the shadows?

2336
01:48:16,281 --> 01:48:18,481
- Oh, of course not.
- Lady Merton.

2337
01:48:18,519 --> 01:48:19,777
There you are.

2338
01:48:19,861 --> 01:48:21,378
Lady Grantham.

2339
01:48:21,462 --> 01:48:23,078
And, Lady Mary,
I didn't know you were coming.

2340
01:48:23,162 --> 01:48:24,845
Let me find you a seat.

2341
01:48:24,929 --> 01:48:26,781
Lady Mary is sitting in
the front row with the family.

2342
01:48:26,865 --> 01:48:29,765
- Are you sure? Because you have plenty...
- I'm quite sure.

2343
01:48:31,169 --> 01:48:32,552
Ah, Lord Grantham.

2344
01:48:32,636 --> 01:48:34,353
We have a place reserved for you.

2345
01:48:34,437 --> 01:48:36,016
Ah, how kind, Sir Hector.

2346
01:48:36,100 --> 01:48:38,093
How was your dinner last night?

2347
01:48:38,177 --> 01:48:39,963
Just a supper, really.

2348
01:48:40,047 --> 01:48:41,712
I know all about it.

2349
01:48:44,651 --> 01:48:49,162
Hell hath no fury like a snob scorned.

2350
01:48:49,246 --> 01:48:50,471
Congratulations, Mr. Anderson.

2351
01:48:50,555 --> 01:48:52,355
- Ah.
- Thank you so much. Thank you.

2352
01:48:54,661 --> 01:48:59,224
And now our final prize today
for our Local Hero.

2353
01:49:00,830 --> 01:49:04,618
But first, as a tribute to my predecessor,

2354
01:49:04,702 --> 01:49:08,088
we have renamed this the Violet Grantham Cup.

2355
01:49:10,737 --> 01:49:12,171
When was that decided?

2356
01:49:15,141 --> 01:49:17,793
And I would like to invite
Lady Mary...

2357
01:49:17,877 --> 01:49:19,736
- Ah.
- ...To present it.

2358
01:49:19,820 --> 01:49:20,804
What?

2359
01:49:24,718 --> 01:49:26,810
Quite right! Go on!

2360
01:49:37,500 --> 01:49:39,785
Firstly, I can't explain

2361
01:49:39,869 --> 01:49:43,152
how much your support today means to me.

2362
01:49:43,236 --> 01:49:47,121
But I want you to know
that you are, all of you,

2363
01:49:47,205 --> 01:49:49,648
more important to me than I can say.

2364
01:49:51,577 --> 01:49:55,802
Now, this prize is for someone
who's made a real difference.

2365
01:49:55,886 --> 01:50:00,444
A farmer for 60 years until his retirement.

2366
01:50:00,528 --> 01:50:03,178
It gives me great pleasure to present the cup

2367
01:50:03,262 --> 01:50:05,276
to Mr. Albert Mason.

2368
01:50:05,360 --> 01:50:06,776
Huh?

2369
01:50:06,860 --> 01:50:09,479
Oh. Go, go, go, go, go. Go. Now.

2370
01:50:11,798 --> 01:50:13,903
Oh. Thank you very much.

2371
01:50:16,935 --> 01:50:18,555
Well, thank you.

2372
01:50:18,639 --> 01:50:20,778
Uh, thanks so...

2373
01:50:23,110 --> 01:50:26,069
Thanks to you all for this great honor,

2374
01:50:26,153 --> 01:50:27,897
and thanks to Lady Mary,

2375
01:50:27,981 --> 01:50:30,734
the new mistress of Downton Abbey.

2376
01:50:30,818 --> 01:50:34,042
Like all of us, I wish her well.

2377
01:50:42,933 --> 01:50:47,049
Well, everyone seems very happy, Sir Hector.

2378
01:50:47,133 --> 01:50:48,553
When standards are lowered this far,

2379
01:50:48,637 --> 01:50:49,918
that is usually the case.

2380
01:50:50,002 --> 01:50:52,975
We just had to be patient.

2381
01:51:07,954 --> 01:51:09,940
I'm all but finished, milady.

2382
01:51:10,024 --> 01:51:11,481
Mr. and Mrs. Bates will go ahead,

2383
01:51:11,565 --> 01:51:13,273
and it should all be ready when you arrive.

2384
01:51:13,357 --> 01:51:14,775
You're kind to have allowed this.

2385
01:51:14,859 --> 01:51:16,244
Not really.

2386
01:51:16,328 --> 01:51:18,328
You know Mrs. Bates well, and, of course,

2387
01:51:18,372 --> 01:51:20,721
I'm glad to work for Lady Mary.

2388
01:51:20,805 --> 01:51:22,291
She'll need all the support she can get.

2389
01:51:22,375 --> 01:51:24,292
She'll not be disappointed.

2390
01:51:24,376 --> 01:51:26,227
Not if I can help it.

2391
01:51:26,311 --> 01:51:28,195
Thank you, Baxter.

2392
01:51:33,444 --> 01:51:35,570
So, off we go for our next adventure.

2393
01:51:35,654 --> 01:51:37,464
I'm looking forward to it, milord.

2394
01:51:37,548 --> 01:51:40,440
I'm honored to be doubling
as valet and butler.

2395
01:51:40,524 --> 01:51:41,974
I won't let you down.

2396
01:51:42,058 --> 01:51:44,554
Do you ever think
of where it all began, Bates?

2397
01:51:46,657 --> 01:51:49,549
That day at Tugela Heights,
under General Buller,

2398
01:51:49,633 --> 01:51:51,319
waiting to march on Ladysmith?

2399
01:51:51,403 --> 01:51:52,819
To be honest, milord,

2400
01:51:52,903 --> 01:51:54,490
I didn't think we'd get out of that alive.

2401
01:51:54,574 --> 01:51:55,884
I wouldn't have done without you.

2402
01:51:55,968 --> 01:51:57,952
- I don't know.
- I do.

2403
01:51:58,036 --> 01:52:00,174
I know it very well.

2404
01:52:01,375 --> 01:52:03,975
You took a bullet for me,
and I think about it often.

2405
01:52:07,378 --> 01:52:09,098
I wanted to catch you before you left.

2406
01:52:09,182 --> 01:52:10,834
I was just coming up to say goodbye.

2407
01:52:10,918 --> 01:52:12,234
We'll see a lot of each other,

2408
01:52:12,318 --> 01:52:14,906
even if your new duties keep you busy.

2409
01:52:14,990 --> 01:52:16,911
I'll look forward to that, milady.

2410
01:52:16,995 --> 01:52:21,184
But... I do have one thing
I'd like to ask, if I may.

2411
01:52:21,268 --> 01:52:23,560
Of course. What is it?

2412
01:52:24,931 --> 01:52:27,590
When the baby's born,

2413
01:52:27,674 --> 01:52:31,106
might you consider being the godmother?

2414
01:52:32,741 --> 01:52:34,571
I should be honored.

2415
01:52:38,013 --> 01:52:40,167
That means so much to me, milady.

2416
01:52:40,251 --> 01:52:42,131
So much.

2417
01:52:42,215 --> 01:52:44,207
Now, I think I've told
Miss Baxter

2418
01:52:44,291 --> 01:52:45,808
all she needs to know.

2419
01:52:45,892 --> 01:52:49,706
I'm sure you have,
but I'll still depend on you.

2420
01:52:49,790 --> 01:52:51,648
You know that.

2421
01:52:51,732 --> 01:52:54,382
I think we all depend on each other, milady.

2422
01:52:54,466 --> 01:52:56,164
The way people should.

2423
01:53:17,485 --> 01:53:20,235
We'll just say goodbye
to Robert and Cora and Mary,

2424
01:53:20,294 --> 01:53:21,640
and then we'll be off.

2425
01:53:21,724 --> 01:53:23,845
Ah. I'll say goodbye now.

2426
01:53:23,929 --> 01:53:25,876
I promised Lucy we wouldn't be back too late.

2427
01:53:25,960 --> 01:53:27,711
You've been so helpful, Tom.

2428
01:53:27,795 --> 01:53:29,179
With all of it.

2429
01:53:29,263 --> 01:53:31,847
You know I'll never be off the telephone,

2430
01:53:31,931 --> 01:53:33,690
asking advice.

2431
01:53:33,774 --> 01:53:35,524
I doubt I can offer much
you don't know already,

2432
01:53:35,608 --> 01:53:37,690
but I'll always be happy to help.

2433
01:53:37,774 --> 01:53:39,735
Goodbye, darling.

2434
01:53:41,944 --> 01:53:43,816
Sybil would be so proud of you.

2435
01:53:46,144 --> 01:53:47,598
Goodbye, Aunt Mary.

2436
01:53:47,682 --> 01:53:49,349
Dear Sybbie.

2437
01:53:51,854 --> 01:53:53,837
I had good news in the post.

2438
01:53:53,921 --> 01:53:55,675
Good news for you anyway.

2439
01:53:55,759 --> 01:53:57,405
An offer on Grantham House.

2440
01:53:57,489 --> 01:53:59,611
I didn't know things had gone that far.

2441
01:53:59,695 --> 01:54:00,908
You were right.

2442
01:54:00,992 --> 01:54:02,618
It was time.

2443
01:54:02,702 --> 01:54:04,254
We should go.
They're all waiting.

2444
01:54:04,338 --> 01:54:06,554
We've decided to walk.

2445
01:54:06,638 --> 01:54:08,698
Come along, George.

2446
01:54:13,204 --> 01:54:14,923
Goodness. Thank you.

2447
01:54:15,007 --> 01:54:16,431
Like the old days.

2448
01:54:18,017 --> 01:54:20,095
The kitchen staff weren't
included in the old days.

2449
01:54:20,179 --> 01:54:21,769
That was then, this is now.

2450
01:54:21,853 --> 01:54:24,370
I'm glad to see you,
Mrs. Patmore.

2451
01:54:24,454 --> 01:54:27,573
I heard you were going, milady,
and I-I wanted to say goodbye.

2452
01:54:27,657 --> 01:54:29,274
Thank you, milady.

2453
01:54:29,358 --> 01:54:31,908
Please thank Mr. Mason
for what he said at the show.

2454
01:54:31,991 --> 01:54:33,327
I will, milady.

2455
01:54:34,464 --> 01:54:35,527
Ooh.

2456
01:54:38,369 --> 01:54:39,782
Mm.

2457
01:54:42,404 --> 01:54:44,657
It was very kind of His
Lordship to lend us the car.

2458
01:54:44,741 --> 01:54:46,991
I think you've earned it.

2459
01:54:47,075 --> 01:54:48,388
And my plan was to swing

2460
01:54:48,472 --> 01:54:50,344
through that window up there...

2461
01:54:53,380 --> 01:54:55,162
Would you like a visit to the Dower House

2462
01:54:55,246 --> 01:54:56,529
to help you settle in?

2463
01:54:56,613 --> 01:54:58,682
Give us a few days, and we'd love it.

2464
01:55:01,890 --> 01:55:03,306
Off they go.

2465
01:55:03,390 --> 01:55:05,854
Yes.
We really must be going, too.

2466
01:55:08,862 --> 01:55:09,980
You ready?

2467
01:55:10,064 --> 01:55:11,904
I am.

2468
01:55:27,950 --> 01:55:29,922
Right. Back to work.

2469
01:55:38,289 --> 01:55:40,031
Mr. Carson.

2470
01:55:46,570 --> 01:55:48,072
Thank you.

2471
01:55:52,779 --> 01:55:55,164
Please say you're not sorry to leave.

2472
01:55:55,248 --> 01:55:57,026
I'm not.

2473
01:55:57,110 --> 01:55:58,767
We've done our duty.

2474
01:55:58,851 --> 01:56:01,662
I've given half my life to Downton,

2475
01:56:01,746 --> 01:56:05,403
and I'm glad I have some left to give to you.

2476
01:56:05,487 --> 01:56:08,236
I think we'll be happy
living in the Dower House.

2477
01:56:08,320 --> 01:56:10,743
Sharing it with Mama's ghost.

2478
01:56:10,827 --> 01:56:12,648
She's part of our story.

2479
01:56:12,732 --> 01:56:15,714
And it's all part of our story.

2480
01:56:15,798 --> 01:56:17,984
And I love you.

2481
01:56:18,068 --> 01:56:20,553
That's what makes it all worthwhile.

2482
01:56:28,574 --> 01:56:30,939
Give my love to your brother.

2483
01:56:32,311 --> 01:56:33,436
Are you sure you won't stay?

2484
01:56:33,520 --> 01:56:34,735
We ought to get going.

2485
01:56:34,819 --> 01:56:37,403
And I'm eager to see Peter.

2486
01:56:37,487 --> 01:56:40,190
And you're pleased with the way
things have worked out?

2487
01:56:41,821 --> 01:56:44,777
Every time a place like this
passes to the next generation,

2488
01:56:44,861 --> 01:56:46,955
it's a victory in itself.

2489
01:56:54,167 --> 01:56:56,074
Long live Downton Abbey.

2490
01:56:58,203 --> 01:56:59,968
Amen to that.

2491
01:59:37,496 --> 01:59:43,224
♪ I'll see you again ♪

2492
01:59:43,308 --> 01:59:49,459
♪ Whenever spring breaks through again ♪

2493
01:59:49,543 --> 01:59:55,298
♪ Time may lie heavy between ♪

2494
01:59:55,382 --> 01:59:58,367
♪ But what has been ♪

2495
01:59:58,451 --> 02:00:04,538
♪ Can leave me never ♪

2496
02:00:04,622 --> 02:00:09,777
♪ Your dear memory ♪

2497
02:00:09,861 --> 02:00:16,453
♪ Throughout my life will come to me ♪

2498
02:00:16,537 --> 02:00:21,889
♪ Though my world has gone awry ♪

2499
02:00:21,973 --> 02:00:27,937
♪ Though the years my tears may dry ♪

2500
02:00:28,021 --> 02:00:34,269
♪ I shall love you till I die ♪

2501
02:00:34,353 --> 02:00:41,275
♪ Goodbye. ♪

